   <text:p text:style-name="P12">Getting Over Madeleine</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Subtitle">A love story by T. M. Jarman</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:word-count>63418</text:word-count><text:bookmark text:name="_GoBack"/> words</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P1">Copyright <text:span text:style-name="T3">©</text:span> 2011 T. M. Jarman. All rights reserved.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">Dedication</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para">For Ethel and her mother, who inspired this book; and for Nicky, who inspires my life.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">1</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Chapter_20_subheading">London, 1995</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">It began at seven o&apos;clock sharp when the alarm clock on the bedside erupted into hooting life. Three hoots later it was silenced by a pale and clouting hand from beneath the duvet.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">At seven-fifteen the alarm clock on the windowsill began to chirrup. There was a grunt, more arm, groping, silence.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">At seven-thirty, the one on the chest of drawers chimed in and Jane finally hauled herself out of bed, lurched across the room and shut it off. It was just about daylight. She pulled back one curtain and squinted cautiously out through the streaming condensation into the grey morning. It might have been raining. Steaming cars were queuing up at the traffic lights behind three crammed and misted buses. There was no denying it: it was Monday.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Turning, she caught sight of herself in the mirror, winced, and made for the bathroom, hugging a bathrobe round herself for warmth. It was going to be a long day.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P11">Jane and two other girls occupied the first floor of a large and presumably once desirable house <text:s/>in the centre of Camden. Donna was the friend of a friend; Sue was the result of a postcard in a newsagent&apos;s window. The rent included a fridge that should have been in a museum, a temperamental and sometimes terrifying gas cooker, and a selection of Bakelite electrical fittings connected together in ways which Jane was too nervous to investigate. There was also a small lounge, mostly occupied by a decrepit three-piece suite and what might have been one of John Logie Baird&apos;s early TV sets which needed to be fed 50p pieces at intervals. Luxury it was not, but you could live there.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P11"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Her room was the largest, but it was also at the front so you got the noise of the traffic. After a while this had ceased to bother her. What was more of an issue at this time of year was the draughtiness of the ancient sash windows which, combined with its cavernous height, made the room impossible to heat. The translucent blue curtains used to billow in the slightest breeze. There was a night storage heater directly under the window, which may have technically made some slight difference to the average temperature of Camden as a whole but never had much impact on the room itself. It was a pleasant enough room apart from that, so long as you didn&apos;t pay too much attention to the frayed carpet or the peeling pink wallpaper or the slowly disintegrating ceiling which was starting to resemble a map of the Amazon basin. At least it was furnished. She even had a double bed, not that she got much practical advantage from it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">By the time she reached the bus-stop it was definitely raining, a fine determined rain that was going to last for years. Her glasses fogged up on the bus. She wanted a cigarette but the New Year&apos;s resolutions were still holding up somehow. Well, that one was anyway. The </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">hangover wasn&apos;t too bad considering, and she managed not to throw up over the man next to her as the bus jerked and jolted its way across London. She wasn&apos;t even all that late, for a Monday.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P11"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane worked in one of the several London offices of a large multinational which liked to describe itself as a “solutions provider.” What this amounted to was sending an army of plausible men in expensive suits to the corporate headquarters of other large companies in order to persuade those companies to pay for an even larger army of much younger men in cheaper suits to write computer software. This was supposed to solve some problem or other, the exact details of which always seemed to be rather vague. As part of the package, the lucky client would be provided with several stout ring-binders crammed with unhelpful verbiage. Jane&apos;s part in all this, together with another small army of staff, was to create this so-called “User Documentation.” She hoped devoutly that no actual user of the software was ever required to peruse the stuff. Even the small parts of it written in comprehensible English were usually out of date or just plain wrong. Luckily the authorship of these documents was strictly anonymous, so there was little chance of some crazed corporate peon exacting a dreadful revenge. But had one ever done so, Jane would have had to acknowledge the justice of it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P11"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">The worst thing about the job, apart from the inescapable fact that she was expected <text:s/>to turn up and actually do it five days a week, was that nearly all of her family, friends and acquaintances were convinced that because she worked for a software company she somehow knew everything there was to know about computers, and in particular how to fix theirs whenever it had gone wrong. Her brother was the one oasis of sanity in this regard, which was unusual for him as he was generally assumed by his loved ones to be a borderline lunatic.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P11"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">The office she worked in had been newly built when she had first started there two years before, but even then it had already had an essential and eternal drabness about it. There were grey nylon carpet tiles on the floor, and a similar arrangement on the ceiling relieved only by florescent lights at intervals. The large windows were uniformly obscured by grey plastic vertical blinds. The identical desks were of pine, as were the identical sets of drawers; each had an identical dark brown telephone (although hers had never once rung), an identical grey computer, <text:s/>and an identical plastic revolving office chair. Essentially, everything you could see was either grey, beige, or some shade between the two so nondescript it had no known name. The desks were arranged in islands at regular intervals with a rubber-plant beside every third island. When she looked across the room Jane sometimes thought she could discern the curvature of the Earth. Of course, it was sometimes just that she&apos;d been drinking.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane hated the coffee out of the machine but it was slightly less disgusting than the tea. She had extra sugar, or at least she pressed the button for it but there was no discernible difference. Fortunately in the post-Christmas lull there wasn&apos;t too much to do. More coffee. Staring vacantly at the computer screen trying to look alert and intelligent. A limp white roll stuffed with even limper salad, prawn cocktail squirting out onto her lapel, hey it&apos;s lunchtime, </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">only another four hours to go. The headache eased eventually. She could have taken paracetamol, she kept some in her desk, but she&apos;d read something in a magazine about how it could damage your liver and was trying to cut down on her intake. She bought a bottle of mineral water and drank it very slowly. It got darker outside. It was still raining, pattering listlessly against the windows.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Fancy a drink?&quot; That was Marcie, the dark little Welsh girl at the next desk.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Why not?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">There was a pub they always went to on these occasions, one of those thoroughly kippered Victorian pubs with an elaborate plaster ceiling and lots of glossy dark wood that could have been mahogany but almost certainly wasn&apos;t. In the week it was generally quiet, and you could talk if you had a mind to. Marcie bought the first round: white wine and soda for Jane, rum and Coke for herself. They didn&apos;t usually go for a drink after work unless it was Friday – well, usually at least Wednesday - and especially not with a week still to go until pay-day. Jane made the obvious deduction.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Man trouble?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Marcie made a face. &quot;Any other sort?&quot; She took a long sip of her drink. &quot;Paul and me split up at the weekend.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;What, again?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Oh, he&apos;s not serious. Usual bollocks about commitment and wanting to find himself. I told him, if he wanted to find himself he should look in the bloody phone book.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Under T for tosser.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Marcie shrugged. &quot;He&apos;s not that bad.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">That didn&apos;t sound to Jane like much of an endorsement of the man who had been The One a few months back, but she let it go.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;How long do you give him before he comes crawling back?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"><text:s/>&quot;Friday.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;No, he&apos;ll be out on the pull Friday. When he doesn&apos;t, he&apos;ll be on the phone Saturday.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Jane Sharp, you&apos;re a bitter and cynical woman.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Not cynical. Just single.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;And bitter. And it&apos;s your birthday next week.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane was immediately on the defensive. &quot;So? Twenty-five isn&apos;t </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T7">old.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T7"><text:s/></text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Older than me,&quot; Marcie said complacently.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Are you saying I’m on the shelf? Jesus Christ, you&apos;re worse than my mother.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Only kidding.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">There was a small silence between them. &quot;Fancy another?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Marcie looked at her watch. &quot;I shouldn&apos;t really.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"><text:s/>&quot;Never stopped you before.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Same again then.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">When Jane returned from the bar there was a gleeful look on her friend&apos;s face that she knew of old. It usually meant trouble of one sort or another. Accepting the inevitable, she said:</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;What?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Behind you. Those two blokes at the corner table.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;What about them?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;The tall one fancies you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;You know a lot about it.&quot; Jane pulled open a packet of crisps and laid it on the table between them.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I can always tell.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;m not even going to look.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;He&apos;s not bad. The other one&apos;s all right as well.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Stop looking at them. You&apos;ll give them ideas.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Why not?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane thought: </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">I&apos;m knackered, it&apos;s only Monday, there&apos;s prawn cocktail halfway down my blouse, and I&apos;ve got enough problems in my life already.</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"> She said: &quot;I suppose.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">There was a spotty mirror on the wall in front of her advertising some long defunct brand of whisky. Jane saw in reflection the two men getting up, hesitating. She saw Marcie shift position slightly in her chair. It was inevitable. Marcie was smiling, damn her.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Mind if we join you?&quot; said the shorter man. He was fair-haired, stocky, pleasantly-spoken and eminently forgettable.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;It&apos;s a free country,&quot; said Marcie.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Stools were dragged across, there were introductions. The fair-haired man said his name was Tom. The other man still hadn&apos;t spoken. He was tall and gangly with untidy dark hair and the air of being about to ask for directions to wherever else he ought to be instead of here.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Haven&apos;t seen you in here before,&quot; said Tom.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;We come in now and then after work. Work together, see.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;What do you do then?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Small talk. The likelihood was that it would get smaller. Jane was drinking too fast so as to pre-empt the boredom; she&apos;d skipped breakfast as usual, and one prawn cocktail roll wouldn&apos;t go far to soak up the alcohol. She became aware that her silent companion was staring at her, or possibly at something a little way behind her. His eyes were intensely blue. Some sort of conversational gambit seemed inevitable.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;What&apos;s the matter, have I got two heads?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;We&apos;ve been here before,&quot; he said. It sounded odd. He had a beautiful voice, but she didn&apos;t care for his line in dialogue.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Often come in here myself, &quot;Jane rejoined briskly. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;No. I mean you and me. We&apos;ve done this before.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Don&apos;t think so.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I had a dream.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">Oh God, we&apos;ve got one here</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">. &quot;Funny that, you don&apos;t look like Martin Luther King.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He seemed to come to. &quot;Sorry, I didn&apos;t mean to come over weird. I just had one of those moments, you know. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T13">Déjà vu</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T7">. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Like I remembered having been here before, like this.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Do you remember what happened next?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He looked down. &quot;Sorry, I&apos;m making a prat of myself.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Yes.&quot; Jane ate the last crisp. &quot;But you could always buy me a drink to make up for it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Seven o&apos;clock the next morning: the alarm clock on the bedside table heralded the same gruesome ritual.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I can&apos;t believe we did that,&quot; Jane said to Marcie as they shared her paracetamol.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Just a drink and a friendly chat, nothing heavy.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;That Tom was all over you. Looked heavy to me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I can look after myself.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;ve noticed.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">In a moment of optimism, Jane had opted for tea. It was still just as awful as the last time she&apos;d tried it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;And you and Nigel seemed to be getting on all right.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane shuddered. &quot;God, I could never go out with someone called Nigel. I mean, can you imagine, in the throes of passion, calling out &apos;Nigel, Nigel&apos;?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Don&apos;t knock it till you&apos;ve tried it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Don&apos;t tell me, I don&apos;t want to know.&quot; Jane had too often been favoured with Marcie&apos;s intimate reminiscences. &quot;And anyway, his name&apos;s Michael.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Must have misheard.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Yes, you and Tom were too wrapped up in each other to notice.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;m a single girl,&quot; Marcie said defensively. &quot;No harm in that, is there?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Wait until Saturday.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Friday.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Fiver on it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;You&apos;re on.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">On principle, Jane never answered the phone in her flat: it was never for her, unless it was her mother. Sometimes her flatmates would give her an alibi, if she was feeling particularly down. So when it rang that evening she didn&apos;t even look up from stirring her noodles.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;It&apos;s for you,&quot; said Donna gaily, putting her head round the door. Donna always sounded chirpy: it was the New Zealand accent that did it. Usually Jane only found it unbearable in the mornings, but she found herself ready to make an exception.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Shit.&quot; Jane took the saucepan off the gas and went out into the dingy little hallway. Then she caught Donna&apos;s quizzical eye. Not her mother, then. She took the receiver.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Yes?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;It&apos;s Michael.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Michael who? Not her brother Michael, wrong voice. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T10">Or did I give my number to that guy? Oh, Christ. I did, didn&apos;t I?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Are you still there?&quot; the voice in her ear said. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I was wondering.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Yes?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Are you busy at the weekend?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Why?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Well, I was wondering,&quot; he said again. &quot;Do you like Chinese food?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Sometimes.&quot; She thought longingly of the noodles on the stove; she was starving.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Would you like to go out for a meal? You know, a Chinese meal. Maybe at the weekend. If you&apos;re not busy.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;All right.&quot; Well, why not?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;That&apos;s great.&quot; He sounded surprised. &quot;Saturday okay?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Saturday&apos;s fine.&quot; Saturday was usually fine.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He explained about the restaurant, which was a new one. Jane had passed it on the bus. They arranged a time and a place to meet. She put the phone down. She was in mild shock.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Donna was in the kitchen eating rice-cakes. She never seemed to eat anything else; no wonder she looked like an Oxfam poster. This time she was having them with Vegemite. Jane had tried one once and would rather have eaten table-mats.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Anyone I know?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Just a bloke.&quot; Jane re-heated the noodles; they were almost cooked.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Sue came into the kitchen, laden with groceries and gossip. She&apos;d only been living there a couple of months but it already seemed like a lifetime. If they hadn&apos;t been in such a hurry to find someone, Donna and Jane might well have thought better of Sue. She was certainly very domesticated and almost obsessively tidy; considered as someone prepared to clean the oven she was an undoubted success. It was just that she never shut up. Even as she walked into the room she was already narrating the minutiae of her trip to Budgen&apos;s.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">This evening, though, Jane was almost grateful. Given a clear field, Donna would have grilled her mercilessly. The flow of superfluous information about two-for-one offers </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">rolled over them like a healing tide, and Jane was able to eat her noodles, if not in peace, at least in safety.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Although it was eight o&apos;clock, there was only one other couple in the restaurant. Jane felt very exposed. She hadn&apos;t enlarged on her explanation to Donna, in spite of her permanently raised eyebrows. She hadn&apos;t even mentioned it to Marcie. Now she was here she felt desperately shy. Michael wasn&apos;t helping either: he kept looking at her.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">She tried making conversation but it was uphill work. When she asked what he did for a living he said that he had an aunt.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I didn&apos;t know that was a career choice,&quot; she said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Well, it isn&apos;t, I suppose. But I had this dotty aunt, very sweet but well to the right of Genghis Khan. When she died last year we all thought she&apos;d leave her money to my cousin Jeremy but it turned out that she didn&apos;t approve of him having a Jewish girlfriend and she&apos;d left it all to me. It&apos;s not a lot but it pays the rent.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">This long speech apparently exhausted his conversational resources. They ordered too much food which neither of them felt like eating. The twangy Chinese music was getting on her nerves. Jane couldn&apos;t think of anything to say and he just kept looking at her. It was like a nightmare.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Thank you,&quot; he said eventually.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;What for?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Coming out. You know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I wasn&apos;t doing anything.&quot; </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">I wish to God I had been</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">, she thought.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I was surprised. I thought you&apos;d be busy.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Why?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Girl like you. Saturday night.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane tried to interest herself in a spring roll, without success. &quot;I don&apos;t go out much, really.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Would you like to?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Like to what?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;You know. Go out. More. With me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane thought of her dreary flat and the dross on television. &quot;Maybe.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Are you going to eat that?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;m not hungry.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Neither am I. Shall we go and get a drink somewhere?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Why not?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He was very awkward in the street, not knowing how to be next to her, all elbows and nervous glances.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;m not after anything serious,&quot; she said suddenly. &quot;I don&apos;t really do relationships.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Oh.&quot; He seemed disappointed. This surprised her.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;What were you expecting?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I don&apos;t know,&quot; he said miserably.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;So you didn&apos;t dream this bit, then.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;m sorry about that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Don&apos;t worry about it. Water under the bridge.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">The first pub they came to was too big and loud and crowded, so they turned up a side-street and found an Irish bar — the real thing, not some faked-up chain outlet. Jane was the only woman in the place apart from the barmaid. Heads turned.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;What would you like?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Pint of Guinness,&quot; she said brazenly. She&apos;d probably never set foot here again anyway.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He had the same and they sat in a corner feeling very watched. &quot;Do you often drink pints?&quot; he asked.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Never. Cheers.&quot; They drank. She hadn&apos;t had Guinness before and wasn&apos;t sure if she liked the taste. It felt very cold sliding down inside her. On the plus side, it definitely contained alcohol.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Why are you so interested in me?&quot; she demanded.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He looked down. &quot;You remind me of someone.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Let me guess: Michelle Pfeiffer.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Don&apos;t make fun of me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;All right. Only kidding.&quot; She looked him over. If he calmed down he wouldn&apos;t be so bad really. Jane had learned to be guarded in her responses to the opposite sex: it didn&apos;t do to set her sights too high. At least he wasn&apos;t completely insensitive. And he&apos;d paid for the dinner, such as it was.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;It&apos;s my birthday on Wednesday,&quot; she said conversationally.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Is it?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Guess how old I am.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;You&apos;ll be twenty-five,&quot; he said without a moment&apos;s hesitation, as if he&apos;d known the answer as a matter of course. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Good guess.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I wasn&apos;t guessing,&quot; he said. &quot;Not exactly.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;You knew?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He nodded. &quot;It was a bit like the other night. You know, a dream.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Do you often dream things that are going to happen?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Sometimes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;How are you on racing results?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He smiled wanly. &quot;Nothing yet.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Can&apos;t win &apos;em all.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;d like to take you home with me,&quot; he said quietly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane almost choked. &quot;On the first, date? You don&apos;t hang about, do you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"><text:s/>&quot;Christ, I&apos;m sorry, I don&apos;t know what came over me. I never meant to say that. I&apos;m sorry.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Don&apos;t mention it. A girl likes to feel wanted, you know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;m sorry,&quot; he said again.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"><text:s/>&quot;Did you dream that as well?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He was blushing. She liked that. She&apos;d never been out with a man who blushed.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;It&apos;s all right,&quot; she said. &quot;You&apos;re forgiven.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He didn&apos;t take her home with him that night but she did let him kiss her at the bus station. He was a lot taller than her but it didn&apos;t seem at all awkward. It felt surprisingly good and she wasn&apos;t even all that drunk.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">The next day he called her again.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;ve been thinking about you,&quot; he said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Nice thoughts, I hope.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Very nice thoughts.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Down, boy.&quot; She was enjoying this.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;What are you doing for your birthday?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Cream cakes for all the girls at the office, down the pub after work and a God-awful hangover the next day, as per usual. &quot;Nothing much.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Could I see you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"><text:s/>&quot;Maybe.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Buy you dinner?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Not Chinese.&quot; Jane didn&apos;t think she could ever face a spring roll again.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"><text:s/>&quot;French?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I never know what I&apos;m ordering in a French restaurant.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;ll order.&quot; He sounded very confident.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;You speak French?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Degree in modern languages. French and Spanish.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">She was impressed. &quot;All right then.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;ll book us a table then. Shall I pick you up?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"><text:s/>Jane thought of Donna&apos;s eyebrows. &quot;No, I&apos;ll meet you there.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Okay. I&apos;ll give you a ring when I&apos;ve confirmed the booking.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Great.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">When she went back into the sitting-room her flatmates abruptly fell silent. She felt herself blushing and was immediately furious with herself. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Looks like rain again,&quot; Donna said. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Have you two been talking about me?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Do I look like that kind of girl?&quot; said Sue archly. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Don&apos;t be so uptight. Here, you couldn&apos;t lend me a pair of tights, could you? &quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">“No.&quot; Jane went off to her own room, unreasonably angry.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">When she got into work on Monday there was a five-pound note stuck to her screen with Blu-Tak.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Back together then?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Marcie smiled contentedly. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I made him confess everything first.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Was I right?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;In every detail. On his own admission he propositioned no less than four different women. Still had the hangover at three the next afternoon.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;So he managed to find himself in the end, then.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;State he was in I&apos;m surprised he could find a taxi.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Serves him right.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Bless.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T31">2</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Wednesday morning: many happy returns from Sue and Donna on the kitchen table. For once, Jane had actually managed to get up in time to grab some breakfast. She was feeling nervous.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Bus. Office. Indecent birthday card from Marcie on her desk. Coffee. Still awful, but not as bad as the tea. Deep breath.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Marcie.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Yes, love?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I won&apos;t be coming to the pub tonight.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Oho. Got a better offer, have we?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Don&apos;t get excited.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Anyone I know?&quot; Marcie grinned. &quot;It&apos;s that bloke, isn&apos;t it?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Keep your voice down —&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Soul of discretion, me.&quot; She leaned over confidentially. &quot;Fast worker, I&apos;ll give him that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Not that fast.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Playing hard to get?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Him or me?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Either.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Look, it isn&apos;t serious.&quot; Jane could feel herself going pink, first with embarrassment and then with fury.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Keep your wig on, love. But if you go down with a mystery virus tomorrow morning, you know what </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">I’ll</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"> be thinking.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Don&apos;t you dare —&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;My lips are sealed.&quot; Marcie smiled angelically. That was always a bad sign.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Back at the flat, more birthday cards: her parents, her brother, a couple of old college friends, and one whose spiky writing she didn&apos;t recognise but could immediately identify. Michael. She was sure she&apos;d never given him this address. What was he, a mind-reader? Detective? Serial killer? The wording was conventional enough, and his name was followed by a single </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">kiss: fair enough, they&apos;d shared one. Jane wasn&apos;t sure that she wanted to share another. This was getting a bit too weird.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">She stood all the other cards on the mantelpiece in the sitting-room. Nobody passed any comment. She knew they&apos;d both noticed.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">There wasn&apos;t much time to change and she couldn&apos;t decide what to wear, not that she had that much to choose from. She&apos;d only got as far as underwear when the phone rang. It was her mother.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Happy birthday, darling. I didn&apos;t expect to catch you in.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Yes, well, just getting ready to go out actually.&quot; A mistake.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Oh, going anywhere special?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Just a meal. You know. With a friend.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Anyone we know?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;No.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Oh. Well, I won&apos;t keep you.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Thanks for the card. I&apos;ve got to run.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Goodbye then, darling. Have a lovely evening.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane was furious with herself, as she often was after a conversation with her mother. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">Why didn&apos;t I just lie?</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"> she thought. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">I&apos;ll never hear the end of this, never.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">She chose a black dress which made her look fat but was not quite as hideous as the alternative. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">I need to lose at least a stone</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">, she thought. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">Two. And this is too short. He&apos;ll think I&apos;m a tart and I&apos;ll probably freeze to death. But I don&apos;t have any shoes to go with the pink one, or not shoes I can walk in. Why am I doing this? Hell and damnation, it can&apos;t be that late already. It&apos;ll have to do.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">This had better be a bloody good meal.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">She was late, of course. At first she couldn&apos;t find him, and then with a shock realised that the assured young man in a dinner-jacket waving to her was Michael. He didn&apos;t seem out of place at all. She wondered if he was a regular here. It was all rather disturbing; he hadn&apos;t been like this.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Happy birthday.&quot; She let him kiss her cheek. &quot;Did you get my card?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;How did you know the address?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;You told me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I never did.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Didn&apos;t you?&quot; He was overdoing the surprise. She didn&apos;t like this.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Have you been following me?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He shrugged. &quot;My spies are everywhere.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Don&apos;t piss me about, Michael. This is freaking me out.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Someone told me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Who?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Nobody you know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Michael, this isn&apos;t funny. Tell me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He looked down, away. The familiar awkwardness reassured her a little. &quot;There are some things about me that are hard to explain.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Too right.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Do you believe in angels?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane sat back in her chair. &quot;Are you pissed or something?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Look, I know it sounds weird.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;No kidding.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I get — told things.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Like in your dreams?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Sort of. More specific. Oh God, how can I explain this? When I first saw you — well, it was like a memory, as if I was living it again.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;You said: I&apos;ve been here before.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Yes. But although I knew you, I didn&apos;t know anything </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T7">about </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">you. I knew you were, would be, someone important to me, but I didn&apos;t know your name or your profession or anything like that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;And that&apos;s where the angels come into it?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;It&apos;s hard to explain,&quot; he said again.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane looked at him, hard. &quot;Are you for real?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I don&apos;t understand it myself. It&apos;s not something I can control.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Pity. Might be useful.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Any predictions as to what we&apos;re going to eat?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He ordered for both of them. It seemed to be an awful lot. Apparently the aunt had done him pretty well. Jane harboured secret misgivings about the capacity of her stomach, and indeed her dress. When the food arrived, however, it was so good that she forgot her worries and ate like a wolf. They drank a good deal of wine, but they went steadily and were left in the end with coffee, cognac and a deep glow of inner well-being. Jane was quite mollified.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;That was fabulous. Thank you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;My pleasure.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">There was a small contented pause. Jane glanced at her watch.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Christ, it&apos;s gone midnight.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Don&apos;t rush off.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Got to go to work tomorrow.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Call in sick.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I shouldn&apos;t.&quot; This was certainly true. But it seemed a shame to cut the evening short.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Come back for a nightcap,&quot; he said. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Is this an attempt on my virtue?&quot; &quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Would you like it to be?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">She smiled. &quot;Ask the angels.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para">On Thursday morning she called in sick. By the grace of God, it wasn’t Marcie who took the call.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">The worst thing about Friday morning was that Marcie said absolutely nothing. Jane felt as if she were sitting at her desk stark naked.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Coffee. No sugar, in the hope of miraculous weight loss; no more or less disgusting than usual.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Marcie, you haven&apos;t said anything, have you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Me? Discretion is my middle name.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;No it&apos;s not, it&apos;s Gwendolen. You told me that on the Friday night of the first week I worked here, just before you threw up.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I never breathed a word, I swear.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"><text:s/>&quot;Good.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;So how was he, then?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">How was he? He was a revelation.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane had had lovers: not many, but enough to make comparisons. She had always been made to feel slightly inadequate in bed and this had exaggerated her natural shyness to a point where she had almost convinced herself that she was no longer interested in sex. It had been over a year since her last experience, which had been a less than successful and very drunken encounter with an ex-boyfriend at a party given by mutual friends. She hadn&apos;t desired Michael. It was more that the wanted to thank him for a wonderful meal by giving him something he appeared to want.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He shared a flat with a friend who happened to be away. It wasn&apos;t much bigger than her own place but somewhat more up-market. She didn&apos;t really take much in, since they processed more or less directly to his bedroom.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">She had no memory of undressing, although undressing certainly took place. What she remembered was the way he touched her. He seemed to have a complete understanding of her body. It wasn&apos;t something she could ever express to herself in words or even images. The closest thing to it was music. She stopped being herself. She stopped thinking of him as someone separate. She stopped thinking altogether and simply experienced. It didn&apos;t seem to have a beginning, a middle or an end. She quickly lost track of what he was doing to her; he did what she wanted and she wanted what he did. It was unearthly, dreamlike.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">At some point normality resumed and they resolved themselves into two hot and rather sweaty bodies curled together like lettuce-leaves.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Thank you,&quot; he said softly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;The pleasure was mine.&quot; She disentangled herself slightly. &quot;God, that was fantastic. You were fantastic.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"><text:s/>&quot;We were fantastic.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;That as well.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Will you stay?&quot; he murmured.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I don&apos;t think I could walk if 1 wanted to.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Good.&quot; He kissed the back of her neck, making her shiver.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Don&apos;t start me off again. I&apos;ll die.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I wouldn&apos;t want that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">There was a long, drowsy pause.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Michael.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Mm?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;It&apos;s never been like that before. Not ever.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Well into their second drink of Friday evening, Jane found courage to venture the question.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Marcie. What was the best sex you ever had?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Marcie pondered. &quot;I don&apos;t know. It&apos;s all pretty much the same, isn&apos;t it?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I used to think so.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">A knowing smile. &quot;Had a good time with Nigel, then?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Michael.&quot; Jane took a swallow of wine. &quot;I wouldn&apos;t call it a good time exactly.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Make your mind up, girl. Hot or not?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;It was different, that&apos;s all.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Here, he&apos;s not into anything kinky, is he?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;No, not like that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Well, then?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I don&apos;t know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Thought he might be a bit weird. It&apos;s the quiet ones you want to watch, I always say so.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane finished her drink. &quot;Your round.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">While Marcie was at the bar Jane&apos;s mobile rang, which was unusual. Indeed it was only ever her mother who called it – Jane suspected she was checking that she had it with her, because it had been her mother&apos;s idea to get it and Jane hated the thing. It was supposed to be </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">useful in an emergency, such as being attacked in an alley (Jane&apos;s mother supposed Camden to be a hotbed of violent crime). If she ever had been attacked in an alley, Jane thought her best bet was to whack her assailant over the head with the wretched object. It was certainly heavy enough to inflict some damage.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">It was Michael.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;How did you this my number? — No, don&apos;t tell me, let me guess.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He was apologetic, which at least seemed to be normal for him. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Is it a bad time to call?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;No, it&apos;s fine.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I just wanted to hear your voice.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Well, you&apos;ve heard it.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Can I see you tomorrow?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I suppose. If you like.&quot; Marcie was coming back with the drinks. &quot;Look, I&apos;d better go. Call you later, okay?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">It was too late; she&apos;d been spotted.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;He&apos;s keen, isn&apos;t he?&quot; Marcie said comfortably.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Seems to be.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Well, good for you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">When she got back to the flat the others had gone out. She needed to eat something to counteract the alcohol and was gazing sadly into an almost empty fridge when the phone rang. She knew who it would be.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Michael, this is getting ridiculous.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;m sorry.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;And stop bloody apologising.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Should I call you later?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;No. No, it&apos;s okay. Just a bit spooky, that&apos;s all.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;ve missed you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Me too.&quot; Jane was feeling slightly sick. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">I must eat something, she thought. Anything. Just give me carbohydrates.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Have you had anything to eat yet?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Now you&apos;re a bloody mind-reader.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I was just guessing, honestly.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;No, I&apos;ve just got in. I&apos;m starving.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Shall I cook you a meal?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;You can cook as well? Is there </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T7">anything </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">you can&apos;t do?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Come over. I&apos;ll make pasta or something. Bring a bottle of wine.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;ll bring two.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Yes, he could cook. And it hadn&apos;t been a fluke: he really was that good in bed. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">I could get used to this</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">, Jane thought. They were sitting up in bed finishing the last of the wine.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Tell me about your angel,&quot; she said. &quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">“Are you going to laugh at me?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"><text:s/>&quot;No, promise. I&apos;m interested.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;It&apos;s happened on and off since I was little. I can&apos;t control it or anything. Lately it&apos;s been happening a lot.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;d noticed.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I know it sounds completely insane.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;It&apos;s not exactly an everyday thing, is it?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I — well, I hear a voice.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane suddenly felt very cold. &quot;You hear voices?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;One particular voice. It&apos;s very quiet, doesn&apos;t say much. Often it&apos;s just a single word.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Man&apos;s voice or a woman&apos;s?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Hard to say. Woman&apos;s I think.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;How do you know it&apos;s an angel?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;That&apos;s just how I&apos;ve always thought of it. Until I was about ten or eleven I used to think everyone had one.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Not me,&quot; Jane said firmly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;No.&quot; He finished his wine. &quot;It&apos;s only ever told me the truth, and only things I needed to know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Like my mobile number.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I missed you,&quot; he said defensively.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Do you do this to all your girlfriends? This psychic stalker routine?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"><text:s/>&quot;It&apos;s not a routine.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;But you must see it&apos;s a bit — off-putting.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Does it put you off?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Scares me a bit sometimes.&quot; </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">Scares me a lot sometimes</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">, she thought.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;There&apos;s nothing to be scared of. Honestly.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">She looked at him. He appeared to be harmless. This was their second night together and he hadn&apos;t killed her yet, although there was always the possibility that she might die of sheer sexual excess. It didn&apos;t seem too dreadful a prospect. She put down her glass and they curled up together. It felt safe. She could sleep here.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">3</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">When Tom got back from Zurich it was after midnight. He was tired and it was raining and he wanted a drink. The kitchen was a mess, the table hadn&apos;t even been cleared and there was no alcohol of any kind anywhere, although an empty wine-bottle taunted him from the draining-board. He could read the signs: Michael had pulled. It didn&apos;t improve his temper. At the farewell dinner he&apos;d completely failed to get off with Anna, who he&apos;d been chatting up for weeks, ever since the negotiations started and they&apos;d been in the initial meeting. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">Bloody Swiss. Bloody lawyers.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">In the morning he slept in, allowing the mysterious house-guest a chance to depart unseen. He wondered vaguely who she was. They&apos;d shared this flat for over a year and it was the first time this had happened, or the first time this way round at any rate. It was usually Michael who was having to be discreet</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">. Well, it&apos;s his turn</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">, he reflected. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">Probably a good thing; about time Michael pulled himself together a bit.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">When he emerged at about eleven the kitchen was spotless, there was coffee in the pot and Michael, alone and fully dressed, was calmly reading the paper.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Good trip?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Fucking freezing and boring as hell.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Same as last time then.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Colder. We got the job done, though. All signed and sealed.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;That&apos;s good.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Tom put some toast on. &quot;I see you&apos;ve washed up then.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I always do. You know I do.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;You hadn&apos;t last night. Came in here looking for a drink, thought a bomb had hit it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Michael coloured slightly. &quot;I had someone over for dinner.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Thought so.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;You met her once, actually. In the Queen&apos;s Head. You were trying to chat her friend up, remember?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;What, that Welsh bird?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Her friend.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Oh yes. I remember she was with someone but I couldn&apos;t tell you what she looked like. No, hang on. Blonde girl with glasses. Wouldn&apos;t have been too bad without the glasses. Bit on the plump side. Am I right?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Well, she&apos;s blonde and she wears glasses.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;No accounting for tastes.&quot; Tom opened a pot of jam. &quot;No, but good for you, mate. Couldn&apos;t have happened to a nicer bloke.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Thanks.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Still on for this afternoon?&quot; Tom had tickets for a rugby international. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Sure. Wouldn&apos;t miss it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Many hours later they found themselves in an Indian restaurant somewhere in Bayswater without any very coherent idea of how they&apos;d got there. They were both pleasantly but thoroughly drunk.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;No, I&apos;m really pleased for you, mate,&quot; Tom was saying, by no means for the first time.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;So am I.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;About time. You know what I always said.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Yes.&quot; It wasn&apos;t going to stop him saying it again. &quot;What you need, son, is the love of a good woman.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;The love,&quot; Tom said again, as distinctly as he could manage, &quot;of a good woman. You can&apos;t beat it.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You can&apos;t go on forever, you know. Good woman, that&apos;s it.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Always said so. She </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">is </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">a good woman, is she?&quot; Tom was suddenly concerned. &quot;This what&apos;s-her-name?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Jane. Yes, I think so.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Good for you, mate. Just what you need. Just what you </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">deserve, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michael old man.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Well, I&apos;m very happy as well, Tom.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;That&apos;s good. That&apos;s bloody good. Always good to see you with a smile on your face. Been too long.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Been a while.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Been a bloody lifetime. Well what I say is, what&apos;s gone is gone.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You can&apos;t live in the past. Future, that&apos;s the thing.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Here&apos;s to Jane.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Cheers.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;All the best, mate. All the best.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">The hangover wasn&apos;t good. Michael had once been through a hard-drinking phase but it was some time ago and his system had lost the knack. It wasn&apos;t that he especially wanted to stay in bed, it was just that any form of sudden movement was so painful. Tom was jolly and made him tea. The tea was a lot better than the jollity.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Carefully nursing his head against the pillows he thought of the box under his bed and supposed hopelessly that he ought to do something about it. But even thinking too hard seemed to hurt.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Still, it was progress of a sort that he could think about it and the only pain was physical.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Tom and Jane were properly introduced the next weekend, when she came over for dinner</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T12"> </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T12">à trois</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Tom had tried to angle for a foursome but was philosophical when he learned that Marcie was now spoken for (again). Naturally, Michael was doing the cooking; Tom was supplying alcohol, this being his speciality. By the time she arrived, he was already well into a bottle of Chardonnay and in expansive mood. This was in part also due to news of his impending promotion for his part in the Swiss deal. It was Tom who buzzed her in on the entry-phone.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Jane, brilliant,&quot; he said. &quot;Come in, come in. Michael&apos;s doing something amazing with a chicken. Glass of wine?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Thanks.&quot; She joined Tom in the sitting-room, where he had enthroned himself in the only armchair. That left the matching sofa, or the floor. She opted for the sofa.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I expect the </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">chef de cuisine </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">will be through in a second.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Have you known Michael long?&quot; she asked. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Donkey&apos;s years. Well, since university anyway.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Did you study French as well?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;God, no. As much as I can do to speak English. Economics, me. One of my mates in the rugby team knew Michael from school and we sort of became a set. About a year ago we were both looking for a place in London so we clubbed together and here we are. It&apos;s worked out pretty well. I make the mess and he cleans it up.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Where were you before you moved here?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Well, I was in the States getting my MBA and of course Michael was in France.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I didn&apos;t know Michael had lived in France.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Oh.&quot; Tom looked guilty. He had such a childlike face that the effect was rather comical. &quot;Top you up?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;No thanks, I&apos;m fine.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michael sidled in. It was one of his awkward days. &quot;Ready in about fifteen minutes. Hello, Jane. I hope you&apos;re hungry.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Starving. Your flatmate&apos;s been plying me with drink on an empty stomach.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;ll open another bottle,&quot; Tom volunteered, heading for the kitchen.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michael took his place beside Jane, uneasily. She took his hand.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What&apos;s the matter?&quot; she asked softly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Nothing.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Bollocks.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">He stirred. &quot;I don&apos;t know. Just been thinking a lot about stuff. You know.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;About me?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;No. Not you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane tried another tack. &quot;You never told me that you&apos;d lived in France.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Yes. Yes, I did, for a while. I suppose Tom told you.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Well, I didn&apos;t get it from the Archangel Gabriel.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It was a long time ago. I don&apos;t talk about it.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;d noticed.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Oh for God&apos;s sake, Jane, we&apos;ve only known each other a fortnight. You can&apos;t expect to know my whole life story already.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Tom came in wearing a bright smile, a bottle of wine in one hand and a full glass in the other. &quot;Are we having fun yet?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Thanks.&quot; Michael took the proffered glass and drank off about half of it. &quot;I&apos;d better check the dinner.&quot; Pausing only to top up his drink, he was off.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Tom frowned. &quot;Did I say something?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I did, I think.&quot; She held out her glass for a refill. &quot;Tom. What happened in France?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Lots of things happened in France, one time or another,&quot; he said evasively. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Sorry. I shouldn&apos;t have asked.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Look.&quot; Tom sat next to her. &quot;I don&apos;t want to speak out of turn. I&apos;ve known Michael a long time, and he&apos;s — well, he&apos;s very different from me in a lot of ways, but, you know. He&apos;s a good friend. And things haven&apos;t always been easy for him.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;No. I&apos;d guessed as much.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Be good to him, Jane.&quot; He looked at her intently. &quot;He&apos;s a special kind of guy.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michael put his head round the door. &quot;It&apos;s ready.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Monday morning: exhaustion: rain: disgusting tea from the machine because coffee was off. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Somebody died?&quot; Marcie enquired cheerfully. &quot;Or was it you and you just haven&apos;t stopped moving yet?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I love you too. Up for a drink tonight?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;Think you&apos;ll live that long?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Thanks.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">After exacting several probably unreliable promises of discretion, Jane set out all the facts she knew about Michael before her friend. Even as she spoke, the words ceased to make sense to her. Marcie was unusually quiet and heard her out without any intervention. Eventually Jane petered out and there was a thoughtful silence.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;New one on me,&quot; Marcie said eventually.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;But what do you think?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Don&apos;t know what to think exactly.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&apos;Join the club.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Well, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T15">do</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> you </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">think he&apos;s a nutter?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane hesitated. &quot;No. I don&apos;t think so.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;So he&apos;s for real?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I don&apos;t know. I suppose so.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You really believe all that crap about angels?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I don&apos;t have much alternative, do I?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Jesus.&quot; Marcie was impressed despite herself.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I just wish I knew, that&apos;s all.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What do you want to know, exactly?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I don&apos;t even know that.&quot; Jane finished her drink. &quot;The story of his life, I suppose.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Then ask him.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I can&apos;t,&quot; she said miserably.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Look, love, you could always chuck him.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane said nothing.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It&apos;ll probably be okay,&quot; Marcie said, trying to sound encouraging.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">4</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">It&apos;s no good</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">, Jane said to herself, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">I&apos;ll have to bite the bullet</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">. She&apos;d been through this appalling ordeal twice before and each time had been even worse than she&apos;d expected it to be, but it couldn&apos;t be avoided forever. Hoping to soften the blow, she broached the subject when they had just made love and there was a safe post-coital cosiness.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Michael,&quot; she murmured into his armpit, &quot;I&apos;d like you to meet my parents.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Sorry?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She repeated the invitation more audibly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Oh,&quot; he said. &quot;All right.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I thought we could go for the weekend.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Where do they live?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Sutton Coldfield.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Isn&apos;t that in Birmingham?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane had long ago given up denying it. &quot;Yes.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;All right.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">There was nothing like sex, Jane thought, for making a man reasonable.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">They hired a car for the weekend. Michael offered to drive, which surprised her; she&apos;d somehow assumed that he couldn&apos;t, with his physical awkwardness and lack of mental focus. She wasn&apos;t at all surprised to discover that he was absolutely terrible. Jane was not a good passenger at the best of times, and this was a white-knuckle ride. The trouble began at the first left-hand turn. At first she just thought he&apos;d taken it a bit wide, but then she realised he was proposing to stay on the right-hand side of the road.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Michael!&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Wrong side of the road.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Oh, yes. Sorry.&quot; He changed sides. She hoped it lasted.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">It amazed her that they even made it out of London. The M40 was not an experience she was looking forward to. Somehow they made it, though, and while there were one or two near-misses he didn&apos;t quite manage to wreck the car. And at least it took her mind off what her mother would say.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">At long last they turned into the dull familiar street where she had been born and bred. Jane had never thought she&apos;d be so pleased to see the place again. Michael parked, or at least brought the car to a halt within walking distance of the pavement, and they carried their bags up the gravel driveway. Jane was shaking a little. A gin and tonic would do her no harm at all, she decided.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Her mother came to the door, very much the suburban chatelaine. Not for the first time, Jane wished she wouldn&apos;t dress quite so much like the wife of a prospective Tory candidate.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&apos;Jane darling, lovely to see you. And this is Michael?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">He admitted it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Your father&apos;s just in the kitchen, I&apos;ll get him. Do sit down, Michael. Arthur will take your bags up. Did you have a good journey?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;Fine,&quot; said Jane.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Would you like a cup of tea? Coffee?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Anything stronger?&quot; Jane asked, trying not to sound as desperate as she felt. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Tea will be fine,&quot; Michael said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You sit down, I&apos;ll see to everything. Arthur? They&apos;re here!&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">They took their places on the sofa. Michael was looking about him with interest. Jane hoped he wasn&apos;t making deductions about her own taste in decor on the basis of what he could see. It was a hideous specimen of middle-class niceness, all chintz and tasteful ornaments; the sort of house where you could confidently expect to find a knitted toilet-roll cover in the shape of a top hat. When she eventually got a place of her own, Jane had long ago decided that it would have stripped floorboards, white walls, and the bare minimum of simple modern furniture. There might possibly be a couple of Mondrian prints if she was feeling baroque. Her mother came in and set a tray down on the Louis Quinze-style coffee table. Inevitably she was using the best china. Jane hadn&apos;t seen it since she&apos;d brought Robert, her last boyfriend, two years ago. He&apos;d broken a teacup, and the relationship had never really recovered.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Her mother hadn&apos;t brought her a proper drink, so she went and helped herself. Her father was in the kitchen manfully slicing vegetables. He never looked truly comfortable in a pinafore.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Hello, love. Good journey?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Terrible.&quot; She kissed him.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Well, you&apos;re here now. Have a G &amp; T and get me one while you&apos;re at it.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What&apos;re you cooking?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Something your mother found in Delia.&quot; He gestured vaguely at the open cookbook. &quot;He&apos;s not a vegetarian or anything, is he?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Michael? No, this&apos;ll be fine.&quot; She handed him his drink. &quot;Cheers.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Cheers.&quot; There was a shared moment of bliss as they each took a sip. &quot;It&apos;s good to see you, love.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;And you, Dad.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;ll be through in a moment. Just need to put these on to steam.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She went back into the lounge. Her mother was holding forth on a subject dear to her heart, namely the manifest superiority of Sutton Coldfield over the rest of the world in general, and London in particular. Michael appeared to have gone into a trance, but this was not unusual for him and frankly it was quite understandable in the circumstances.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Jane, darling. I was just telling Michael about the new Tesco&apos;s.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;m sure he doesn&apos;t want to know about that, Mum.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;They&apos;ve got a wonderful fish counter.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;We do have shops in London, you know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You see,&quot; her mother said to Michael with an air of triumph. &quot;She simply won&apos;t be told, will you, Jane?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">The evening passed off without much incident. The meal was excellent. It never ceased to amaze Jane that her father was such a good cook; he always looked utterly lost in the kitchen, as if he&apos;d never seen one before. There were hidden depths to him. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">Perhaps that&apos;s why I fell for Michael,</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> she thought. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">God, how Freudian</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I thought we&apos;d eat out tomorrow,&quot; her mother said. &quot;There&apos;s the most divine Italian restaurant that opened a few months ago, we went there for our wedding anniversary, didn&apos;t we, Arthur? </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Much </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">better than that place you took us when we came to see you last time.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;If you say so,&quot; Jane said reasonably.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I do say so. Do you like Italian food, Michael?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What? Oh, yes. Very much.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;That&apos;s settled then.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">There was a small awkwardness at bedtime. Michael had been installed in her brother&apos;s room, since he was away at university, while Jane was back in her old bedroom. As a matter of principle she was determined that they would share the same bed. Jane and her mother had fought this battle before. Mrs Sharp affected to suppose that, being unmarried, Jane was not only a virgin but had no sexual needs at all. Previously she had more or less gone along with this, but this time she was going to make a stand. It probably meant going without sleep, because two people are a lot in a single bed and Michael was not a compact sleeper, but it was a price she was willing to pay.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">After everyone had retired to their separate rooms she tapped softly on Michael&apos;s door. He was already in bed. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Move over,&quot; she whispered. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;There isn&apos;t room.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Yes there is.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">He complied without much enthusiasm. He was right; there really wasn&apos;t much room. She could only get about three-quarters of herself onto the mattress. It didn&apos;t feel very secure.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You okay there?&quot; he asked.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;m fine. Go to sleep.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">For a long time she lay in darkness, one chilly buttock hanging over the void, listening to the distant roar of the motorway. Even though he was squashed up against the wall, Michael apparently had no trouble getting to sleep. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">Bastard</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">. She hoped her mother was going to notice.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Hours passed. The town fell quiet. There was a street-lamp just outside her brother&apos;s window making the curtains glow a lurid orange. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">I wonder how he manages to sleep in here</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">, she wondered idly. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">I suppose he&apos;s used to it.</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> In the time-honoured fashion Jane tried counting sheep. It had never worked for her in the past, and this was no exception. What else? She tried visualising herself on a tropical beach but it wasn&apos;t easy with a cold bum. Her neck was starting to ache because of the angle it was pressed into her half of the pillow. It was going to be a long night.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Did you sleep well?&quot; her mother asked the red-eyed hag who had staggered down to breakfast.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Fine.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;How about you, Michael?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;All right.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It was a bit cramped, actually,&quot; Jane said. There was no way she would let her suffering have been in vain.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;ll make some more coffee,&quot; her mother said smoothly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">They drove out to Stratford-on-Avon for the day and did tourist things. Jane had no interest in Shakespeare whatsoever, and neither as far as she knew did Michael, but he bore it with admirable patience. Her mother was a pillar of the local amateur dramatic society and a bit inclined to gush on the subject of the Bard. Nobody attempted to stem the flow, so she was left with the agreeable impression that the day had been a great success. Jane fell asleep in the car on the way back. She could do that when her father was driving. When she was a child they used to go on caravan holidays and it was a family joke that she always nodded off on the journey. This time it was mostly basic sleep deprivation.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Her mother, of course, wanted to change for their meal out. Jane hadn&apos;t really packed clothes for such an occasion, not that she possessed much in that line anyway, but she made the best of what she had with her. Michael combed his hair, and her father put on a jacket. The restaurant was actually quite good, in spite of her mother&apos;s recommendation. Jane ate heartily in the comforting knowledge that it was at someone else&apos;s expense. There was wine. Michael became surprisingly talkative, by his standards. He explained about his own family, which he&apos;d never really discussed with her: his father, who had died ten years before, and his French mother who had now remarried and was living in California. It all sounded a lot more glamorous than Sutton Coldfield.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Do you speak French?&quot; Mrs Sharp enquired.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;m pretty much bilingual. My mother always tried to bring me up to speak French, and of course I studied it at Cambridge.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;And Spanish,&quot; Jane put in, just to make sure none of his accomplishments were lost on her mother.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;That must be jolly useful,&quot; her father said. He approved of practical things.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I used to work for a French company, handling their exports into Britain,&quot; Michael went on. &quot;Electrical goods.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Really?&quot; said Mrs Sharp, evidently impressed.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Then I came into some money, and, well, for a variety of reasons I left. Sales aren&apos;t really my thing.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Spot more Chianti?&quot; asked Mr Sharp. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Thanks.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">The evening got better and better. Jane had the most gorgeous </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T16">tiramisu</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T7"> </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">of her entire life, followed by an espresso and a small but effective grappa. She could tell that in his quiet way her father approved of Michael, which pleased her immensely. He wasn&apos;t a demonstrative man, but they had always been close. She sometimes thought he found her brother a bit intimidating, though. Mathematicians have that effect on some people; Jane had given up on him when he got to about fifteen or so. Her friends&apos; brothers had all been normal, interested in football and cars, and later also alcohol and sex. As a teenager she had attempted to pass herself off as an only child. He was supposed to be a genius of some sort, which is rarely a social asset. Even her mother had stopped mentioning it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Michael was telling them about a visit he had paid to his mother in California. Mrs Sharp was spellbound by his description of the house she and his stepfather lived in.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Just imagine, Arthur. A swimming-pool!&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He had been taken on the obligatory tour of one of the big Hollywood studios, which he contrasted with their outing to Stratford. From what Jane could make out the main difference was that the Americans milked the tourist dollar on a larger scale and with more honesty. Her mother lapped it up. The climax of the tale was that they had been in some restaurant and seen someone who might have been Tom Cruise.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Gosh, how exciting!&quot; Mrs Sharp exclaimed.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I saw Bob Hoskins in a newsagent&apos;s once,&quot; Jane volunteered.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;And have you been back there since?&quot; her mother asked, ignoring her.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;No. We&apos;re not close, really.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;That&apos;s a shame. Isn&apos;t that a shame, Arthur?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">All in all it was a very satisfactory day. Jane only hoped she might get more than three hours&apos; sleep at the end of it. Michael suggested that she should sleep in her own room.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;No way.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Why not?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I want to sleep with you. Is that a problem?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I just thought you&apos;d be more comfortable on your own.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It&apos;s not about being comfortable.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michael was baffled. &quot;What is it about, then?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I want my mother to realise that we sleep together, that&apos;s all.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Doesn&apos;t she know that?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;She thinks I&apos;m still a virgin.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Why should you care about that?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I just do, all right?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">This time it was marginally less uncomfortable and she managed to get some sleep in the end, although by no means as much as she craved. Still, she was alert enough the next morning to be able to take over the driving. Jane wasn&apos;t a very confident or experienced driver but she was sure she was better than Michael. At least if they died in a road accident she&apos;d have nobody else to blame. He didn&apos;t seem to take it as a slur on his competence, even though it was. She was glad about that because he was very much in her good books. The weekend had gone extremely well and he&apos;d handled her parents like a dream.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;They seem like nice people,&quot; Michael said conversationally.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;My mother? You&apos;ve got to be joking.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You haven&apos;t met mine,&quot; he pointed out.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;That&apos;s true.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;The way you carry on about her, I thought she would be some sort of ogre.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I don&apos;t carry on about her.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Yes, you do.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Well, perhaps.&quot; Jane had her usual nervous crisis about getting onto the motorway, but it was okay. There was very little traffic. &quot;Anyway, she seems to like you. And my dad.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;He&apos;s very quiet, isn&apos;t he?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Doesn&apos;t get much choice, married to my mother.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I suppose not.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">They survived the journey home without any untoward incident. Jane was exhausted. It was a long time since she&apos;d driven so far, and having had so little sleep she had no reserves of energy. Michael was solicitous.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Can I stay at yours?&quot; she asked him.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Of course. Will you be all right for work tomorrow?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane considered. She had some clothes that would do. &quot;Yes, I&apos;ll be fine.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;In that case, I&apos;ll cook us some dinner and you can get an early night. You look as if you need it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I do.&quot; </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">Truly</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">, she thought</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">, this is the kind of man fantasies are made of</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">5</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">It took a long time for the warm glow of that weekend to wear off. Jane had always thought of her parents as representing the acid test for any prospective partner. It was at her parents&apos; that the dashing Robert had shown that he had feet of clay. He was easily the best-looking man that Jane had ever gone out with, but he couldn&apos;t hack it with her mother. The same went for Graham, her steady boyfriend for most of her time at university, although in his case she&apos;d had her doubts for a while. There&apos;s something wrong with a man who feels the need to iron his underpants.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">It was really quite a trivial incident that first made her wonder about Michael. They&apos;d been out for a drink and Jane was in a pleasantly amorous frame of mind. He seemed a bit absent, but she was used to that. It wasn&apos;t going to put her off. Tom was out for the evening, the night was young, and she was as near to being in love as made no difference. They were on the sofa: the lights were low.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Don&apos;t,&quot; he mumbled.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Don&apos;t what?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;m not in the mood.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Well, I am.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">He pushed her away, none too gently. &quot;Not tonight.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Why not? Wrong time of the month?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I think you&apos;d better go.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane was outraged. &quot;Why? What&apos;s the matter?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Nothing.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Bollocks. There&apos;s something up. Tell me.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It&apos;s an anniversary,&quot; he mumbled.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Anniversary? Anniversary of what? Are you married or something?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;No, of course not.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Well?&quot; Desire was rapidly congealing into anger. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">“Just go,&quot; he said wretchedly. &quot;Please.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane stood up. &quot;All right. If that&apos;s what you want.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">“I&apos;m sorry.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Oh, you will be.&quot; She started gathering her things together. &quot;Don&apos;t you worry about that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">All the way home she wondered furiously what was going on with him. Didn&apos;t he want her any more? He&apos;d been the one who seduced her in the first place, hadn&apos;t he? She was angry because he was being so mysterious, and angry too from plain sexual frustration. There had better be a really good explanation for this.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">But when he eventually called her —Jane would rather have died than call first under those circumstances — she could get nothing out of him. He apologised at length, which was the least he could do. He evaded her questions with such clumsiness that it only piqued her curiosity still further. She wasn&apos;t quite prepared to chuck him for a first offence, but if he thought she&apos;d forgotten about it then he was mistaken. Jane was determined to get to the bottom of this one.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">They made up, of course. Boyfriends that her father approved of were not so common that she could afford to discard them willy-nilly. Indeed, Michael was the first to meet that criterion since she was seventeen. And when he </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T11">was</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> in the mood, he was still the best lover she&apos;d ever had, and she could forgive a lot for that.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Nevertheless she couldn&apos;t let go of it altogether. To begin with she hoped he&apos;d bring it up of his own accord in time. She waited, and waited. Jane was good at waiting. All the same her patience was finite, and eventually she tackled him again. This time she&apos;d gone too far: his stubbornness matched her own, and he was obviously determined to say nothing at all. There was a dreadful forty-eight hours when she thought it was all over. She had to promise not to ask him again, and that was very hard. It went against the grain. But if the alternative was losing Michael, she found that she preferred to give way.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">After that things were never quite the same again. She tried everything she could think of. She systematically confessed all the worst things from her own past, of which there were a few although nothing too lurid. He listened and was marvellously sympathetic and volunteered absolutely nothing in return. Even the story about Robert and the mayonnaise only made him laugh. This was an achievement in itself, as he wasn&apos;t especially prone to laughter, but that was small consolation. After that she gave up.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">They went on for some weeks, awkwardly, neither of them prepared to return to the subject they were both thinking about. Most weekends she stayed over at his flat. Once she cooked a meal for the three of them, which wasn&apos;t a success. They went to unthreatening films, to art galleries, once to a chamber music recital which bored her alarmingly. The year, no longer new, grudgingly conceded a damp spring; things began to flower. Jane began to feel a sense of hopelessness. Apparently he&apos;d stopped having his dreams, or maybe he&apos;d just stopped talking about them. He never had been all that communicative anyway.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Tom worried about them. She liked Tom: they shared a deep unspoken concern for Michael&apos;s happiness. They had long and inconclusive conversations about him when he wasn&apos;t there. Tom was determined not to break any confidences, but just knowing that there were confidences he might break encouraged her. At least there was some sort of explanation, even if she was no nearer finding it than the night they&apos;d met.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">And yet it was genuinely by accident that she&apos;d found the box. She wasn&apos;t looking for clues; she knew he&apos;d have hated the idea of anyone going through his personal things, and had always respected that. She was resigned to waiting for him to tell her when he was ready, assuming she lived to see the day. And then one morning when the two men were out she was tidying the flat (she practically lived there by this time), ran the vacuum cleaner under his bed, felt rather than heard the thump, and there it was.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane knelt and peered under the bed. It was an ordinary enough box: plain brown cardboard, square, with a lid; about the size of two shoeboxes side by side. It might have contained anything or nothing. She was immediately consumed with passionate curiosity. Something about its being hidden under the bed struck her as symbolic — of what, she couldn&apos;t say. Her first thought was that she would show Tom, followed immediately by a second thought that he would be appalled at such a violation of his friend&apos;s privacy.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">All along, of course, she knew that she would have to open it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She looked at her watch. It would be at least an hour before they returned. Jane reached under the bed and drew the box towards her. It was quite heavy. As she got it out into the light she saw the thick layer of dust on top of it, and a printed label pasted to the lid. With difficulty, she made out: </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Auber </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T12">&amp; fils, Pâtissiers</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Taking great care not to disturb the dust, she eased off the lid and set it on the floor beside her. The box was full of letters, all by the same hand, in no apparent order. Jane swallowed hard. She had an overpowering urge to sneeze and had to turn away quickly. When she turned back the letters were still there. They weren&apos;t in Michael&apos;s handwriting. Still not daring to touch, she leaned over and stared at the topmost letter. It looked to her like a woman&apos;s handwriting, and it was in French.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane had studied French at school in what now seemed to have been a previous life. She&apos;d even somehow passed an exam in it once. Even as she stared down at the creamy notepaper she was already thinking of the English-French dictionary she had left behind at her parents&apos; house. She was trying not to look and at the same time helplessly looking. Pale blue ink. A crisp graceful hand, easy to read. It would all be in here: all of it. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">Christ</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">. Jane felt her mouth go dry. She shouldn&apos;t even be looking at this, let alone be trying to read it, even upside-down.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">Sky-blue, translucent as a butterfly&apos;s wing, the flimsy envelope let slip the flimsier page. The darker blue of the ink ran like poison, foreign and familiar. Jane was completely <text:soft-page-break/>stilled by the absolute certain chill of sudden fear. There was a scent <text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">—</text:span></text:span> was there a scent? <text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">—</text:span></text:span> that might have been violets. Or her imagination. She looked at the paper as if it had come from Venus. She held in her hand <text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">—</text:span></text:span> her fingers were actually touching <text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">—</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">But when you have stepped off the edge of the cliff, all you can do is keep falling.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">And then she&apos;d read it, the first words anyway. She tried not to understand them but her eyes had already sucked them in.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">My dearest —</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">It hurt. It already hurt. And there was a whole box of this. Jane checked her watch again. There was time. She went to the kitchen, extracted a plastic carrier-bag from the drawer where Michael kept them, came back into the bedroom. The box was still there. She swallowed, knelt, and scooped the letters into the bag as if they were so many dead leaves. With trembling hands, feeling the police were about to arrive at any moment, she replaced the lid and slid the box back into its hiding-place. Then she knotted the carrier-bag. It took her a long time; the plastic kept slipping through her limp and sweating fingers. At last it was done. She got unsteadily to her feet, clutching the bag to her chest with both hands. For a second, or an eternity, her mind was blank. Then she remembered her overnight case. It was practically a fixture here these days, but surely she could take it home without arousing any suspicions. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">Laundry</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">. She hid it under her laundry. It still seemed appallingly conspicuous. Surely anyone walking in would see immediately what she&apos;d done?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">Oh Christ, the door</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">. She leapt back into the bedroom, fumbling for the switch on the hoover, but it was only Tom.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Where&apos;s Michael?&quot; she asked, trying to sound casual.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Said he was going for a walk. You know what he&apos;s like, needs to be on his own sometimes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;You all right, Jane? You look a bit pale.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;m fine.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Tell you what, let&apos;s pop over the road and I&apos;ll buy you a gin and tonic. Put some colour back in your cheeks.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;What about Michael?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Leave him a note.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">She couldn&apos;t think of an excuse to get out of it, but all the time they were sitting in the pub opposite she was horribly aware of her stolen treasure lying unguarded in the flat. Tom </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">told her some long story about Anna, whom he had finally managed to seduce on his latest trip over to Zurich but who was now making difficulties about coming over to see him in London. After a while, even Tom noticed she wasn&apos;t paying attention.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;What is it, Jane?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;What&apos;s what?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Come on, something&apos;s eating you. Spit it out.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She was confused for a moment by his suggestion that she spit out something that was eating her — surely it must be the other way round? — and before she could stop herself she said: &quot;It&apos;s Michael.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What about him?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;He&apos;s keeping something from me, I know he is, and he knows that I know. It&apos;s like there&apos;s this invisible thing we have to walk around all the time. And it just seems to keep on getting bigger. We hardly talk to each other any more.&quot; Jane could feel herself going pink: she&apos;d said too much, and knew it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Tom was looking serious. &quot;I didn&apos;t realise it was so bad.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Well, now you know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Do you want me to have a word with him?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I don&apos;t know. It might make things worse. You know what he&apos;s like.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;He cares about you, Jane.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I know he does. I just wish he felt he could trust me a bit more, that&apos;s all.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Tom scratched his ear thoughtfully. &quot;It&apos;s hard for him. You don&apos;t know what he&apos;s been through.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;That&apos;s just the point: I don&apos;t. Why can&apos;t he tell me? Is it so awful?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It was for him.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I mean, did he kill his granny with the bread-knife and they&apos;ve just let him out of the loony-bin? I don&apos;t care what it is, I just need to know.&quot; Even as she was saying this, Jane was conscious of a certain element of bravado.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I can&apos;t tell you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I know that. Oh, I&apos;m sorry, Tom, I don&apos;t mean to dump it all on you. It&apos;s just — I&apos;m going out of my mind with it, that&apos;s all. I feel so </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">stuck.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">At that point Michael walked in, looked about him abstractedly, almost missed them, then came over to their table.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I got your note,&quot; he said, superfluously.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What&apos;ll you have?&quot; asked Tom.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Whatever you&apos;re having.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">He sat down beside Jane without looking at her. Tom went off to the bar. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Are you okay?&quot; she said. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;m fine.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You have a nice walk?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It was okay.&quot; He couldn&apos;t actually remember any of it: his head had certainly not been where his feet had gone.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She felt like screaming but they were in public so she remained silent. They stayed that way until Tom came back. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;There you go.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Thanks.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I was just telling Jane the latest about Anna.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Right.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I don&apos;t know why I put myself through it. I mean, I hate the Swiss and everybody hates lawyers, so why do I fall for a Swiss lawyer?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Why does anyone fall for anyone?&quot; Michael asked nobody in particular.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;If I had any sense, which I don&apos;t,&quot; Tom continued, &quot;I&apos;d go for someone like Jane. You&apos;re a lucky man, mate.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Don&apos;t embarrass me,&quot; she said insincerely. It felt extremely good to be complimented, indeed it felt good just to be noticed, even though she knew he meant nothing by it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I mean it. You could go a long way and do a lot worse. I have.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I thought Anna was your dream woman,&quot; Michael said. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;That was when she was a dream. Reality is something else.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Ah.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What does &apos;Ah&apos; mean, exactly?&quot; Jane enquired. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I don&apos;t want to talk about it,&quot; Michael said. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Is there anything you </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">do </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">want to talk about?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Not at the moment.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane stood up abruptly. &quot;In that case I&apos;m off home. I&apos;ve got a ton of washing to do.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You can do it here,&quot; Tom said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;d rather not. Nothing personal.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Will you be coming back?&quot; Michael enquired calmly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I don&apos;t know.&quot; She kissed Tom on the cheek. &quot;Thanks for the drink.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;ll call you,&quot; Michael said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Whatever.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">As soon as she got home Jane called her mother. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Is there anything wrong, darling?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Everything&apos;s fine,&quot; she said firmly. &quot;I just wondered if you could do me a favour.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Of course. What is it?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;You know that old French dictionary I had for school? Have you still got it?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;m not sure. I&apos;ll ask your father.&quot; There were noises off as they debated the question at some length. &quot;He says he thinks it&apos;s in the attic.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Great. Would you mind posting it to me?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Whatever for?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;m thinking of taking some evening classes,&quot; she improvised. &quot;Brush up my French.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Any special reason?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Well, you know, we&apos;re all Europeans now, and all that. And I did think I might go there on holiday perhaps.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Well, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T7">if </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">your father can find it, and you know what he&apos;s like, dear, but we&apos;ll send it straight over.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Thanks very much.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;It&apos;s no trouble.&quot; Well, it was no trouble for </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">her</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">; she wouldn&apos;t be the one dispatched to the attic. &quot;Everything all right?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Yes, yes, everything&apos;s fine.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Well, keep in touch, darling.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I will.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">After that Jane went into her room and dug out the carrier-bag. She was afraid to open it. She was afraid even to have it on the premises. After all, it was technically theft. Jane had no practical experience of the criminal justice system and wasn&apos;t keen to start now. God knows what Michael will do if he ever finds out, she thought. She put the bag on top of her wardrobe and hid it behind a suitcase. She had to stand on a chair to reach and she felt like a complete idiot. All the same it felt better once the thing was out of sight. Of course it was still there, and some time soon she&apos;d have to open it and face the contents. She wasn&apos;t looking forward to that.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Maybe she wouldn&apos;t be able to make the letters out after all? Maybe she&apos;d forgotten all the French she ever knew and whatever truth they concealed would stay secret? On impulse she popped out to the newsagents and bought the French edition </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style40"><text:span text:style-name="T17">of</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style40"><text:span text:style-name="T7"> </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Marie Claire. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">It felt as if she were buying pornography. She rolled it up as she left the shop to make sure nobody could see what it was, trying to look casual and feeling like a shoplifter. As soon as she got home she raced back into her bedroom.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane was a little dismayed to find that she could understand quite a lot of it even without the dictionary. Ignorance would be no protection</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">. I could take them back</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">, she reasoned. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">It&apos;s not too late</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">But it was too late, and she knew it. Now she had them she would have to read them. She&apos;d already started. And whatever story they told, things would never be the same again.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">She phoned Marcie. She was out. Jane swore, quite loudly. It helped, but not much.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">6</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">The day she dreaded was much like any other. The morning was damp but not unbearably bleak. The bus was no later than usual. The coffee tasted the same as always. Jane had asked for a kettle, but her request was turned down on health and safety grounds. Apparently an electric kettle is such a complicated and dangerous piece of equipment that untrained personnel would be unable to operate it without electrocuting themselves, poisoning themselves, and/or blacking out the National Grid. So they were stuck with the machine.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">When she got home there was a card on the kitchen table informing her that the Post Office had tried to deliver a parcel but she had been out. Jane sat down and stared at the card. It was a perfectly ordinary thing; she&apos;d seen them before. Except that she knew what this one referred to, and she was afraid of what it might unlock.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">There was still half an hour before the sorting office closed and it was only round the corner. She knew she ought to go and collect her parcel but she just sat there, hypnotised by the printed card.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Sue came in, full of the joys of spring. She began to tell Jane a long and involved story about a couple they both knew slightly. One of them was cheating on the other but Jane soon lost the plot. Talking about other people was Sue&apos;s major passion in life; Jane had often thought that if Sue were marooned on a desert island she&apos;d last about half an hour.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;But the best bit is,&quot; Sue was saying, &quot;Jackie went into the ladies&apos;, and there&apos;s Hannah dressed like a million dollars. So she came straight out again and said to Andy—&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;m going out. Sorting office will be shut in a minute.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Oh.&quot; Sue was disappointed at not reaching her punchline. &quot;Anything exciting?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">“Just a book.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">There was a little queue at the window where parcels were collected. A very deaf old man was deep in negotiations that seemed to have little prospect of concluding. Behind him there was a man in a mac who looked like a sexual deviant of the most lurid order, and behind him an improbably glamorous woman of about thirty whose coat alone probably cost more than Jane earned in a month. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">The Great British Queue: the defining institution of our culture</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">, she thought. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">All human life is there. In a thousand years&apos; time archaeologists will dig up our skeletons all neatly lined up one behind the other. They&apos;ll write learned articles about it. No doubt someone will prove it was some sort of fertility rite. That&apos;s what archaeologists always fall back on when they&apos;re stuck.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Eventually, with about two minutes to spare, it was Jane&apos;s turn. The man behind the window had a grizzled, almost rustic appearance, as if he had worked for the Post Office since adolescence, as had his father and grandfather and great-grandfather before him. </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Conceived on a mailbag, and probably had six toes. Jane slid her card under the glass without a word and the man looked at it with open suspicion and an expression of mild disgust. He sniffed. He looked from the card at Jane and back at the card. He evidently didn&apos;t like what he saw. Slowly and with the utmost reluctance he took the card and shuffled off out of her field of view. There was a certain amount of rustling and sighing, and then he shuffled back again, holding her parcel at arm&apos;s length. He sniffed again and slid it under the window.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Thanks,&quot; she said, and grabbed it quickly before he changed his mind. A middle-aged woman stepped up in her place.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Sorry, love, we&apos;re closed,&quot; the postal gnome announced with glum satisfaction, and pulled down the blind. Jane wondered if he slept there. The woman hammered on the window and began to harangue him loudly in a thick accent which Jane thought sounded Russian, but it was clearly going to be useless.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane walked slowly back to her flat, clutching the parcel to her like treasure. She had recognised her father&apos;s graceful, old-fashioned handwriting on the label with an odd pang of homesickness. It was as if she was a schoolgirl again, with a mountain of French homework to do: Marie-Claire goes shopping. She&apos;d quite liked French, partly because she felt sorry for Miss Prendergast who tried to teach them in the rare interludes between rioting. Miss Prendergast was a sweet-natured and rather pretty woman, probably somewhere in her thirties at the time although of course she&apos;d seemed impossibly ancient; left to her own devices she&apos;d probably have spent her life reading Flaubert and Stendhal and Alfred de Musset and doing good works, instead of which she had to man the barricades against 3b and try and make her soft voice heard as she took them once again through verbs ending in </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style42"><text:span text:style-name="T20">—ir. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane wondered what had become of her. Everyone said she was a lesbian, although they said that about all unmarried teachers against whom they had nothing more incriminating. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">Wherever you are, Miss Prendergast, watch over me now.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She cooked herself some pasta, ate it slowly, and washed everything up with the greatest care. All the time she thought of the still unopened parcel on her bed like a ticking bomb. Sue and Donna were watching something on television which had been advertised as a romantic comedy, but it was neither romantic nor comic and in any case Sue talked all the way through it. After that there was the news. Jane usually tried to avoid the news on the principle that what she didn&apos;t know couldn&apos;t hurt her, but tonight she watched it all the way through. A grey-faced man was saying that something or other in Bosnia was unacceptable. She even watched the regional bit at the end. There was going to be a tube strike. There was always going to be a tube strike, or else they&apos;d just called off the tube strike at the last minute, or there actually was a tube strike in which case there was said to be chaos. Jane had never noticed much difference between chaos and business as usual.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">It had got to the point where she couldn&apos;t ignore it any longer. She went to her room and tore open the brown paper. It was the same as she remembered it, a bit dog-eared, with her name inside in loopy schoolgirl writing. On the back cover someone had written &quot;Jane </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">fancies Mark&quot; in big straggly letters. Who the hell was Mark? Had she fancied him? Too late to do anything about it now, anyway.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She took the carrier-bag down from the top of the wardrobe and undid the knot very slowly. Her hands were trembling. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">I need a drink</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">, she thought. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">But nowhere will be open at this time of night.</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> There was a bottle of red wine in the kitchen about a third full, but that was Donna&apos;s. There was a protocol about these things.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane knocked softly on Donna&apos;s door.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Come in.&quot; Donna was sitting at her dressing-table in a long broderie anglaise night-dress, brushing her hair. Jane had had no idea she was so Victorian. It suited her. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Could I nick a glass of your wine?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;Sure. Finish it if you like. It&apos;s only Bulgarian.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;ll buy you a drink sometime.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Don&apos;t worry about it.&quot; Donna put down her hairbrush. &quot;Are you all right?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;m fine. Just fancied a drink, that&apos;s all.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Well, you&apos;re very welcome.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Thanks. Goodnight.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane took a large slug of wine and spread the letters out over her bed as if they were pieces in a jigsaw. Most of them were still in their original envelopes. There seemed to be more of them than she remembered. Perhaps they were breeding.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">The thing to do</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">, she told herself, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">is to get them in order</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">If there&apos;s a story here, it must have a beginning, a middle and an end. Stories do.</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"> She began cautiously comparing dates. With one exception, they covered a period of about eighteen months. The exception was the last one in the set, dated about a year ago. It was also the only one addressed to Michael at his London flat. Disregarding her good intentions, Jane read it first.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Dear Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">I hope you are comfortable in your new flat. <text:s text:c="2"/>It will be good for you to live with someone else. <text:s/>When you are alone I worry about you. <text:s/>It must be strange for you to find yourself back in London. <text:s/>Does it seem foreign?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Odile sends her love. We went last night to the Café Ambrose. <text:s/>It is still the same as ever. <text:s/>I was sentimental and I think Marcel was angry with me. It&apos;s hard to explain.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">If you do not want to reply to this I will understand. <text:s/>Perhaps it is for the best.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Your friend always,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P7"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">That didn&apos;t seem too bad, and she&apos;d only had to look two words up. Jane drank more wine. It was the sort of thing wine writers describe as robust. That was fine with Jane: robustness was exactly what she needed.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">She sorted carefully through the other letters, forcing herself to look only at the dates. It took her a long time but in the end she had amassed about twenty little piles of varying size. This was going to be a long job.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">I&apos;ll have to write it all down</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">, she thought. That was good because it meant she would have to buy a book to write it all down in, which meant she could postpone the rest of them for at least another day. Methodically Jane transferred the piles of letters to the floor, swilled down the last dregs of Bulgarian red, and went to bed.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane woke suddenly in what seemed to be the middle of the night. It wasn&apos;t completely dark, but then London never is. She was still confused from her dream. There had been something about a book, and a room she had to go into that contained something awful. It must have been when she opened the door that she woke up. She was dry-mouthed and sweating. Squinting at the bedside alarm she made out the time: six twenty-four. Too early to get up, too late to go back to sleep.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">She lay there and thought about Michael. Her mother would have advised her to find herself a nice ordinary man, but she&apos;d tried ordinary men and they were a waste of time. He was different, whatever else you might say about him. She was getting used to most of the weirdness and it didn&apos;t freak her out when he went off into that funny place he went to somewhere inside his head. Talking to angels was an unusual hobby, but it seemed harmless enough. The silences she found difficult were the ones where there was something to say and he wasn&apos;t saying it. There had been more and more of those lately. They weren&apos;t even having much sex, which annoyed her now that she&apos;d discovered she enjoyed it. She knew she ought to be patient, but it wasn&apos;t easy. It was a good job she could talk to Tom.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">With a shock she remembered that she had the letters and they were spread out all over the floor of her bedroom. She would have to be sure and lock the door. If Sue or Donna found them there&apos;d be no end of explanations. Donna might even turn her in to the police; virtuous people can be very difficult to live with. Even so that might be preferable to Sue finding out and telling everyone in a ten-mile radius. There was nobody she could trust on this one, not even Marcie. Especially Marcie, now she thought about it. Jane felt very cold and alone. Irrationally she wished Michael were there with her, but of course that would never do. He&apos;d never visited the flat and she hoped devoutly that it wouldn&apos;t suddenly occur to </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">him to do so. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">Let&apos;s hope the angels can keep their traps shut for once</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">, she thought. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">He mustn&apos;t ever find out about this. Well, if they&apos;re looking after him they must be on my side.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">She turned over in bed and tried to concentrate on French irregular verbs. It felt like rehearsing her lines before the first-night curtain. Jane had been in several plays at school, her finest hour having been Gertrude in </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Hamlet. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">She&apos;d always had dreadful stage-fright and this was just the same. You thought you knew how it would be, but this was the moment when you found out. This was for real.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">It was no good. She&apos;d have to read the first one at least.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Dear Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Thank you so much for your pretty card. I have put it by my bed. I would very much like to come and visit you in Cambridge. Tell me when would be best to come. You can telephone me here, it&apos;s no problem. Mme Renouf says that I can take a week off because of all the extra time I worked over Christmas. She&apos;s not being kind, she just doesn&apos;t want to pay me the extra money!</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">We went down to the sea yesterday. There was nobody there and it was like a dream. <text:s/>It was very cold but also very beautiful. You would have liked it. The sea was the colour of your eyes. I wanted to be on my own. Mama said I was being sulky. I couldn&apos;t tell her how I was feeling, not in front of everyone.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">I have been trying to read the book you lent me but it&apos;s very difficult. The names are all so strange. Do people in London really talk like that? I&apos;m sure I shall never understand them. <text:s/>You must think I&apos;m very stupid. <text:s/>The English one learns at school is very correct, not at all the way people speak in real life. I suppose it&apos;s the same with the way you were taught French. <text:s/>It&apos;s wonderful that you speak it so beautifully. You make me feel ashamed of the way I speak!</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Pauline says she is going to get married after all so my mother and father have calmed themselves. I hope it will work out for her. She&apos;s so young. I think I would like to get married and have a baby one day, but not yet! And I am only two years older than her. <text:s/>If it happened to me I would not do what she is doing. But perhaps if it did happen I would not feel the same. Who knows?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">I miss you. Am I being too bold? Well, so much the worse for that!</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Write soon,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane put the letter back in the pile and picked up the next without thinking about it. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Dear Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">I was so happy to get your letter. Pauline has been teasing me ever since it arrived. <text:s/>I don&apos;t care, <text:s/>I am happy! Will you meet the boat? I have never been to </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">England on my own before and I am afraid of getting lost. I wish I could speak English as well as you speak French. Will you teach me?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">I told Mama all about you and she made me promise to be good. Well, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">of </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">course! <text:s/>I said I will be as good as I can. I don&apos;t know how good that will be! <text:s/>I must telephone her as soon as I get to Cambridge. <text:s/>I hope that will be all right. I also promised her that I would go to Mass on Sunday. There are Catholic churches in England, <text:s/>aren&apos;t there?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">It&apos;s so hard to write anything, there are too many things I want to say all at once. I imagine you standing on the quay, and the salty wind and the sound of the gulls. I wish I was coming over tomorrow. <text:s/>But one must be patient. <text:s/>I ought to be more patient, <text:s text:c="2"/>I know. <text:s/>It isn&apos;t one of my good points. Also I am very greedy. <text:s/>I hope you are going to spoil me completely! <text:s/>In fact I know you are.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Until next week (!!),</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter">Madeleine</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">The alarm went off in its usual tactless fashion. Jane silenced it at a single blow without looking up. She ought to get up, but surely there was time for another one.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michel darling,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I have just got back and already I need to write to you! <text:s/>It was not a very nice crossing, and all the worse because it was taking me away from you. But still, here I am. Mama made a big fuss and wanted to know everything. <text:s/>I am sure she can tell what we have been doing! <text:s/>But then she knew nothing about Pauline until the baby. <text:s/>Perhaps it is not so obvious! <text:s/>But I feel so marvellous, I&apos;m sure everyone can see.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Everything seems different here. <text:s/>Spring can&apos;t have started already, surely? <text:s/>But all the colours are brighter somehow, and the birds are singing. <text:s/>I don&apos;t remember them singing before I came to visit you. I wish you could come here and see everything. <text:s/>I want to show you off to my family! <text:s/>I miss you so much. Was it only yesterday, our farewell kiss?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I must go now to Father Lautier and confess my sins(!). <text:s/>Don&apos;t worry, he&apos;s a sweet old thing, he won&apos;t be too hard on me. At least I managed to go to Mass at that funny little church. <text:s/>I don&apos;t believe in a God who thinks it is wicked to do as we have, and what&apos;s more I don&apos;t think Father Lautier does either.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Write soon, my darling.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">With love, </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Seven-fifteen and the alarm-clock on the windowsill started up. Reluctantly Jane got up, picked her way across the purloined correspondence and stopped it. Now she was out of bed she might as well get dressed and get on with the day. It wasn&apos;t going to go away.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She bought the book at lunchtime. It was large and purple with a shiny plastic cover. For good measure she bought a new pen to go with it. The young man behind the counter asked her if she was writing a novel and she said no rather more sharply than she might have done. Afterwards she felt a little sorry for him; he&apos;d seemed very young and it was a perfectly innocent remark.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane forced herself to concentrate on her work. It wasn&apos;t easy. She kept wanting to speak French to everybody. It was absurd: her spoken French had never been anything to write home about, it would have sounded awful as well as being completely inappropriate. Fortunately Marcie was on holiday so she didn&apos;t have to endure an inquisition, and she could slip off home on the dot of five-thirty.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Once again she made herself take it slowly. After a meal which she&apos;d forgotten almost before she&apos;d finished eating it, she wrote translations of the first three letters into her new book with her new pen. Her handwriting was getting worse. It looked like barbed wire. Madeleine&apos;s letters were works of art in comparison. Jane wanted to cry.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T9">Come on</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">, she told herself sternly. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T9">You wanted the truth. Live with it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michel darling,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I think I have read your letter a hundred times already! <text:s text:c="2"/>It was so lovely just to see your handwriting on the envelope, and the English stamp. I saved it up for hours before I opened it. It&apos;s such a beautiful letter. <text:s/>I shall keep it always.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">When can I see you again? I don&apos;t think I can wait until the summer, <text:s/>I shall die. <text:s/>Perhaps if I speak to Mme Renouf she will be sympathetic. But I am afraid I won&apos;t be able to make her understand. <text:s text:c="2"/>I don&apos;t know the words to speak about this. It&apos;s all so new and strange. And wonderful.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I lie awake at night thinking about you. <text:s/>I remember your caresses, your kisses, <text:s/>how you feel inside me — there: I&apos;ve said it. If that makes me wicked, I don&apos;t care. I want to hold on to every little detail. The way the morning sun lights up the pattern on the curtains in your room. The way you breathe when you are sleeping. I wish so much that you were here with me. <text:s/>I want to wake up again with your arms around me. Tell me it will be soon. The nights are long and cold and empty without you.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Do I have to write what I feel? It&apos;s such an ordinary word when everyone else says it. <text:s/>We should have a word all of our own, just for us. I&apos;ve never felt this way before. I used to be confused but now everything is so clear. It&apos;s like the sun breaking through clouds. I want to sing but also I want to keep it secret. It&apos;s a special grace that God has given only to you and me. When I went to Mass today I said a private thank-you to Him. <text:s/>I used to think that God was cold and remote and only interested in saying No. You have shown me I was wrong. God is about sunshine and happiness and the birds in the trees. It&apos;s so marvellous, I can&apos;t express it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Write to me soon, my darling. I long for you so much.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Your own Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane was feeling slightly sick. There was no Bulgarian red to hand to soften the blow this time. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">I wonder what she looks like</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">, she thought. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">I bet she&apos;s gorgeous, damn her eyes</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">. With a trembling hand she turned the page in her book and picked up the next letter.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">My dearest one,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I know I should be patient. <text:s/>You are quite right. I am saving my money and counting the days and the hours. <text:s/>I have said nothing to Mme Renouf. <text:s/>There is nothing for it but to wait. Oh, but the waiting!</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I am glad you are making good progress with your studies. I don&apos;t think I could read a whole page right through the way I feel at the moment! <text:s/>But it is important that you should do well. I am proud of you. (I would be proud of you anyway!) You are lucky to live in such a beautiful place. I often imagine what it will be like in summer. Will we be able to go on the river?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Pauline is making life impossible at the moment. One day she&apos;s choosing a dress, the next it&apos;s all off. Poor Mama is going insane. Personally I think she&apos;s too young to get married. <text:s/>It would never have occurred to anyone if she weren&apos;t pregnant — certainly not to Jean-Paul. He&apos;s only a boy himself. One can only hope and pray that it turns out for the best. <text:s/>I know I shall miss Pauline dreadfully, even though we fight and argue all the time. She&apos;s so unhappy at the moment, it&apos;s hard for me to bear. I wish I could give her just a drop of the ocean of happiness inside me. But she won&apos;t speak to me. She&apos;s not speaking to anyone at the moment: she had yet another row with Mama and went off to her room. Mama was crying. I didn&apos;t know what to do. She hates it when people see her crying, she&apos;s so proud. She&apos;s tried so hard to bring us up properly. Father is no use at all. He pretends nothing is happening and sits there and reads the newspaper. I wonder sometimes what she ever saw in him.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">It&apos;s all so different for us, darling. There are no questions, no doubts. I could certainly never imagine treating you the way Pauline treats Jean-</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Paul. The poor boy doesn&apos;t know where he is from one moment to the next. But you know, don&apos;t you, that you are always in my inmost heart?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I must stop writing or I&apos;ll start to cry. Write again soon. I miss you so much.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">A thousand kisses, </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">your Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane turned the page and picked up the next letter. It was easier if she pretended that they were addressed to someone other than Michael, some person she&apos;d never met, and this was just a piece of French homework. Looked at in that light it was almost pleasant. It was certainly more interesting than Marie-Claire wanting to know the price of carrots.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">My dearest,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I&apos;m so excited! As soon as I got your letter I spoke to Mama. Poor Mama, she&apos;s wearing away to a shadow. I think I rather frightened her. But — I can hardly believe it myself — she said yes!! Of course you will have to sleep in Pauline&apos;s room and Pauline will be sharing with me. That&apos;s the official story anyway. I am sure we can come to some arrangement!</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I had to speak to Father and explain about you. He was terribly pompous and made a big speech about morals. I told him you were a brilliant student at Cambridge and sure to be very rich one day. Sure enough, that shut him up! <text:s/>But in his eyes almost anyone would shine compared to Jean-Paul. He can&apos;t bear the sight of the poor boy. <text:s/>I don&apos;t know why everyone is so against him. It&apos;s true he&apos;s young and doesn&apos;t have much money, but he cares for Pauline, which is the important thing, <text:s/>don&apos;t you think? <text:s text:c="2"/>I try to be kind to him, since nobody else is. My heart is so full, I can afford to be generous.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">There are so many places I want to take you to see and people I want you to meet. We shall never have time for a quarter of it, I know. But it will be enough for me just to see you again and hold you close.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Counting the hours, </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">There was a gap of a few weeks after that one. Things had evidently taken a turn for the worse and Jane could not repress a quiet feline satisfaction.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michel darling,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">It&apos;s so awful here without you. <text:s/>I&apos;m going out of my mind. <text:s/>There has been nothing but rows and shouting and tears. <text:s/>You know how I hate shouting. <text:s/>When we are not all arguing with one another we say absolutely nothing and the house is like a tomb.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jean-Paul said he wouldn&apos;t marry Pauline after all. I thought it was very brave of him to say it right out in front of everyone like that and in my opinion he&apos;s quite right. <text:s/>They&apos;re far too young. <text:s/>My father went crazy. <text:s/>I thought he was going to have a fit. I can&apos;t begin to tell you half the things he said, or rather yelled. <text:s/>My mother was in tears. <text:s/>Pauline was the calmest person there, <text:s/>although she was very pale. <text:s/>I think she knew it was coming. <text:s/>Jean-Paul was as red as a beetroot but he wouldn&apos;t change his mind. My father threatened to have him arrested, I can&apos;t imagine on what charge. At any rate Jean-Paul has been banned from the house forever and I&apos;m sure it&apos;s nothing but a relief to him. <text:s/>He&apos;s never been comfortable here, <text:s/>and who can blame him? <text:s/>Poor boy.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">So that was one thing. <text:s/>Then my father got it into his head that you were just the same. <text:s/>He started sounding off about improvident young men and how he wouldn&apos;t stand for his daughters being ruined, on and on until I couldn&apos;t bear it any longer. <text:s text:c="2"/>I had to stand up for you, <text:s/>Michel. <text:s/>I said — well, <text:s text:c="2"/>it doesn&apos;t matter what I said. <text:s/>The fact is we had a blazing row in front of Jean-Paul and everyone. <text:s/>He said I wasn&apos;t to have anything more to do with you, <text:s/>as if you weren&apos;t more precious to me </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">than the air I breathe. I can&apos;t live without you, <text:s/>and I told him so. <text:s/>He was so angry. <text:s/>I&apos;ve never seen him so angry. <text:s/>I thought he was going to hit me and he&apos;s never done that in my life. As for me, <text:s text:c="2"/>I was on fire. <text:s/>I wanted to rush out of the house and go straight to you, <text:s/>just as I was. Of course I didn&apos;t. <text:s/>I went for a long walk down by the river and calmed down a bit. When I got home everything was quiet, <text:s/>like a deathbed. <text:s/>Mama was like a ghost. <text:s/>Pauline had locked herself in her room. As for my father, <text:s/>he&apos;d gone out for a drink. <text:s/>No doubt he&apos;ll be complaining to the whole town about me.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T7">I wish they understood what you are really like and how things are between us. They&apos;d be so happy, I&apos;m sure. <text:s/>I know they only want what&apos;s best for me. If only they could see that what&apos;s best for me is you, my darling. <text:s text:c="2"/>I shall pray for them on Sunday.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T7">If you were here, <text:s text:c="2"/>everything would be all right. In your arms I can forget about everything else. There&apos;s only you and me and nothing else matters. Please write to me soon. <text:s/>I need to feel your strength.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Your Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane turned another page, picked up another envelope. It got better.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michel my dearest,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I could kill my father. <text:s/>This morning your letter arrived and he tore it up in front of my eyes. Just like that! <text:s/>He said I was to write and tell you it was all over between us. <text:s/>How could I ever do that? It will never be over. <text:s/>He was so self-righteous and bombastic. What business is it of his? <text:s/>Even Mama was shocked. <text:s/>If he goes on like this I shall have to move out, <text:s text:c="2"/>it&apos;s unbearable. <text:s/>Even telling you about it makes me want to take a knife and stab him a thousand times. <text:s text:c="2"/>I&apos;m so furious I&apos;m shaking.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">You&apos;d better write to me care of the café. <text:s/>You know the address. <text:s/>I&apos;ll have a word with Mme Renouf, I&apos;m sure she&apos;ll understand. <text:s/>Perhaps she may know of a cheap room somewhere. <text:s/>I can&apos;t go on like this, that&apos;s for certain.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I must go to Father Lautier at once and confess my sins. <text:s/>God is with us, <text:s text:c="2"/>I <text:s/>know: <text:s/>He won&apos;t let us be parted like this. <text:s/>It&apos;s not right.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Please, my darling, write at once before my heart breaks into pieces.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Your Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">Right on, Dad</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">, Jane thought. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">More power to your elbow</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I spoke to Mme Renouf last night and she says I can stay with her for a little while. <text:s/>She&apos;s a wonderful woman: <text:s/>she understands everything. We talked for hours. <text:s/>She told me about how difficult it was when she met her husband — his parents thought she was a </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">gold-digger, only interested in getting her hands on the café. <text:s/>They had to meet in secret for a long time, then as soon as he was of age they married in </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">secret too and announced it to the family as a </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style45"><text:span text:style-name="T6">fait accompli. <text:s/></text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">It sounds very romantic. <text:s/>But it was a sad story in the end because when they had only been married a short time he fell ill and she nursed him for years and years, and then in the end he died. Anyway, that&apos;s why she has such a soft spot for us.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">There was another shouting match when I told my parents I was leaving. <text:s/>Pauline understands: <text:s text:c="2"/>I think she is even happy for me, as far as she can be happy under these circumstances. <text:s/>She is the one I will miss most. Mama said very little but she looked terrible. <text:s/>It&apos;s only a matter of a few kilometres: you&apos;d think I was going off to the North Pole. <text:s text:c="2"/>I won&apos;t even be all by myself.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Please, <text:s/>please, <text:s/>come and visit soon if you possibly can. <text:s/>I simply don&apos;t have the money to come to England again. <text:s/>If I did, <text:s/>I&apos;d already be there, believe me. <text:s/>More than anything in the world I want to be with you. My heart and soul and my whole body long for you.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I send you a thousand kisses.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Now there was another gap. The next letter was also dated from the café, however, so there had evidently been no reconciliation with the family.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I cried and cried after you had gone. <text:s/>The world is so empty without you, and yet a few hours ago it was so full of joy and love and beauty. <text:s/>I wish we could be together always. Of course I know you must complete your studies, <text:s text:c="2"/>I understand that. <text:s/>With God&apos;s help I will get through the next few months somehow. But it is so hard just at this moment.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I went and had a talk with Father Lautier. <text:s/>He is a very wise and good man, and I know I can trust him. He&apos;s known me my whole life. <text:s/>I told him all about the troubles in my family. Of course he already knew a good deal of it; there&apos;s not much goes on around here that escapes him. <text:s/>He advised me to be patient </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">and to trust in God. We prayed together and afterwards I felt a little better.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">It&apos;s my faith which really keeps me going. <text:s/>And yet before I met you I hardly believed at all. <text:s/>I went to church because it was something one did; we were simply brought up that way. In my daily life I never really thought of God. <text:s/>He was just there in the background somewhere, like the weather. Through you I have come to know God much better, and to love Him too. That&apos;s why I can&apos;t believe that we have sinned, whatever the Church might say about it. <text:s/>When we make love it is for me something holy, a glimpse of Heaven. Don&apos;t laugh at me: I&apos;m quite serious. I really believe that this is something we have been blessed with by God.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Pauline is enormous now. <text:s/>I saw her as I came back from church and she looked so ill. <text:s/>She says she has been sick every day for weeks. <text:s/>Mama must be so worried about her. <text:s/>She said that when the baby comes she wants me to be there. <text:s/>I cried and I hugged her, and she cried too, and a pretty picture we must have made there at the church gate! <text:s/>I didn&apos;t ask her if she&apos;d heard from Jean-Paul but I don&apos;t </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">think so. There was no happiness in her. She was so quiet, it isn&apos;t like her at all. <text:s/>I hope it will be all right. I shall pray for her.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">There&apos;s no need for me to say once again how much I miss you. <text:s/>I know it&apos;s hard for you too. <text:s/>I will never forget these last few days together. Truly I am a different person when I am with you. All my worries fall away and I can laugh and be at peace. <text:s/>I am so lucky, so blessed. <text:s/>I shall kiss this letter, as the next best thing to kissing you.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Always, your Madeleine.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane was puzzled. The girl was turning into some sort of religious maniac. Michael might be a bit peculiar but she hardly imagined that that kind of thing would appeal to him. Still, he&apos;d kept the letters: they must mean something. She started the next one.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">So, I am an auntie now!! Pauline had the most beautiful little baby girl this morning at six o&apos;clock and we are all exhausted. She will be called Justine, after our mother. The contractions came on suddenly late last night and there was no time to take her to the hospital, so they called out Dr Poussy and he delivered her at home. I was with her the whole time. It was the most incredible, indescribable thing I have ever witnessed. <text:s/>It truly is a miracle. Pauline was so brave. She held my hand so tightly I thought she would break something. I can&apos;t imagine what it must be like. Will I ever have the courage to go through that!? <text:s/>But when it was all over and she was holding little Justine for the first time, she looked so beautiful, <text:s text:c="2"/>so happy and peaceful that I wanted to cry. I was so proud of her. My little sister, a mother! Isn&apos;t it wonderful?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Mama is completely in love with her new granddaughter. I haven&apos;t seen her smile like that for a long, long time. She looks ten years younger. When Pauline and the baby had gone to sleep, Mama and I embraced. There was no need to say anything. <text:s/>We are a family once again, or we would be except for my pig of a father. He didn&apos;t even get out of bed. I can&apos;t believe how cruel he is being to Pauline. If he thought he could get away with it he&apos;d throw her out of the house, but of course Mama would never let him.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I must get some sleep now, I can hardly keep my eyes open but I had to tell you the news. I&apos;ll write again soon.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">was as good as her word, the next letter being dated the following day.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Well, my father has finally deigned to acknowledge his grandchild. <text:s/>In spite of himself I think he&apos;s charmed by her. <text:s/>She&apos;s irresistible. I&apos;m sure he&apos;ll come round in the end. <text:s/>He&apos;s even been reasonably polite to me, even though we hadn&apos;t spoken a word since I moved out. Justine is being very good. She sleeps most of the time. I </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">can&apos;t get over how tiny and how perfect she is. When Pauline feeds her they make the most exquisite picture. I have never seen my sister so happy.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I am staying here for a few days to help Mama out. I forgot to tell you that Pauline has moved into what used to be my bedroom, so I am sleeping in the room where you stayed when you first came here. Sweet memories!</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I wonder if anyone has bothered to tell Jean-Paul that he is now the father of a beautiful baby girl? I don&apos;t want to interfere in other people&apos;s business, but I do think he ought to know. You&apos;d want to know if it was you, wouldn&apos;t you? He must realise that it was due, of course. The poor girl&apos;s been like a Zeppelin for weeks. I wonder how he&apos;ll take the news? <text:s/>It&apos;s a big thing for him to have to cope with at his age. <text:s text:c="2"/>(Goodness, don&apos;t I sound grown-up?) But I&apos;m sure he&apos;d like to see her. I hope my father lets him.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Pauline is taking to motherhood quite naturally. It amazes me. <text:s text:c="2"/>I would have said she was the last person on earth to take an interest in babies. Is it the same for all women, I wonder? I confess I haven&apos;t felt the urge myself as yet, but perhaps one day I shall feel differently. Certainly one can&apos;t look at Justine without being completely besotted with her. But the thought of it is absolutely terrifying. I don&apos;t just mean the pain, but the responsibility is so enormous: to bring another soul into this world. Pauline&apos;s life will never be the same again after this. It&apos;s quite a thought.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Naturally I wish you were here to see little Justine, but I must cultivate patience. Work hard, my love, and pass your exams, and we shall be together soon. You know you are always in my thoughts and in my heart.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">With love,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Tante(!) Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane looked at the bedside clock and was alarmed to see how late it was. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">Better call it a night</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">, she thought. She put the letter back in its place, closed her book, and went to clean her teeth. She was no further forward than when she&apos;d started.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">7</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">When the airmail letter came, Tom almost opened it thinking it was from Anna. Then he noticed the return address was French. He left it on the kitchen table, together with the gas bill, and went out to get a newspaper. When he came back the letter had gone, and so had Michael.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">He wasn&apos;t worried to begin with. Michael was an odd and solitary person, and quite often wandered off to be on his own; he always turned up in the end. As soon as Tom&apos;s momentary disappointment passed he forgot about the letter. He was still campaigning to persuade Anna to come to London and had got as far as an agreement in principle. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">The trouble with lawyers,</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> he thought, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">is that they always have to argue about everything. It&apos;s habit as much as anything.</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> He was reluctantly approaching the conclusion that Anna was more trouble than she was worth.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane phoned, and he promised to tell Michael she&apos;d called. He tried to get her advice about Anna but she said she was in a hurry and rang off. This was another mild disappointment. Tom had hoped she might be able to give him some insight into the female mind, a subject he had always found deeply mysterious in spite of having three sisters.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michael didn&apos;t surface at any point during the weekend, but this wasn&apos;t particularly unusual. Admittedly since meeting Jane he seemed to have become much less erratic, but then the whole Jane thing was going through a sticky patch. Tom made it a rule to steer well clear of sticky patches as far as possible, his own and other people&apos;s. He did know that Jane was unhappy, and he was sorry about that since he liked her and thought that on the whole she was very good for Michael. However, Tom had enough sense to realise that the role of relationship counsellor was not one to which he was naturally suited.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">A couple more days went by without any evidence of Michael. It was easy enough to spot this because nobody did the washing-up. Tom put his head round Michael&apos;s bedroom door once or twice, but there was no sign of him. By now even Tom was beginning to get seriously uneasy. Jane phoned two or three times. They both colluded in a transparent pretence that there was nothing to worry about. They each knew that the other was worried sick.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">It hadn&apos;t happened for a long time, but it was just possible that Michael had gone on one of his benders. Tom himself liked a drink as much as the next man, if not as much as the next several men, but when Michael was on the rampage his capacity for alcohol was awe-inspiring. Apart from the sheer quantity he drank, it was the vicious and relentless pace that was impressive. It was as if he had some deep personal grudge against his liver. The first time Tom had witnessed this behaviour was at university, and even he had thought Michael was going to do himself serious injury. Somehow he never did. He wasn&apos;t a loud or obnoxious drunk: he was the silent, embittered type. The more he drank the less he said, until eventually </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">he was completely comatose. Curiously enough he never seemed to have much of a hangover when he eventually came round again.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">If Michael was off on one, logic suggested that he would be found in a pub somewhere. London, however, contains a lot of pubs, and he could be anywhere by now. Maybe in a police cell. Maybe in hospital. Maybe on a mortuary slab, although Tom skated round that possibility. There was no telling. All he could do, really, was wait.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Another airmail letter arrived. This time it was from Anna, finally agreeing to come and stay on condition that he made a return visit to her parents&apos; house in Winterthur. Tom had no idea where Winterthur might be but he was ready to agree anyway. Life was too short to argue with Anna.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane rang yet again.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Still no sign,&quot; Tom admitted glumly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Something must have happened. He can&apos;t just have disappeared for no reason.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Maybe he&apos;s been abducted by aliens.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane sighed. &quot;Wouldn&apos;t put it past him.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;No.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Have you noticed anything unusual, out of the ordinary? Was he in a mood?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;He&apos;s always in a mood these days. You should know.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Tom, I&apos;m really worried about him.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">It was at this point that Tom remembered. &quot;There was one thing.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;What?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Saturday morning he got a letter. Airmail.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane was onto it at once. &quot;Airmail? Where from?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;France.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;What was the handwriting like?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;God, I don&apos;t remember. Girly.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Would you recognise it if you saw it again?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I don&apos;t know. Maybe. Why?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Stay right where you are. I&apos;m coming over.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">When Jane arrived he was on the phone to Anna and he had to spend several minutes conducting a three-way conversation in a mixture of English, German and sign-language so that he could say hello to Jane without giving the wrong idea to Anna. He didn&apos;t know for certain whether Hell had no fury like a Swiss woman lawyer scorned, but he didn&apos;t intend to risk it. It was with some relief that he finally put the phone down. Jane was waving an envelope at him.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Is this the same handwriting?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He took the envelope from her and peered at it vaguely. &quot;Could be.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Yes or no?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Christ, Jane, you&apos;re worse than Anna.&quot; He looked at it again, then back at her steely eyes. When exactly had she turned into Perry Mason? &quot;All right, yes. Probably. I didn&apos;t pay that much attention to it. It wasn&apos;t my letter.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane sat down heavily. &quot;Shit.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Do you want a drink?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Several.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;What would you like?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Alcohol.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Tom poured them each a hefty glass of red wine. It wasn&apos;t Bulgarian but it still had a kick. They drank for a minute or two in silence.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;You know who it is, then?&quot; he asked eventually. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Haven&apos;t you guessed?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Oh, shit.&quot; Their eyes met. &quot;Madeleine.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Madeleine,&quot; she confirmed hopelessly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">There was another pause for refreshment. Tom refilled their glasses from the bottle he had thoughtfully brought in from the kitchen. He had realised as soon as he saw her that this was no time for half-measures.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;So he&apos;s told you about Madeleine,&quot; he ventured.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Not exactly.&quot; Jane was blushing. He thought the effect was rather fetching, but this wasn&apos;t the time to mention it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;So he hasn&apos;t told you about Madeleine.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;No.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Tom considered this enigma for a while, &quot;</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">I</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> never told you about Madeleine, did I?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;No.&quot; Jane was already helping herself to more wine. Her hand was shaking and she spilt a little onto her trousers.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;So.&quot; Tom didn&apos;t really know how to go on from there, so he stopped.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I stole them,&quot; she said suddenly. &quot;The letters.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What letters?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;The letters from Madeleine.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;They were under his bed. I found them when I was cleaning. I hid them under my laundry and took them home.&quot; Her cheeks were wet. &quot;I&apos;ve been reading them ever since. They&apos;re in French.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;That explains the envelope.&quot; Tom was glad to find that something was explained somehow.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You won&apos;t tell him, will you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;No, of course not.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;He&apos;ll never forgive me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Shush, don&apos;t worry, I won&apos;t tell him. Scout&apos;s honour.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She sat and cried silently for a while. Tom always felt helpless in these situations. All he could do was wait for her to stop, which she did eventually. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;m sorry,&quot; she said. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Don&apos;t worry about it. You all right?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;m fine. Really.&quot; She didn&apos;t look at all fine, but he decided not to push it. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;How much do you know?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane took a purple book out of her shoulder-bag. &quot;It&apos;s all in there. My translations. Sorry about the handwriting.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Tom took the book uncertainly, opened it, and began to read.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Thank you so much for your beautiful letter. <text:s/>I read some of it out to Pauline, the part about her and Justine, and she says to thank you from both of them. You are a very special man. I wish Pauline had someone like you for herself, to take care of her and her baby. Oh, but I am not so self-sacrificing as to give you up! I want you to myself. Is that greedy of me?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Tomorrow I shall be going back to Mme Renouf&apos;s. I think Father has forgiven Pauline — what is there to forgive, after all? — but he&apos;s still being stubborn about you. <text:s/>So long as he has that attitude I can&apos;t live under his roof. All the same it has been good to be </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style45"><text:span text:style-name="T12">en famille</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style45"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">for a little while. <text:s/>Mama seems much happier. Who would not be, with a darling granddaughter like Justine?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I have been thinking a lot about what you said in your letter about the future. For me the present has always been enough. When I am with you, I am with you and that&apos;s all that matters. When you are not here, I remember being with you or look forward to the next time. Our next meeting is the furthest horizon of my life. Is it really possible that we could have the rest of our lives together? When I think of marriage, I look at Mama and my father and I think No, that isn&apos;t for me. <text:s/>But perhaps it would not be like that for us? I don&apos;t know. I am learning a lot about life. When I see Pauline and her baby I can sometimes imagine that it was me. I&apos;m not sure how that makes me feel, though. I know that you would love our baby and take good care of her, and of me. Is that what I want? One day, perhaps. But I get the feeling from what you wrote that it&apos;s what you want, and that frightens me a little. We are still young, my darling. Let&apos;s not rush things.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">We&apos;ll speak of this when we are together next. It&apos;s too complicated to write down in a letter. I worry that I will put things clumsily and give the wrong impression, and I can&apos;t bear the thought of any misunderstanding between us. Also I worry about your examinations, which I know will be soon. Don&apos;t let this distract you. When you come back we will have a long talk.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Oh, what an earnest and serious letter this is! Really you must know that I am not worried in the least. I have a beautiful niece and in a few weeks I shall see my handsome lover again. God is good to us, don&apos;t you agree?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">With a thousand kisses, </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Your Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Where have you got to?&quot; Jane asked impatiently. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Sorry I&apos;m being slow. It&apos;s your writing.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">“Get used to it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Tom looked at her thoughtfully. &quot;Are you sure we should be reading this stuff?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Not at all sure. But it might help us understand what Michael&apos;s going through.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">He sighed and turned the page.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I shan&apos;t wish you the best of luck, because I know you don&apos;t need it, you clever boy! All the same I lit a candle for you on Sunday. Am I silly and superstitious? Still, it can&apos;t do any harm. You know that my thoughts and love are with you. Pauline sends her love as well.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I&apos;ll keep this short because I know you must be busy. Write to me when the exams are over, but not before. (You see, I am learning some patience!) I cannot imagine why God has blessed me with such a lovely, kind, brilliant man. Now show the world!</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Blessings, </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Your Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">That was the last letter for several months. Then there followed:</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I have got so used to having you here that I have become quite spoilt. I couldn&apos;t eat breakfast this morning because you weren&apos;t here to share it. I ought to be grateful for these last few weeks, and believe me I am, but it doesn&apos;t make our separation any easier. Such a greedy girl I am!</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Why must you go to London? I detest big cities. Well, I know, there are good practical reasons for it, but I wish you could get a job here. (Maybe here in the café? Odile is always looking for a </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style45"><text:span text:style-name="T12">plongeur</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style45"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">— only joking!) But as you say there are more openings in the city. If Father were at all reasonable I&apos;m sure he could find you something in the business, but he won&apos;t hear of it. At least he&apos;s condescended to be civil to you, that&apos;s something. I suppose I can&apos;t expect the whole world to love you as I do.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I worry about how we shall manage with you there and me here. <text:s/>If you have money then I suppose it will be possible for you to travel back and forth but it will be hard for you. I wish I were brave enough to come and live with you in London, but my English is so bad and London is such a big and frightening place. You haven&apos;t complained about it, I know, but it&apos;s pure cowardice on my part and I must admit it. I shall pray for courage.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Life goes on here, even without you. Justine&apos;s cough is better now. Pauline is so relieved, even though we all told her it was nothing to worry about. She is so completely absorbed in that child. I can hardly believe it. She never used to be able to concentrate on a single thing for ten minutes at a time. Motherhood has changed her completely. I wonder what it would do to me? But we&apos;ve had that conversation already.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Marcel is back from his trip to Africa. He&apos;s so brown, it&apos;s as if he&apos;s been bathing in coffee. He&apos;s been telling me all sorts of stories about the wonderful things he saw. I&apos;m not sure if all of them are true, mind! He always was a storyteller. He has a stack of photographs to be developed, and then we shall see.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Danni says that Jean-Paul has gone to live in Toulouse. <text:s/>He has a job in a car factory there. I hope everything goes well for him. He&apos;s not a bad boy. I rather think Danni was a bit disappointed as she fancied him for herself, but I think it&apos;s a case of &quot;once bitten, twice shy&quot; as the English say. (You see, I am learning something!) She&apos;s so pretty she could have anyone she liked, but we always want what we can&apos;t have, don&apos;t we? Just as I want to have you here with me now.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between">Jane was starting to wish there was a list of characters. Still, Madeleine could hardly be expected to explain who all these people might be, when presumably Michael already knew them.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">The letter concluded:</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Well, writing it down won&apos;t make it happen. I hope you find a wonderful job soon and you can come and tell me all about it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Your Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">But then only a few days later:</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I wish you were somewhere I could telephone you. I am going out of my mind with worry. Can you call me here as soon as you get this?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I haven&apos;t told you this but I haven&apos;t been myself for a few days now and my period was very late. So today I finally made my mind up to go and see Dr Poussy and he did a test. It was positive. Michel, I am going to have your baby. I have never been so terrified.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Nobody knows except Odile. I had to tell someone. She has been so kind to me. Michel, I need you here, now. I can&apos;t face this on my own. What my parents will say I can&apos;t imagine. <text:s/>How did this happen? We were so careful. Is it a punishment from God?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I can&apos;t write any more. For God&apos;s sake call me. Even to hear your voice will give me strength.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What a thing to get in the mail,&quot; Tom observed. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Did you know about this?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I sort of worked it out. You know what he&apos;s like. Doesn&apos;t give much away.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;d noticed.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I have been praying so hard but I think God has forgotten me. <text:s/>I spoke to Father Lautier and he said I had to tell my parents. <text:s/>I can&apos;t, I simply can&apos;t. Mama will die. As for my father — I daren&apos;t even think about it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I don&apos;t know what we&apos;re going to do. <text:s/>You still have no job, <text:s text:c="2"/>and you&apos;re so far away. Is this what you wanted? I am so alone. I have never been so alone. There is this thing inside me like a cancer. Perhaps it will kill me. How can you leave me alone like this? You who say that you love me. I am so frightened, Michel. I am not ready for this, it&apos;s too soon, too big. Everything will change now. I didn&apos;t want this, not yet. It wasn&apos;t supposed to happen this way.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Perhaps I took my happiness for granted and God has withdrawn it as a punishment. I know I have been greedy and selfish. But I can&apos;t bear this, Michel. I&apos;m not brave and strong like Pauline. I don&apos;t have her gift for love. You don&apos;t realise what an immense, all-absorbing thing a baby is. There were so many things I wanted to do with my life, and now I shan&apos;t get the chance because there will be this baby in the way, demanding everything from me. Pauline hardly sleeps at all, do you know that?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Every moment of the day and night she is a hostage. That&apos;s the next twenty years of her life, at least. Can you imagine that? <text:s/>Can you imagine how I feel about it?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I&apos;m so confused, so unhappy. I blame myself, I blame you, I blame God. Odile says I can stay here and not to worry about the rent. She&apos;s a darling.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Call me soon. I need to hear your voice. Tell me I&apos;m not alone.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P4"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Thank you again for calling. I&apos;m sorry I cried so much. I feel as if I am wandering all alone in a strange place on a dark moonless night, and you are the only star that I can see.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I took your advice and spoke to Pauline. We both cried but afterwards it felt better. She understands everything without even having to be told. What a rock she is. She&apos;s grown up so much in these last few months, I feel as if I am the younger sister and she is the wise older one. She has promised to be there for me if the baby comes when you are away. I don&apos;t know if I want you there or not. It&apos;s a hard thing to watch someone you love go through, Michel.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Odile is like a mother hen, fussing over me the whole time. <text:s/>She makes me laugh. I told her I can still wait at table, the baby won&apos;t even be showing for weeks yet, but she&apos;s such a worrier. I think I&apos;ve become the daughter she never had. It&apos;s nice to be spoiled, though. Anyway, I insisted on working as usual. If I&apos;m not there people will notice, and it&apos;s bound to get back to my parents, and then they&apos;ll want to know what&apos;s up. To tell you the truth, now that I know what it is I don&apos;t feel ill at all. I feel </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">different, but not ill. I can&apos;t explain it. Pauline said that she knew the instant she was pregnant. <text:s/>If it ever happens to me again (God forbid!) I&apos;m sure I&apos;ll know.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">You mustn&apos;t fret too much about me, Michel. I am being well looked after. One way or another we will get through this. <text:s/>Every day I say a prayer for us and for the baby. So long as we love one another, it will work out.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">With all my love, </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T8"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">8</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">He could perfectly well have flown over, but Michael took the ferry. He needed time to think. It still had that feeling of adventure: going overseas in the literal sense, passing into another world. The sea wind was real and abrasive, stimulating. It was something he had forgotten he had missed.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She met him off the boat in a beaten-up 2CV that he could barely fold himself into.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It&apos;s Odile&apos;s,&quot; she explained. &quot;If I don&apos;t get it back in one piece she&apos;ll kill me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;How&apos;s Marcel?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;How do you think?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She concentrated on driving the car. Although the engine was small it was loud enough to make conversation difficult. That and the flimsiness of the car made him think of flying in one of the old biplanes. He was glad he hadn&apos;t brought much luggage: they might never have made it out of the car-park. Michael watched her driving, her face set, her intense eyes flicking to the mirror, back to the road. She left the main road at her first opportunity, and he was soon completely lost amongst the high hedges and the twisting lanes.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">At the café Odile was there to meet them. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">My God, she&apos;s aged</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">, thought Michael. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">I wonder if that&apos;s been sudden</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">. They all had coffee. Nobody said much.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Marcel went out,&quot; Odile said. &quot;Said he&apos;d be back later.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;How is he?&quot; Michael asked. Odile shrugged.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Do you want to unpack?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Later will do. There isn&apos;t much.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Odile gave him a spare key and went out front to open up. They sat in silence. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Thank you for letting me know,&quot; he said at last, formally. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You had a right to be told.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It was a shock.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Yes. It must have been.&quot; She was very controlled, very pale. He guessed she hadn&apos;t been sleeping much. She looked very thin but he didn&apos;t know what was normal for her these days.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;How are the family?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Awful.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;And you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She looked away from him. &quot;I can&apos;t begin to tell you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">There was another silence. Michael touched her hand lightly and she drew away from him as if burned. She was determined to shut him out as completely as possible. The effort was visible in the tightness of her throat and the set of her shoulders.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;d better go up, sort the room out,&quot; he said. &quot;I&apos;ll see you later.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I miss you every day — I suppose I should say we miss you. It must be so hard for you, all alone in that enormous jungle of London. <text:s/>Don&apos;t be too disappointed about your interview. I&apos;m sure there will be other opportunities. Someone will surely want to gobble you up soon, you&apos;re so clever and wonderful in every way. But perhaps I am biased? (Joking!)</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Odile says there is a flat going over the </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T12">pâtisserie</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> across the street from Danni&apos;s house, you know the one? I might go over and have a look at it sometime. It belongs to M. Auber who was an old friend of her husband, he comes in here now and again. Of course it&apos;s early and everything might change, but we shall need somewhere. Odile hardly has room for us and a baby too. Anyway there&apos;s no harm in taking a look.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I went to visit Pauline yesterday. I can&apos;t think what I should do without her. Mama cooked us all a splendid lunch and Father was quite nice to me, by his standards. I think being a grandpa is growing on him. In a few weeks he will be an absolute slave to Justine, you&apos;ll see. She is so like her mother. Isn&apos;t it strange how babies can show a resemblance even when they&apos;re so tiny? <text:s/>Mama showed me some old photos of Pauline at the same age and they are practically identical. <text:s/>It&apos;s probably just as well she takes after her mother and not Jean-Paul.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">If you don&apos;t come and rescue me soon I shall be as fat as a pig. Odile keeps trying to make me eat the whole time, she&apos;s worse than Mama. She says that I&apos;m eating for two now but I&apos;m sure she gives me enough for three. If anything I have less of an appetite than I did before, but there&apos;s no reasoning with her. Well, at least you don&apos;t have to worry about me starving to death.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">As for you, are you looking after yourself properly? I know London is an expensive place and you don&apos;t have much money, but you must eat. I shall want you fit and strong for when you have to do all the housework! And for other things as well(!).</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Write soon, and good luck. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Your Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">The room was just the way he remembered it; the pale blue curtains, the sloping, out-of-kilter walls. Even the dusty aspidistra was the same, or perhaps a little taller. He lay on the bed, making imaginary maps out of the cracks in the ceiling, letting the spirit of the place take hold of him. In some ways he had never really left this room. He had been happy here and yet he had rarely thought about it since without a deep and crippling grief.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">He did not know yet how he felt about this. It hadn&apos;t sunk in at all. He had assumed for so long that this chapter of his life was closed for ever and yet here he was. All he knew was that he had to be here. How he felt was a side-issue: he wasn&apos;t here for himself.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michael got up, opened his bag, and began distributing his few belongings in the old familiar places. The wardrobe still had that slight smell of mothballs. His stomach was beginning to wonder about lunch. It would be all right. It would have to be all right.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">You will say I am a worrier and not to be silly, but it&apos;s nearly a week now and I haven&apos;t heard from you. Are you all right? Are you ill? <text:s/>Please just write a line and tell me how you are. <text:s/>You know my thoughts and prayers are with you always.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">There is nothing much new to tell you. Danni has got a new boyfriend, another Jean-Paul if you can believe it. <text:s/>I don&apos;t think it will last. He&apos;s very possessive about her and she can&apos;t stand that. Still, he is very good-looking and he seems to have money. Marcel is terribly jealous — you know he and Danni were an item once? —but he won&apos;t admit it. Typical man!</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Odile and I went to look at that flat I told you about. It&apos;s not very big but I suppose we could manage. M. Auber is prepared to knock a bit off the rent for us, for the sake of Odile, which is kind of him. Still, we can&apos;t make any decisions until things are more settled. I&apos;m being impatient again, aren&apos;t I? But it&apos;s natural for a woman in my condition to be anxious about the future.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Please write to me soon, my darling. Better still, call. I wish so much that you were here with me.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">A thousand kisses, </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Your Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Please don&apos;t be angry with me, but I have a confession to make. <text:s/>Pauline and I have been conspiring to bring Father round and now I think we have succeeded. The wonderful thing is he thinks it was all his own idea! Of course Mama saw what was going on at once, but she was on our side so that was all right.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Anyway the news is that Father wants to offer you a job as export manager, whatever that is. It sounds very grand. He&apos;s been saying for a long time they need to </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">get into the English market but he could never find anyone around here who knew the language well enough. All we had to do really was to keep pointing out how perfect you would be. It took him forever to take the hint: I don&apos;t know if he was being stupid or just stubborn. Anyway, after lunch today he made his big announcement and we all had to pretend to be surprised. <text:s/>Naturally he wants to have a proper talk with you and explain all about it. When can you come? Soon, I hope.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I hope you don&apos;t think I was too presumptuous, but you didn&apos;t seem to be having much luck in London and it would be so much better if we could be together here, don&apos;t you agree? Now that Father has finally seen sense things will be much easier all round. You&apos;ll see: everything will work out.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Looking forward to seeing you very soon, </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Your Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I&apos;m so, so sorry. After we talked last night I cried for hours. <text:s/>You are quite right, I know. I shouldn&apos;t have done it without telling you. I wanted it to be a surprise. I thought you&apos;d be pleased. Well: I was a fool, I admit it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">What hurt most was that you said I didn&apos;t respect you. I do: <text:s/>I respect you more than anyone in the world. It&apos;s not that I don&apos;t think you can find a job on your own, not at all. I have perfect faith in you. I am impatient: it&apos;s a great fault in me, and I try so hard to correct it, but it always seems to break out again.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michel, I never thought for a moment that you would fail me. I know that what is between us is absolute and will endure our whole lives; nothing can break it, not even death. You did not go to London to escape from me, I know that. On the contrary it was for my sake — for our sake. I should have talked it over with you first, I quite see that now. I have put you in a very difficult position, but you must understand that that was never my intention. You do understand that, don&apos;t you? I was trying to find a solution to our difficulties, not add to them.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">If you want me to I will explain things to Father. I will take the blame on myself. I would rather die than have him think badly of you because of this.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Please, my darling, forgive me for my stupidity and impatience, for that&apos;s what it was. I can&apos;t live without your forgiveness and your love. Every moment until I hear from you will be like a week.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Your Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I took your letter to Father, as you asked me. He read it through twice while I stood there trembling like a schoolgirl. <text:s/>He said nothing for a long time and I thought </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I was going to faint. At last he nodded and said, &quot;Very well: in a month&apos;s time.&quot; He wasn&apos;t pleased about it but at least he didn&apos;t go off into one of his speeches. So perhaps I haven&apos;t absolutely ruined everything after all.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">As for me, these next few weeks will be like a prison sentence. <text:s/>I&apos;m glad: it will be a penance for what I did. When I see you it will have been wiped away. I promise not to do anything so silly again. I can&apos;t imagine what I was thinking of.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I know I don&apos;t deserve your love and forgiveness, but then as Father Lautier says we none of us deserve the love and forgiveness of God. That isn&apos;t love&apos;s way. Michel, I love you so very much. Even the thought of losing you terrifies me.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">You know my thoughts and prayers are with you. God will bring everything to its proper conclusion, I&apos;m sure of it. I shall light another candle for you on Sunday.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Your penitent Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Tom finished his wine. &quot;Is there a lot more of this?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;See for yourself. The book&apos;s almost full.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Christ. It must have taken you forever to translate this lot.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Miss Prendergast would be proud of me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Who?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Never mind. Look, just skip to the next bookmark. The next one&apos;s a year later.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I am too exhausted to write more than a few lines. Micheline is hardly sleeping at all, it seems. I&apos;m not sure how long I can go on like this. Pauline is a great help but of course she has Justine.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Come back safely. We need you here.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">With love, </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I have just come back from a long talk with Father Lautier. <text:s/>I have been feeling so guilty about you and about Micheline and everything. He was very gentle with me. <text:s/>He says it is quite natural to be feeling this way, and many mothers do, especially with their first child. All the same I look at Pauline and she is so contented, so at ease with it. I can&apos;t help feeling there is something wrong with me. Shouldn&apos;t I be more like her?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">When you are here, it is not so bad. It&apos;s when you are away that it becomes so difficult. I know that it&apos;s part of your job, and you wouldn&apos;t leave us if you didn&apos;t have to, but I resent it all the same. We didn&apos;t wish for any of this. I know you said that you wanted children, but not like this, surely? Or perhaps you thought it would be easy? Well I can tell you that right now it&apos;s far from easy.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I must go. Micheline is crying again.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I&apos;m sorry I&apos;ve been so horrid to you in my last letters. Sometimes when I&apos;m on my own with her it all gets too much for me. I didn&apos;t mean to take it out on you. Of course I don&apos;t think it&apos;s all your fault. It&apos;s not a question of fault: we have a beautiful baby girl and we should give thanks to God rather than trying to blame one another. I get so tired and bad-tempered and it just builds up inside me. I shouldn&apos;t worry you with it when you have your job to do.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Marcel came to call this afternoon and took Micheline out in the park. He&apos;s been wonderful with her. She seems to calm down when he&apos;s here, the way she does with you. Every time I pick her up she starts to scream! So I have a few precious minutes to myself and I can write to you the way I really want to.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Danni and Jean-Paul have got engaged. I was completely astounded when I heard about it. <text:s/>You know I never gave them a chance when they first got together: that shows how much I know, doesn&apos;t it? She has such a big smile on her face every time I see her. I&apos;m so pleased for her. It&apos;s what she&apos;s always dreamed of as long as I&apos;ve known her. They are going to have a big church wedding, very traditional. I expect her father will pull out all the stops. <text:s/>Nothing has ever been too good for his little girl. <text:s/>He&apos;s been saving up for it since she was in nappies; it was a joke when we were at school. Of course she&apos;s an only child, which must make a difference.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">We&apos;ve never really spoken about getting married, have we? <text:s/>I suppose with us we knew from the start that there was an eternal bond between us, so in a way marriage would not change anything. I don&apos;t know how I feel about it, quite. Certainly I wouldn&apos;t want the sort of thing Danni and Jean-Paul are planning: all those bloody aunts, and my father making a speech. But part of me would like to make things regular. I know Father Lautier thinks we should, <text:s/>although he&apos;s never pushed it. It would be a way of giving thanks to God. I&apos;m afraid I&apos;ve done very little of that lately.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Marcel and Micheline are back, so I must go. Marcel says to give you his regards.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Kisses,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Your Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I hope this reaches you. I have the list of hotels but I&apos;ve completely lost track of which city you&apos;re in so I&apos;m guessing it&apos;s Leeds. If I&apos;m wrong, too bad! I shall blame my father. <text:s/>I wish he wouldn&apos;t keep sending you away on these epic tours, they&apos;re so tiring for you and also for me. <text:s/>I miss you, and so does little Micheline.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">You know, I think there may be a little romance brewing between our landlord and Odile. He&apos;s certainly in the café a lot more than he used to be. It would be lovely if it worked out. She&apos;s had a very sad life and she&apos;s such a lovely person. But for goodness&apos; sake don&apos;t breathe a word of this to her: she&apos;d be mortified. She&apos;s very old-fashioned in some ways. I dropped one or two hints that I suspected something and she told me to mind my own business, which isn&apos;t like her at all. Well, it will all turn out in the end one way or the other.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I&apos;m in such a fix about what to wear for Danni&apos;s wedding. It&apos;s all right for you men: <text:s/>you just put on a suit and there you are. Pauline and I are planning a big shopping expedition together. Don&apos;t worry, I know we don&apos;t have much money to spare, but I really want to make an effort for Danni. She showed me a picture of the dress she&apos;s having and it&apos;s like something out of a dream. She will look fantastic. Goodness knows what it cost, I didn&apos;t dare ask.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I had a letter today from my cousin Thérèse in Clermont. Apparently she&apos;s getting married too! There must be something in the air. She&apos;s been living with Luc since they were students together, three or four years now, so I&apos;ve no idea what brought it on. I always thought she was the modern type. Anyway, she seems really pleased about it. I imagine her mother practically died of shock.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Marcel is coming over to dinner this evening, to keep me company and help me out with Micheline. He&apos;s such a support. <text:s/>I don&apos;t know what I&apos;d do without him, with you being away so much. We shall drink your health.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I hope all this travelling doesn&apos;t wear you out too much. If Father is working you too hard then you must say so. Don&apos;t let him take advantage of you. He thinks he&apos;s doing you a big favour but you&apos;re helping him as well, it isn&apos;t all on one side. I know for a fact that business has picked up a lot since he took you on. In my opinion he should work you a bit less and pay you a bit more, but there, I suppose it isn&apos;t my opinion that counts.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Sometimes I long for it to be the way it was in the old days, just you and me. Even when you&apos;re here we&apos;re both so exhausted all the time, it&apos;s no wonder we hardly make love any more. <text:s/>Last night I could hardly sleep even though Micheline was quiet practically all through: I lay all alone thinking of you, longing for you. We belong together, you and I.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Counting the hours, </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Your Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Well, I have just had a blazing row with my father over lunch — about you, naturally. He simply won&apos;t see reason. I told him how I feel about all these trips to England and how hard it is for me, and all he said was to get a baby-sitter, as if we could afford it on the pittance he pays you. He just has no idea how difficult it is. When he started comparing me to Pauline I completely lost my temper. Of course I don&apos;t deny that she&apos;s a wonderful mother, but she has Mama there the whole time to help her out, and she never has to worry about paying the rent or any of the household expenses. He called me unnatural. Can you believe it? I swear if I had had a pistol in my hand I would have done away with him then and there. I took Micheline and stormed out without even finishing my meal.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Pauline came round later to see if I was all right. She feels as bad about it as I do. He is such an insensitive, blind, stubborn pig! I don&apos;t know how she can bear to live under his roof, although as she said she doesn&apos;t have much alternative. <text:s/>I asked her if she thinks I&apos;m unnatural and she said of course not. All the same I&apos;m not sure if she really understands how bad it gets for me sometimes. It isn&apos;t fair.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I&apos;m sorry to dump all this on you but I simply had to get it out of my system. I&apos;ll be fine in a few hours&apos; time, you know what I&apos;m like. Don&apos;t fret about me. I&apos;m breathing more easily already.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">If you can, call me. Your voice is so good to hear.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">With all my heart, </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Your Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michel darling,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I tried to call you at the hotel but I couldn&apos;t get through. I will keep trying, but if I don&apos;t succeed call my parents the instant you get this letter.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Micheline has been taken very ill. Dr Poussy thinks it is pneumonia. They&apos;ve taken her into hospital and I am staying there with her. She can hardly breathe, the poor little darling. They won&apos;t tell me what her chances are but there are a lot of long faces and I fear the worst. I can&apos;t bear even to think about it. Come as soon as you can.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michel darling,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">My first proper night&apos;s sleep in I can&apos;t remember how long, and the flat all to myself: it&apos;s like a miracle. They say I can pick her up from hospital this afternoon. </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Marcel is giving me a lift. But first I shall go to church and thank God for her recovery.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I couldn&apos;t have stood it if you hadn&apos;t been able to come back. <text:s/>Even Father could see that it was necessary. He was as frantic with worry as the rest of us. If only the whole wretched trip could have been cancelled forever and not just postponed a few days. Still, I should be properly grateful, and I am.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">One thing I do know is that I definitely want us to get married and have Micheline properly baptised. I don&apos;t care even if I have to listen to my father making a speech. It&apos;s something we simply have to do. I believe this was a warning to us, and we may not get another. I know you weren&apos;t too keen on the idea, but that was before all this happened. It&apos;s no longer just a question of pleasing my family, or of pleasing me: it&apos;s for Micheline&apos;s sake that I want this. Are you able to understand? <text:s/>Even if you can&apos;t, please agree to it, I beg you. I can&apos;t begin to explain how much it means to me.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I think Father is beginning to see some sense at last. He has been very affectionate these last few days. He even went so far as to apologise for what he said to me that day at lunch. After you had gone back to England he said he might look for an assistant for you so that you wouldn&apos;t have to travel so much. I don&apos;t know if he mentioned it to you. It seems to me like a splendid idea, and I told him so. I think he was quite touched. He saw for himself how close you and I are, and how devoted we are to Micheline. He&apos;s definitely softening.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Here&apos;s Marcel: I must go.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Love, Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Tom leafed through the book to the next bookmark.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;Did you ever meet her?&quot; Jane asked him.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;No. I&apos;ve seen photographs, though.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What&apos;s she like?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Well, I&apos;m not much good at describing people.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Try.&quot; She was back in Perry Mason mode.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Thin. Tallish, about five-seven or eight. Shoulder-length hair, sort of wavy. Light brown, I think.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Attractive?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;If </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">you </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">like that sort of thing.&quot; Hastily he returned to his reading.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">How can you be so cruel? Not just to me, but to Micheline? <text:s/>If I hadn&apos;t seen it in your own handwriting I&apos;d never have believed it. I am shocked, angry, confused — </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I don&apos;t know how to describe it. I simply don&apos;t understand what is going in your head. I thought you loved me, that you loved Micheline. <text:s/>Is it really so terrible, living with us? Does everything between us mean nothing to you?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I have told you a hundred times: Marcel is a good friend and nothing more. Do you want me to swear it on my baby&apos;s life? <text:s/>Very well, I swear it. Are you satisfied? Ask him yourself if that isn&apos;t enough for you. Yes, it&apos;s true, I see a good deal of him when you are away on these interminable bloody jaunts. He&apos;s company, and he&apos;s good with Micheline. What do you want me to do, live in a nunnery? Don&apos;t I suffer enough being left to cope on my own all the time?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">If we can&apos;t trust one another, it will have to end between us. <text:s text:c="2"/>I mean it, Michel. How do I know that you aren&apos;t seeing other women when you&apos;re off in England? You could have a wife and family over there and I wouldn&apos;t know a thing about it. I&apos;ve always trusted you completely. The very idea that you might be unfaithful is absurd, or it used to be. But now, who knows? Is it a guilty conscience that has put these crazy thoughts into your head?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">It makes me feel ill even to think about this. Losing you would be worse than a nightmare. Perhaps I have lost you already. Your letter wasn&apos;t written by the man I fell in love with. Please send him back to me. I miss him.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P3"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Darling Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I have read and re-read your last letter and I still don&apos;t know what to think. On the one hand I am deeply hurt that apparently you still can&apos;t trust me. On the other I was moved almost to tears by your unhappiness. I didn&apos;t realise you felt like that.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">It&apos;s true that this was never the life we dreamed of. All I ever wanted was for us to be together. I thought that was what you wanted too. You say you feel that you&apos;re in a trap. Well, <text:s text:c="2"/>I feel that way too sometimes. I find it hard to love Micheline the way I ought to, and I worry the whole time that I am a bad mother and a bad person altogether. Nobody understands what it&apos;s like. The one person in the world I can turn to for love and understanding is you: I don&apos;t know how I shall cope if you take that away from me.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I&apos;m sorry I accused you of being unfaithful. I was upset and not thinking. It&apos;s just that the idea of losing you is unbearable. Come back soon and we can talk properly. With God&apos;s help I am sure we can work this out.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Your ever-loving Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P3"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I can&apos;t carry on like this. Either I hear nothing from you for days on end or you write me incomprehensible letters. Do you no longer care about me at all? Sometimes it feels that way. <text:s/>Here I am having to manage everything on my own while you mope around hotel rooms feeling sorry for yourself. It would be your own fault if everything you suspected came true.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Micheline is well, not that you care. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T19"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Still no word from you: I don&apos;t know if you&apos;re alive or dead. Why are you pushing me away from you like this? What have I done? <text:s/>Every night I pray to God and find no answer.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">If you don&apos;t come home soon I am afraid of what may happen. <text:s text:c="2"/>I have only so much strength. I know you are on business but there are some things more important than that. <text:s/>If you can&apos;t come home, at least call. Michel, do I have to beg for your love? Very well: I beg you.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T8"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">9</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T7">The only other letters Jane had marked were almost the last.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I didn&apos;t want to say this in a letter, but Marcel insisted. Michel, I am so sorry, but it&apos;s true. We have become lovers.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I did not mean this to happen, I swear. But you have been so changed these last months, so cold and distant, like a stranger. Even when you are here it&apos;s as if you are not here. <text:s/>I resisted for a long time. It was Micheline who really made the difference. He is more like a father to her than you ever were. Marcel is kind and loyal and he will look after us. I have to put my baby even before you.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">It is good to be with someone who loves me. I have not felt that with you for a long time. I don&apos;t know what I did to forfeit your love, but being deprived of it was the worst punishment I have ever suffered.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Please don&apos;t think I did this to hurt you. It&apos;s not like that at all. I have never stopped loving you. It&apos;s just that you stopped being the person that I loved. Does that make sense? <text:s/>We had something that was the realest thing in the whole world and I don&apos;t know what happened to it. My time with you will always be precious to me, but I think you have known in your heart for a long time that it had no future.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Marcel cares for me and I wouldn&apos;t be human if I didn&apos;t return that affection. He is a good man. I believe we can be happy together.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michel,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style43"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I shan&apos;t mention your vile letter, which I have already burned. Of course you are angry. Be as angry as you like: it won&apos;t make any difference. I&apos;ve made my choice. It wasn&apos;t easy, but I shall stick to it. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I have already packed your things as far as I was able to. <text:s/>You can come and collect them whenever you want. You can leave the key here or with M. Auber, it doesn&apos;t matter. I have arranged with him for Marcel to move in at the end of the month.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I was stupid enough to hope that we could have remained friends, but you have made your feelings extremely clear.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michael sat in the café and drank a glass of Calvados very slowly, remembering. It had been so long since he had allowed himself to remember that even the pain seemed like a luxury. He </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">thought back to the night their daughter had been born, the crazy drive to the hospital in the pitch darkness and the pouring rain, and then the endless hours of waiting. She hadn&apos;t wanted him to see the birth in case it upset him, so she&apos;d had Pauline with her instead. There&apos;d been nothing to do but wait and hope. It seemed to go on forever. The rain stopped and a pale sun rose and he was still waiting. At last a nurse had come for him, and there was Madeleine and Pauline and this little pink bundle. When Madeleine gave him the baby to hold for the first time he couldn&apos;t get over her smallness, the little clenched face, her tiny perfect fists. It hadn&apos;t seemed real.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Odile brought him another Calvados without being asked. They exchanged shy half-smiles. He thought</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">: It must be dreadful for her, and yet here she is, getting on with the business of life. Everyone in here must know, but nothing ever gets said. But then there&apos;s nothing to say, really.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">He let his mind go way, way back, to times so long ago they were almost the stuff of legend. He remembered the first time they had met, at the house of a girl in Cambridge he had briefly gone out with. Janet something. At the time he was in pursuit of a friend of hers from Girton with extraordinary red hair so long she could sit on it. It was a lunch party; Janet was cooking. He couldn&apos;t remember anything about the meal but he could remember Madeleine. She&apos;d hardly spoken a word: she always was shy of her English, although as a matter of fact it was pretty good. He&apos;d struck up some sort of conversation with her about politics, of all things. It wasn&apos;t a subject either of them cared about. All the same speaking French turned her into a different person. She smiled, and from that moment he was utterly lost. The girl with red hair could have danced naked on the table and he wouldn&apos;t have given her a second glance, even to satisfy his curiosity about the colour of her pubic hair.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">He allowed himself to remember the first time they had made love. She had been a virgin and he was by no means very experienced, and yet there had been no fear or awkwardness about it. He had felt a tenderness for her greater than he had ever known before. He could still feel it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Marcel came in, looking like death. The two men acknowledged one another warily: they had been friends, once, but neither quite knew any more what to expect of the other. Marcel slumped down opposite him and called for a </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">coup de rouge. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">The silence between them was crammed with unspoken words.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I bear you no ill-will,&quot; Michael said. &quot;I want you to know that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Marcel shrugged. &quot;It was a long time ago.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It must be hard for you. I&apos;m sorry.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Thanks.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">They drank in silence.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;ve been to make the final arrangements,&quot; Marcel said with an effort. &quot;The flowers, you know.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;You&apos;ll be staying for a few days, I suppose? We thought you might come for dinner one evening.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;d like that. Thanks.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Marcel toyed with his glass. &quot;I&apos;ve always been jealous of you, you know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"><text:s/>&quot;Of me?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;You&apos;re the only man she&apos;s ever really loved.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"><text:s/>&quot;It was you she chose, Marcel.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I know.&quot; He sighed. &quot;I&apos;ve tried my best, God knows.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;If I hadn&apos;t known you could make her happy, I wouldn&apos;t have left.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">The ghost of his old crooked smile passed across Marcel&apos;s face. &quot;You&apos;re a good man, Michel.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;So are you.&quot; They touched glasses.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I must be off,&quot; said Marcel. &quot;So much to organise.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;ll see you tomorrow.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Until tomorrow.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Michael watched him go out. Life had always sat so easily on Marcel&apos;s shoulders, but today he looked as if he was carrying the burden of the entire world. He tried without much success to imagine what it was like for him. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">Love is the worst</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">, he decided.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">10</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Opening_20_para_20_Char">After the service Michael made himself scarce. Nobody there was prepared to acknowledge his existence, to the point that he almost felt invisible. He didn&apos;t belong here any more. This wasn&apos;t his family. At the same time he had a right, even a duty, to be here. The only kindly face was old Father Lautier, looking more than ever like a pickled walnut in a soutane. They exchanged nods but there was no chance of a conversation. Michael thought he might go over for a talk in a day or two</text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">There had been crowds of people — the aunts were out in force — but she had somehow been quite alone. Even Marcel was excluded. In black she looked even paler. She was wearing dark glasses to conceal the bottomless pain in her eyes. People milled about hardly daring to murmur their condolences to her. Michael couldn&apos;t take his eyes from her stark otherworldly beauty.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">The sky had threatened rain but it never quite arrived. It was that sort of day. He hadn&apos;t known what he had expected to feel, but whatever it was he hadn&apos;t felt it yet. Perhaps it needed time. He went for a walk among the low hills, looking for a glimpse of the sea. Eventually he gave up and sat down for a rest on the trunk of a recently felled tree. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">Why can&apos;t I cry like the rest of them? </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">he wondered. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">Is there something wrong with me?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">It was getting dark by the time he got back. He wasn&apos;t hungry but he had an omelette anyway.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;She called round for you,&quot; Odile said. &quot;I didn&apos;t know where you&apos;d gone.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Just out walking.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">He ate slowly, making himself finish it for Odile&apos;s sake although the rich oily texture was making him feel slightly sick. He had a glass of white wine to take the edge off it. It didn&apos;t help much.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;m going over to see her,&quot; he said. &quot;Don&apos;t wait up.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Give her my love.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P10"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">For about the eleventh time, Tom said: &quot;I&apos;m not sure this is a good idea.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;Shut up and drive.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It&apos;s a good job I have an understanding boss. I only hope I have an understanding girlfriend.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;This is hardly an elopement.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You don&apos;t know what she&apos;s like.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;Leave her to me,&quot; Jane said firmly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">The motorway was reasonably quiet for a weekday. They shouldn&apos;t have any trouble making the ferry. Jane checked her watch again anyway. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;We don&apos;t even know if he&apos;ll be there,&quot; Tom pointed out. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;He&apos;ll be there. I just know.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What are you expecting to do? Kidnap him?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;I just need to see him. And to see her.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;m not sure we should interfere, that&apos;s all.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Interfere? Excuse me, this is my boyfriend we&apos;re talking about. If he&apos;s off shagging some French ex of his then I&apos;m bloody well entitled to interfere.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">They passed a coachload of pensioners. Jane looked at her watch again. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;There&apos;s loads of time,&quot; Tom said soothingly. &quot;Relax.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Relax, he says.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;He&apos;s probably not even there. You know what he&apos;s like. I bet he&apos;s back at the flat right now wondering where everyone&apos;s got to.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;He&apos;s there all right. She whistled and he went running. Bloody men.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Pardon me for breathing,&quot; said Tom. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You don&apos;t count.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Is that supposed to be a compliment?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">After that she just sat and fumed in silence until they reached the ferry terminal.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane hated travelling by sea. She&apos;d even been sick on the Mersey ferry once. This was not the part of the expedition she was looking forward to. Unfortunately she didn&apos;t have the money for both a hire car and the air fare, and under the circumstances she hadn&apos;t felt able to ask Tom to contribute. It was a miracle he&apos;d agreed to come along in the first place.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She stood on deck, hoping that fresh air would help. The sea was battleship grey and flecked with scum, like old washing-up water. A few gulls were squabbling over something which was fortunately downwind of her. She fancied a cigarette, which surprised her: it normally only struck when she&apos;d had a drink or two. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">Must be nerves</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">, she thought. The deck beneath her feet shuddered and then settled down to a steady throbbing as the rumble of the </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">engines began. People who seemed to know what they were doing were removing the gangplank.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;We&apos;re off then,&quot; Tom said cheerfully. He was one of those people who never seem to be ill under any circumstances, and can never understand it when other people are.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Oh God, I think I&apos;m going to be sick.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You can&apos;t be seasick yet. We&apos;re still in the harbour.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I can be seasick in the bath.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It&apos;s all psychological. Try fixing your eyes on the horizon.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">But it was too late: she was already bent double over the side, adding her portion to the all-embracing sea.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">He rang the bell and waited. Marcel came to the door. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Come in. She&apos;s expecting you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">They climbed together up the narrow staircase. He hadn&apos;t remembered it being quite so steep. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">Must be getting out of condition</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">, he thought. She was waiting for them at the top of the stairs. She was still in black but she&apos;d removed the dark glasses. Her eyes were red wounds.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Thank you for coming,&quot; she said, very formally.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Odile said you&apos;d called.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Yes. It was so difficult to talk with all those people around.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">They went into the sitting-room. It had been redecorated since he had last been there; the walls had been painted a pale yellow, and the ghastly coffee-table had gone. There were plants everywhere. Michael sat down on the ancient sofa.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I have to go out,&quot; Marcel said vaguely. &quot;Sorry to be a bad host.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;We&apos;ve known each other too long to worry about that sort of thing,&quot; said Michael.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Yes, I suppose we have.&quot; He kissed Madeleine briefly on her alabaster cheek. &quot;I won&apos;t be late.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">They sat and heard his footsteps clamber down the stairs, the squeak and slam of the door. The ensuing silence was so perfect he could hear her breathing. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Are you married, Michel?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;No.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;But there is someone.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Yes, there is.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She nodded gravely. &quot;That&apos;s good. I&apos;m pleased for you.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">There was another silence.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It&apos;s so strange,&quot; she said, &quot;seeing you again like this.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I can think of happier circumstances.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It must have been a shock for you. We knew it was coming so we had some time to prepare ourselves, but for you it was a surprise.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Perhaps it&apos;s easier that way,&quot; he said. He was thinking of his father and his long losing battle against cancer. She knew it too without his mentioning it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;She never knew you. She always thought Marcel was her daddy.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It was for the best.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;He&apos;s taken it very hard. He was devoted to her. I think it was her he fell in love with rather than me.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Don&apos;t say that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Why not? It&apos;s the truth. Since the accident — since we knew that she wouldn&apos;t come out of the coma — we&apos;ve had nothing to say to one another. Secretly I think he blames me for it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Madeleine, no. It wasn&apos;t your fault. Some idiot got drunk and lost control of his car. Blame him, if you want to blame anyone.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I wasn&apos;t a good mother to her.&quot; She said this very matter-of-factly, as if she had long ago come to terms with it. &quot;The truth is I never wanted her in the first place.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;That&apos;s not the same as being responsible for her death.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;He wanted another child, you know. I refused.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;And now?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She shook her head. &quot;It&apos;s not for me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;You say that now. Give it time.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;No. It&apos;s the way I am. I&apos;ve known since the moment Dr Poussy told me that the test was positive. I was horrified. It was if the rest of my life had been stolen from me. No, whatever thing it is that makes some women into mothers, I don&apos;t have it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;That doesn&apos;t make you a bad person, Madeleine.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I wonder.&quot; She passed a fist over her eyes. &quot;Look at what&apos;s happened in my life. I lost you. I&apos;ve lost Micheline. I&apos;m losing Marcel. Every gift I&apos;m given is taken away from me. Why is that, if God isn&apos;t punishing me?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You haven&apos;t lost me. I&apos;m here, aren&apos;t I?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It&apos;s too late, Michel. We&apos;re not the same people any more. You live in London, you have a girlfriend there, you&apos;ve moved on.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;Do you know, I&apos;ve still got all your letters?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She smiled. Compared to the smile he knew of old it was as moonlight is to sunshine, but still it brought a new light into her face. &quot;I have yours too.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;So much for moving on.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine let the smile fade, although a little of it stayed with her. &quot;Tell me about your girlfriend.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;There isn&apos;t much to tell.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Liar.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Her name&apos;s Jane. I haven&apos;t known her very long. Tom introduced us — I told you about him, we share a flat.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Is she pretty?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Not as pretty as you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Now I know you&apos;re lying! I look terrible.&quot; But the smile was coming back. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;To tell you the truth,&quot; he said, &quot;she doesn&apos;t know I&apos;m here. I&apos;ve never explained about — well, about what happened.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;She doesn&apos;t know that you had a daughter?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;No. I was meaning to tell her but, well, I could never find the right words. It was cowardice, too. It&apos;s a painful story for me to tell.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Was it painful to come back, then?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Yes and no. It&apos;s been a lot easier than I imagined.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;m glad.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">They sat for a little while in companionable silence.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;ve thought about you every single day,&quot; she said. &quot;I&apos;ve never admitted it to anyone, but I have. Do you think I&apos;m very wicked?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;No.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I even used to imagine it was you when I was with Marcel.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;ve done the same thing,&quot; he admitted.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;With Jane? Goodness, no wonder you didn&apos;t want to tell her about me.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It&apos;s kind of embarrassing.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Do you love her?&quot; The tone of her voice was still light, but he knew her too well to be deceived.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;As much as you love Marcel.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Touché.&quot; She got up. &quot;I&apos;m forgetting my manners. Would you like a drink? A glass of wine?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Please.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She went off into the tiny kitchen. The flat seemed unnaturally quiet. He realised that subconsciously he was waiting for Micheline to start crying. It was then that it really began to hit him that she was really gone, that the child they had buried that afternoon had been her.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">When Madeleine came back with their wine she found him weeping silently, bent almost double on the sofa, shoulders heaving. Wordlessly she put her arms around him and they sat like that for a long time until they had both stopped crying. He became aware of the warmth of her body, of its familiar scent, the soft rhythm of her breathing. It felt good.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Nobody understands,&quot; she said quietly. &quot;Not Pauline, not Odile, not even Marcel. Nobody really knows apart from us.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;m sorry,&quot; he said, his voice muffled by her shoulder. &quot;I&apos;m so, so sorry.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Don&apos;t blame yourself, Michel. I don&apos;t.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I should have stayed. I should have looked after you and Micheline.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I was the one who ended it, remember?&quot; She touched his cheek with the tips of her fingers, turning his face to hers. &quot;If it ever really ended.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane sat in the passenger seat of the car, eyes closed, feeling the colour very slowly returning to her face.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Feeling better?&quot; Tom enquired brightly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I never knew my stomach had so much in it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;We&apos;ll stop and get a bite to eat if you like.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Thanks.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">They found a café where English may or may not have been spoken but was certainly ignored. By pointing and shouting Tom eventually managed to place an order, although Jane had very little confidence that what they got would bear much resemblance to what they thought they&apos;d asked for. She was past caring; having dumped her entire stomach contents into the Channel she was now ravenous. Tom seemed to be thoroughly enjoying himself, which wasn&apos;t helping. &quot;Do you feel up to driving?&quot; he asked.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Don&apos;t know. See how I feel when I&apos;ve had something to eat.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">The food took so long to arrive that she&apos;d forgotten what it was supposed to have been in the first place. Whatever it was, she ate it. The sensation of being at least partly refilled soon began to put some heart back into her.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;God, that&apos;s an improvement,&quot; she said at last.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;All right to push on, or do you want to stop over somewhere?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Let&apos;s just go there. No point in hanging about.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Absolutely.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Tom entered into negotiations with the waiter, which took some time. His stubborn refusal to be fleeced, while not unreasonable in itself, wasn&apos;t doing much for the cause of international relations. Eventually, however, the transaction was concluded to the grudging satisfaction of both parties, and they set off again. Evening was closing in. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane was trying to navigate on the basis of a road atlas which depicted the countryside with rather a broad brushstroke. They passed through several quite substantial townships which were nowhere mentioned. On the other hand, at least one place whose name appeared in bold letters on the map had apparently been bought by an eccentric American millionaire and translated wholesale to Arizona: at any rate she could see no trace of it in France. It was getting late and the road was dwindling into a country lane that might lead nowhere at all. There had been no sign of human habitation for a disturbingly long time.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">In answer to Jane&apos;s fervent prayer, the Lord sent them a sign. It was not a very legible sign, and it had once been a good deal closer to the vertical than it was now, but it bore the name of the town they were making for. Jane beheld it, and saw that it was good.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">The lane down which it directed them was even less inviting than the one they had left, being hedged so closely in on both sides as to resemble a dark tunnel. It was too narrow for two cars to pass, and indeed it threatened to be too narrow even for one. But there was doubt about it being the right way. Jane was exultant. She was bearing down on her quarry.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">And then quite unexpectedly they were there, in what passed for the town square, with houses and streetlights and all the signs of civilisation. There was only one café in the square. This had to be it. Tom drew to a halt, cut the engine. It was suddenly very quiet.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Well,&quot; Tom said, &quot;you&apos;re the linguist. Time to go and dicker with the natives, I think.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">They got out into the chilly evening air. It was almost completely dark. There were perhaps half a dozen people in the café and they all looked round as Tom and Jane walked in. A stout woman of a certain age was behind the counter.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;What do you want?&quot; Jane whispered.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Beer or something. I&apos;m knackered.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T13">Deux bières, s&apos;il vous plaît</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">,&quot; Jane said, too loudly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">The stout woman looked at them shrewdly and nodded. They adjourned to the nearest table. There was a menu on the wall headed </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">Café Ambrose</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">. Jane drew Tom&apos;s attention to it with her eyes.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Bingo,&quot; he said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Carefully Jane composed the question in her head, calling upon the name of Miss Prendergast for guidance in her hour of need. The stout woman brought their beer. Jane took a breath.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T12">Pardonnez-moi</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">,&quot; </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">she began. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T12">Nous cherchons notre ami. Il s&apos;appelle</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michael Ashe.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Before she could continue, however, she was swept away by a torrent of French of which she caught about one word in four.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T12">Parlez-vous anglais</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">?&quot; </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Tom tried optimistically.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T12">Attendez</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">.&quot; </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">The stout woman called over a customer, a kindly-looking soul of about the same age with half-moon glasses and the air of an absent-minded professor. They conferred rapidly and came to some sort of agreement.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I speak a little,&quot; the man announced to them, with evident if quiet pride.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;We&apos;re looking for our friend.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Ah yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;His name is Michael Ashe.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">There was another conference. &quot;He is here, yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Can we see him?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;He is here, but he is not here,&quot; the man said enigmatically. &quot;He will return.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;We will wait, then,&quot; Jane said. &quot;Thank you.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;He is here for his daughter. She die.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Die? How?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;She is hit by an auto. Today they bury her.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Poor bastard,&quot; said Tom, in an awe-struck undertone.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Thank you very much,&quot; Jane said to the man. &quot;Would you like a drink?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">This seemed to baffle him, so she pointed to the beer-bottle and mimed drinking. There was general hilarity. Their informant graciously accepted, and the </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T12">patronne</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">produced a glass of his favourite tipple, a pale amber fluid that smelt of apples. The four of them sat together at the table and toasted the world in general. Altogether, things seemed to be looking up.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Between them, everyone got introduced to everyone else. By now the whole café was participating. With Jane&apos;s broken French and the man&apos;s broken English they managed to construct a sort of mid-Channel pidgin which more or less worked. There was a good deal of commentary on the side which she didn&apos;t really catch, but everyone seemed to be so pleased to see them that it hardly seemed to matter. They drank more beer. Their informant, who said his name was Jean-Marie, recounted his experiences of England, the highlight of which had apparently been a visit to Norwich. There was a lot of sniggering about this amongst his fellow-townsmen, as if Norwich were a notorious den of vice. Jane did her best to return the compliment by telling them about her school trip to Dieppe but it fell rather flat by comparison. Still, it didn&apos;t matter. There was even more beer. She was a bit hazy by now as to who was paying for what.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">The time passed most agreeably. There was no sign of Michael, but Jean-Marie had said he would return and that was good enough for Jane. She liked Jean-Marie a lot. He would have made a very good uncle. She tried to explain this idea to him but it didn&apos;t really get across all that well. Still, he beamed at her over his glasses in the true avuncular style. </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Meanwhile Tom was trying to resist the advances of a couple of young men who seemed to want to involve him in a game of cards. The </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">entente </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">was extremely </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">cordiale.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">She almost didn&apos;t notice when Michael came in. If she hadn&apos;t felt the draught from the door and noticed the </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T13">patronne</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T16">&apos;s</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T7"> </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">quick sidelong glance she would have missed it altogether. He noticed her, though. His face was a picture of astonishment. Under other circumstances she would have laughed aloud, but it was the woman beside him that took her attention. There was no mistaking her from Tom&apos;s description. This had to be Madeleine.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">11</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane had never had much time for the theory that you could tell when other people had just had sex. Some of the times she&apos;d had sex had been so unimpressive that she&apos;d hardly noticed herself. But if the woman in front of her was not in the radiant aftermath of orgasm then she, Jane Sharp, was the queen of China.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Hello, Michael,&quot; she said with dangerous brightness. &quot;Fancy seeing you here.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">“Jane.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Ah, so you do remember. I was beginning to wonder.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine said something to him in urgent French. The café looked on benignly. It dawned on Jane that none of them had the faintest idea who she was.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Where are you staying?&quot; he asked.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Wherever you are. That was the plan, anyway.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;There&apos;s a room here. I&apos;m sure I can organise something.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">More French, involving Madeleine and the </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T12">patronne</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Tom looked round and saw them. He tried to catch Jane&apos;s eye and realised that she already knew.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I think,&quot; said Michael slowly, &quot;it would be better if we talked this over quietly in the back. Odile has a café to run.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Suits me,&quot; said Jane. &quot;Tom?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Sure. Whatever.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">The four of them trooped into Odile&apos;s back parlour. In the café itself the merriment continued unabated. They sat around her plain oak table, four people who might never have met before. Tom was the most obviously embarrassed. Jane would have felt sorry for him if she&apos;d any emotional capacity left over from her overwhelming rage at Michael&apos;s betrayal. Michael himself was as remote as if they had all been strangers to him. He&apos;d gone into that peculiar space where he communed with whatever it was. As for Madeleine — Jane looked at her with undisguised curiosity. Was this the girl who&apos;d meant so much to him that he&apos;d kept all her letters? She didn&apos;t seem worth the trouble. All skin and bones. She was reminded of a remark Marcie had made about an ex-girlfriend of Paul&apos;s, that it would be like going to bed with a bicycle.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">To her surprise it was Madeleine who spoke first, in a clear and melodious English.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Jane. My name is Madeleine. Will you introduce me to your friend?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Tom,&quot; the friend in question said bashfully. &quot;Michael and I share a flat in London.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Ah yes. Michel has spoken of you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I won&apos;t ask what you&apos;re doing here,&quot; Michael said pointedly. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane was outraged at being made to feel in the wrong. &quot;I have as good a right to be here as anyone else.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;So you just stuck a pin in the atlas, did you?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;An angel told me, &quot; she said defiantly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">There was a long moment in which Michael and Jane looked at one another, eye to eye. Well, she had wanted to know the truth and here it was.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I never told you,&quot; he said, &quot;about the time I lived in France.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;No, you didn&apos;t.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I meant to, I honestly did. It never seemed to be the right time. And I didn&apos;t know how to explain it, really. I could never even explain it to myself.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I can,&quot; Jane said brutally.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michael and Madeleine both looked at her with varying degrees of incomprehension. The sense of power flushed her with bitter pride.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Let me tell you the story, as far as I understand it.&quot; Jane leaned back in her chair, her arms folded. &quot;You were a student at Cambridge when you met. You had a relationship. She got pregnant. You moved here and got a job in her father&apos;s firm. The job meant you were away a lot and she was left pretty much on her own with the baby. The relationship went sour. She chucked you in favour of someone more reliable. You buggered off. Then the child got run over and you came back here for the funeral. How am I doing?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">There was a silence. Michael&apos;s gaze moved over to Tom, who was doing his best not to be in the room at all.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Not guilty,&quot; Tom said quickly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michael turned back to Jane. &quot;Well?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;All right then. If you&apos;ll level with me I&apos;ll level with you. I read the letters.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">For a moment he simply couldn&apos;t take it in. &quot;You did what?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I wasn&apos;t looking for them. I just happened across them. Cross my heart and hope to die.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You read my letters?&quot; Madeleine enquired mildly. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine smiled sadly. &quot;Then there is nothing more to be said.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;If you read the letters,&quot; Michael said, &quot;then at least you&apos;ll know that it&apos;s over.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Doesn&apos;t look over to me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;For God&apos;s sake, do you begrudge me going to my own daughter&apos;s funeral?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;No, I begrudge you shagging her mother.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Forgive me,&quot; said Madeleine, &quot;my English is not so good.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>Michael translated in a terse undertone. She went pink. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">Score one for me</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">, Jane thought.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I don&apos;t know about anyone else,&quot; Tom said, &quot;but I could do with another drink.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">A bottle was produced and ceremoniously opened. Jane was reminded of religious ritual. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">Maybe the funeral was like this</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">, she thought. She&apos;d only ever been to a couple of funerals, family affairs, and they&apos;d had the same quality: a group of people who didn&apos;t really know each other getting drunk to avoid social interaction.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine turned to her. She seemed to have come to some sort of decision. Her pink-rimmed eyes were fixed on Jane&apos;s. They were dark blue, the pupils huge and black as midnight. She spoke with a great effort.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Jane. I do not know you, perhaps you know me better if you have read my letters. I am not asking you to give up anything. I do not want to steal what is not mine. In the past I loved Michel. He gave me a daughter and now she is dead. That is what happened and nobody can change it. He came here because I asked him to come. If you have a child, perhaps you understand. I do not know how to say in English properly. I love him. I always love him. You love him too, I think. If you make him happy, take him. That is all I want. For myself, nothing. You understand?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">The huge eyes were filling with tears. Jane looked down. She didn&apos;t know how to deal with this. A fight, yes, she was prepared for that. She would quite happily have resorted to physical force if necessary. So long as Madeleine was just an abstract idea, Jane could have killed her as easily as swatting a fly. But she couldn&apos;t fight against this appalling generosity. She thought again of the letters she had read and re-read. She thought of Micheline.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Michael spoke again. &quot;It&apos;s late. Maybe we should talk again in the morning.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Okay,&quot; Jane said in a low voice.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">There were practical things to arrange. Tom volunteered to sleep in the car, but nobody took him seriously. He ended up on the sofa. Madeleine went back to the flat, and presumably Marcel. Michael and Jane were left with Odile&apos;s guest bedroom.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He left the room while she undressed, and she lay there in the dark waiting for him. Eventually he joined her. The mattress was so old and soft that when he climbed into bed it almost made her seasick again. She lay on her back with her hands folded primly on her belly, very conscious of the inch or so between them.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;You awake?&quot; she said after a while.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He made a small noise that she took to mean yes.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;m sorry about the letters.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;So am I.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;They were private. I shouldn&apos;t have read them.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I shouldn&apos;t have kept them.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I can see why you did.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">There was another silence.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I can&apos;t do this,&quot; Jane said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Can&apos;t do what?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Break you up.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;There&apos;s nothing to break up. It&apos;s over. Micheline&apos;s dead, she&apos;s with Marcel. End of story.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Bollocks to that,&quot; said Jane. &quot;You heard what she said to me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;It&apos;s a difficult time for her. In case you&apos;d forgotten, she buried her daughter today.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;And your daughter.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I wish you&apos;d told me about that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I should have. I&apos;m sorry. It&apos;s just not the easiest thing to slip into the conversation.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I suppose not.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">She tried to sleep. It had been a long and exhausting day, and she&apos;d had rather too much to drink; under normal circumstances she would have been out for the count. But these </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">weren&apos;t exactly normal circumstances. She lay and listened to Michael&apos;s even breathing. How on earth did he manage to stay so calm?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">Tom was right</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">, she thought; </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">I shouldn&apos;t have come here. Michael has enough to deal with as it is. The last thing he needs is a hysterical girlfriend, or ex-girlfriend, or whatever I am at the moment. Poor sod. What a thing to happen to anyone.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">At some point these reflections merged into a dream in which she was having Michael&apos;s baby, except that when it was born it had Madeleine&apos;s eyes; at which point they found themselves on the top deck of a London bus speeding crazily down a country lane, and then they were underwater, still on the bus, and just as she began to drown she woke up gasping for breath.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Something was wrong. Jane sat up sharply. In the half-darkness she could make out Michael dressing.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Sorry,&quot; he said. &quot;Didn&apos;t mean to wake you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Are you all right?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Couldn&apos;t sleep.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Oh.&quot; She rubbed her neck. &quot;What time is it?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Early.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She could hear birdsong. It was eerily quiet here when you were used to London. Jane yawned luxuriously.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;ll be back for breakfast,&quot; he said. &quot;Just getting some fresh air.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Okay.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She stretched herself wide under the duvet. It felt like a rare treat to have a double bed all to herself, even if it did creak alarmingly at every movement. That was probably what had woken her. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">Good job we didn&apos;t have sex last night</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">, she thought; </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">damn thing would have collapsed altogether. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Then she realised that it would have been their bed, when they&apos;d first lived here. Micheline was probably conceived in it. Christ. It spooked her just to think about it. No wonder he couldn&apos;t get to sleep. It must have been like trying to sleep in a haunted house.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">More than ever she felt herself to be an intruder here. She got up, grabbed her dressing-gown, and went in search of a bathroom. It wasn&apos;t as rustic as she&apos;d feared. She threw some cold water on her face to dispel sleep, washed in a rather perfunctory fashion, and got dressed. When she opened the curtains it was definitely morning, although still early. There had been a heavy dew, and the low-slanting sunlight strung jewels on a spider-web in </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">the corner of the window. The pale sky was a delicate shade of blue-white, shining like porcelain. It seemed altogether another world.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She went downstairs. Tom was stretched out on the sofa, sleeping like a baby. Going carefully, still not quite awake, she found the kitchen and the makings of coffee. It smelt wonderful. She sat and watched the morning shadows gradually shorten in the little garden. A portly ginger cat hoisted itself in through the open window, its fur glistening with dew, and greeted her in a polite but restrained manner. It condescended to have its ears tickled. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">This is the life</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">, she thought.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michael was sitting on the low wall of the churchyard, opposite the new-dug grave. He hadn&apos;t consciously intended to come here. It was just where his feet had taken him. All he had been aware of was that he had to get out, to get away from people. Especially away from Jane.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">The stone they&apos;d given her was so tiny. Somehow that made it more pathetic. It was black marble and very shiny beside its lichen-crusted neighbours. In neat golden letters were inscribed her name, the date she was born and the date she died: nothing more. What more was there to say?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">The morning was still cold, and the tears felt as if they were freezing on his face. If it hadn&apos;t been for that he might not have noticed he was crying. Grief had become a background noise in his life that he no longer paid attention to. It had consumed him with the gradual inevitability of a cancer, until now there seemed to be nothing else left. He no longer cared what happened. He might stay here and try again with Madeleine; he might go back with Jane; he might not have a relationship with either of them. It didn&apos;t matter. Micheline would still be dead, and whatever life he had left would have to be lived under the shadow of that little black tombstone glowing in the morning sunshine.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I thought I&apos;d find you here,&quot; she said quietly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I couldn&apos;t sleep.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Neither could I.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine sat down beside him, huddled in her jacket against the cool air. They looked at the grave for a long time without speaking. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Marcel and I had a long talk last night.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;And?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;He&apos;s leaving.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;I&apos;m sorry.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;He would have left anyway.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>Michael thought about this. &quot;Perhaps.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;He loves me, but he doesn&apos;t understand me. It was Micheline he was really close to. Closer than I was.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You said in a letter once that he was more of a father to her than I ever was.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Did I? My God.&quot; She laughed sadly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You were angry with me. I can&apos;t say I blame you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;We both tried our best, Michel. Our best wasn&apos;t very good, that&apos;s all.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;No.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">There was another pensive silence. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What about Jane?&quot; she said. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I don&apos;t know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;She loves you. I don&apos;t suppose she&apos;s said it in so many words, but you can tell.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Perhaps it&apos;s like Marcel.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Perhaps.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">He sighed. &quot;I feel responsible for her.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;But Michel, you feel responsible for everyone. Me, Jane, even Marcel. No wonder you find life such a burden.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">He managed a wan smile. &quot;Come on, let&apos;s go and find some breakfast</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33">.&quot;</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Tom was anxious to be getting back. He didn&apos;t want to take more than two days off work, and Anna was coming at the weekend. Jane supposed she should go back with him. There didn&apos;t seem to be much point in staying on, pleasant though it was in some ways. Michael declined the offer of a lift. No further comment seemed to be required.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She didn&apos;t say much in the car on the way home, and Tom thought better of disturbing the peace. Jane had been dumped before: she&apos;d become almost resigned to it. There was no use getting angry and resentful about it. She could see well enough which way the wind was blowing. Nothing she could do or say would make the slightest difference. Probably he&apos;d really thought he was over Madeline until that letter came. That&apos;s Fate for you, she thought bitterly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">On the boat her physical misery compounded her distress, and well before they reached dry land she was thoroughly sick in every sense. She had, however, formed a plan of </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">action: phone Marcie, go to the pub, get slaughtered. It might not be the most effective long-term coping strategy, but it would do to be going on with. At the ferry terminal she bought twenty Silk Cut and a lighter. It was her first cigarette of the year; the pleasure centres in her brain did a little jog of joy. Maybe life wasn&apos;t a complete washout after all.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Tom,&quot; she said suddenly. &quot;We can still be mates, can&apos;t we? You and me?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Sure. No problem.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;d hate to think that I&apos;d lost both of you.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Jane,&quot; he said fondly. &quot;Don&apos;t be an idiot.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Good.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">After they&apos;d driven a few more miles, he said: &quot;Anna&apos;s coming this weekend.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I know.&quot; He&apos;d hardly talked about anything else all day. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Maybe we could all go for a drink.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Okay. I&apos;d like that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She lit another cigarette and smoked it at a more leisurely pace, allowing herself to enjoy it. There&apos;d be other men. There always had been in the past. Admittedly most of them were tossers, but if she dated enough of them sooner or later she&apos;d find one that was okay. Preferably one who didn&apos;t talk to the angels or have a baby secreted in some obscure part of Europe. Surely there must be a few somewhere in a place the size of London. She&apos;d get some advice off Marcie: she never seemed to have any trouble pulling. If she&apos;d wanted to, Marcie could easily have ended up with Tom, who was a thoroughly decent bloke if you weren&apos;t after subtlety. There was always hope.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;They&apos;ll kill you,&quot; Tom observed as she lit up her third.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;Something&apos;s got to.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Not a nice way to go. Michael&apos;s father had lung cancer, you know.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;My granddad smoked forty a day and lived to be ninety-three.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;One day,&quot; Tom said, &quot;I shall have to introduce you to the mathematics of probability.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Oh Christ, you&apos;re as bad as my brother.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;All I&apos;m saying is I wouldn&apos;t want to see you in an oxygen mask drowning in your own phlegm.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;That,&quot; said Jane, &quot;is the kindest thing anyone&apos;s said to me all day.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"/></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">12</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Marcie was a terrific friend in a crisis, you had to give her that. She&apos;d cancelled her date with Paul without a moment&apos;s hesitation. Almost before Jane had put the phone down, or so it seemed, there she was at the door with a bottle of tequila and a box of tissues, both bought especially for the occasion.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Until that point, Jane hadn&apos;t really let herself experience her emotions. A really good catharsis needs a sympathetic audience, and she knew Tom wouldn&apos;t be able to handle it. Marcie was ideal. She knew when to keep quiet and the right things to say when there was something to say, she knew when to pour her another drink and when to buy another bottle, and she gave a wonderful neck massage when the gale had spent itself and she just needed to collapse.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Eventually Jane sighed: &quot;Why do I always get the weirdos?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;It&apos;s the statistics, isn&apos;t it? There&apos;s so many of &apos;em out there you&apos;re bound to get a few. I went out with a bloke once, wanted me to dress up in rubber. Wouldn&apos;t have bothered me so much if he hadn&apos;t worked in a tyre factory.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Did he prefer you in cross-ply or radial?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I didn&apos;t hang around to find out. Then there was a guy I met at a party, we both got completely out of it and we ended up having sex on top of a pile of coats in the spare bedroom, next thing I know he&apos;s telling me I&apos;m a miserable sinner but Jesus died for me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You&apos;re kidding.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Only a Seventh-Day bloody Adventist, isn&apos;t he? Wanted to convert me to the true way of the Lord.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What did you say?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I told him he seemed like a pretty cheerful sinner five minutes ago. He got quite offended.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Marcie, you&apos;re brilliant. You really are.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I have my moments.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane sat up. With all the alcohol in her bloodstream, it was a rather more drastic manoeuvre than she&apos;d anticipated. &quot;Tell me something.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Sure.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;How do you do it? I mean, how do you pull all those blokes?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;There&apos;s nothing to it, love. It&apos;s all about self-belief. If</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6"> you </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">think you&apos;re drop-dead gorgeous, then so will they. Doesn&apos;t really matter what you look like. Sarah Bernhardt played Cleopatra with a wooden leg and got rave reviews.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;But I look in the mirror every morning and I just see a fat slapper having a bad hair day.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;So see something different.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What, you mean I just get a complete body transplant or something.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;No, I mean change your </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T6">attitude. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">There&apos;s nothing wrong with the way you look. Loads of blokes fancy you.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Name three.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Paul does, for one.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Paul?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Had a thing about you for ages. Haven&apos;t you noticed the way his eyes follow you around the room?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;God, that&apos;s disgusting.&quot; She knew that Paul and Marcie slept together but she didn&apos;t like to think about it, much as most people don&apos;t think too hard about the way slugs reproduce. Paul had always turned her stomach. It was his bulging eyes that did it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Then there&apos;s Jason in Marketing.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Which one&apos;s Jason?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You know, the fair-haired one with the ear-ring, looks a bit like Johnny Depp with highlights. Ever wondered why he&apos;s always hanging around our office doing photocopying?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I thought he was just skiving.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Well, guess again.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;How do you know all this?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I watch people. Some people collect stamps, some people knit, I watch people. I can always tell when there&apos;s something going on.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Any chance of a bloke fancying me who isn&apos;t totally revolting? No offence to Paul.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Listen to me, Jane Sharp. There&apos;s enough talent in this town to stretch from here to Blackpool. You can filter &apos;em out however you like, age, height, salary, colour of eyes, taste in music, and you&apos;ll still be able to fill the Albert Hall with men who meet your every </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">criterion. Statistics, see. You go out there with your head held high and think of Sarah Bernhardt, and you&apos;ll have to fight them off with a shitty stick.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Do you think so?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I know so.&quot; Marcie topped up their glasses. &quot;Here&apos;s to Jane, Camden&apos;s Cleopatra.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">The elation didn&apos;t last long. &quot;But what about Michael?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What about him?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I can&apos;t go on the pull with a broken heart.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;If being on the rebound was so terrible they&apos;d never have invented trampolining. You&apos;ll be fine. Tell yourself it&apos;s only practice.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Maybe.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;No maybes. We&apos;re going to go out and find a cure for that broken heart of yours.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Are we?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Friday night,&quot; said Marcie firmly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What, this Friday coming? As in the day after tomorrow?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6"><text:s/>&quot;You and me, glad rags, Queen&apos;s Head, eight sharp.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I thought you were spoken for.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Look, you learn to drive with someone in the passenger seat, don&apos;t you? It doesn&apos;t mean the instructor&apos;s going to take the test.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Thanks, Marcie. You&apos;re a mate.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;You&apos;d do the same for me.&quot; She put a comforting arm around Jane&apos;s shoulders.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I think I&apos;m going to be sick.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane spent the next two days trying to get out of their hunting party, but Marcie was having none of it. She said that it was like learning to ride a bike. If you fell off you had to get straight back on again, or it just got harder and harder to do. In any case, it would be a laugh. Jane doubted this but there was nothing for it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Just before she set out she phoned Michael&apos;s flat. Nobody answered.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Marcie was already there, at a strategically placed table with a good view of the gents&apos; toilet. She was wearing a crimson dress whose neckline practically reached to her navel and </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">six-inch heels to match. For want of an alternative, Jane had fallen back on her little black number. She had visions of them being offered an alternative career in Soho.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Right,&quot; Marcie said without preamble, &quot;let&apos;s get positive. Look in that mirror over there. What do you see?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Me,&quot; Jane said. It was an accurate reply as far as it went.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Forget about it being you. Imagine it&apos;s some woman you&apos;ve never seen before. How would you describe her?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Well, I don&apos;t know. Blonde.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Go on.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Young, I suppose.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Sexy?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I don&apos;t know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Oh, yes you do. That woman is a sex goddess.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;She is?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;She&apos;s completely irresistible. Every man in here is looking at her and wishing she was his. Look at the way she&apos;s sitting, that poise. Look at those smouldering eyes. Those lush curves.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Stop it Marcie, I&apos;m going all pink.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I&apos;m not going to stop until I make you believe it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Do you think it&apos;s true?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;True as I&apos;m sitting here.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane looked at herself again and straightened up a little. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T8">You know, I&apos;m not too bad in this light actually</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">, she thought. She tried the smouldering eyes thing. It was reasonably effective, considering she was wearing glasses. Well, it might be if you&apos;d had a couple of drinks.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Come on then, get that down you,&quot; Marcie said, indicating a large glass of wine. &quot;This is going to be a night to remember.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">In fact it turned out to be a night of which she could subsequently remember very little. It definitely ended with her falling out of a taxi, but then it had been raining and the pavements were quite slippery. At some point they had visited a cocktail bar, because she found a match-book and a little umbrella in her handbag. There was also a bus-ticket with a </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">telephone number she didn&apos;t recognise scrawled on the back, and a torn buff window envelope with a different telephone number written on it in very neat handwriting. She didn&apos;t recognise that one either. An examination of the clothing strewn around her bedroom also suggested that she had come home without any knickers. She had no explanation for that one and didn&apos;t really want to speculate. She was pretty sure she&apos;d been wearing some when she went out.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">As soon as she was up to it she phoned Marcie.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;What did we do last night, exactly?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Don&apos;t you remember?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;No. That&apos;s why I&apos;m asking you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Oh.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;Well?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">&quot;I don&apos;t remember either.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Some help that was. Jane made herself yet more tea and took it back to bed with her. She looked again at the two phone numbers. They were just phone numbers. Short of going through the entire London telephone directory, she had no way of finding out to whom they belonged. Well, she could call them, of course, but that would be madness.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">This is madness</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">, she told herself. She&apos;d tossed a coin and gone for the bus-ticket first. The phone seemed to ring for ages.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Hello?&quot; said a masculine voice she was sure she&apos;d never heard before in her life.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Hi. It&apos;s Jane.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Jane?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;From last night.&quot; That was all the clarification she was in a position to give, so it had better be enough.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T16">Oh</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T7">, Jane.&quot; </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">he said. Well, at least he remembered her, even if she didn&apos;t remember him. It was a start. &quot;God, I never thought you&apos;d call.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;That was why you gave me your number, wasn&apos;t it?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Yes, of course. But women never call first, do they?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;This woman does.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Well. It&apos;s good to hear from you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Jane decided to take the bull by the horns. &quot;So. Who are you, exactly? I mean I found your number in my bag but I can&apos;t remember the first thing about you.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">He laughed richly. &quot;Douglas. We met in the Lord Kitchener.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Did we?&quot; Jane couldn&apos;t even think where or what the Lord Kitchener might be.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I bought you a gin and tonic. In fact I think I bought you several. Then you asked me for my phone number.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Did I?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;So I gave it to you and then you went off to the ladies and never came back.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Oh. Sorry about that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I&apos;m really glad you called, though. I thought I&apos;d never see you again.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Well, here I am,&quot; she said, trying to sound bright. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Look, how are you fixed for this evening?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I can&apos;t. I&apos;m meeting a friend of mine. He&apos;s going to introduce me to his new girlfriend.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Well, why don&apos;t I come along? Make it a foursome.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Put like that, Jane couldn&apos;t think of a good reason why not. It wasn&apos;t as if an evening with a Swiss lawyer was a prospect she looked forward to with relish. Even Tom seemed to find the idea a bit off-putting, and he was besotted with the woman. &quot;Okay. I&apos;ll ring him first and see if it&apos;s all right with him, then I&apos;ll give you a call back.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;That&apos;d be great.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;I hope you can remember what I look like.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;A girl like you isn&apos;t easily forgotten.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">Bloody hell</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">, she thought, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">this Sarah Bernhardt thing really works</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">. &quot;I&apos;ll call you later, then.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Look forward to it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Tom was a bit nonplussed by her suggestion that she bring a date, but he made no objection. It was all arranged. She couldn&apos;t believe how easy it was. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">Marcie</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">, she thought, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">I owe you one for this. A girl like me isn&apos;t easily forgotten. Christ almighty, the age of miracles is not yet past.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Although she made sure to be there in plenty of time, Tom and Anna were already ensconced in the pub. He brightened visibly at her arrival and hastened to ply her with drink. It had always been one of his strengths. Anna was frighteningly beautiful. She had long dark hair that curved around her face like glossy wings, cheekbones by Modigliani, and huge pale grey eyes. Her unsmiling mouth was small and plump and almost indecently sensual. When she spoke, which was seldom, she had just enough of an accent to be dangerously exotic. Jane had never disliked anyone quite so much on sight.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">She would have been edgy enough just meeting Anna. Combined with the whole Douglas thing it was almost more than she could cope with. It didn&apos;t help that Tom was like a cat on hot bricks too. Consequently the first drink hardly touched the sides on the way down and she was well on the way to finishing her packet of Silk Cut. Without saying anything Anna made it abundantly clear that she thought smoking was a filthy habit. Jane didn&apos;t care. Even before they&apos;d met she hadn&apos;t taken kindly to the way Anna seemed to be treating Tom, who in her view was a thoroughly decent man and deserved better. Seeing her in action was even worse. She wanted to tell him what she thought, but she knew it would only upset him. He was obviously smitten, poor sod.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">A man came up to her and said his name was Douglas. Jane made the introductions. Anna smiled very briefly, or perhaps she was wincing. Tom was a little too hearty to be convincing. There was a light conversation on a number of topics, including the climate of Switzerland, whether Britain should join the Euro, the pros and cons of air travel, and Arsenal&apos;s chances of the double. All the time Jane was trying to decide what she thought of Douglas. Obviously he must have had some basic appeal when she&apos;d originally met him, or she wouldn&apos;t have asked for his phone number; he&apos;d sounded pleasant enough on the phone, and any man who thought she wasn&apos;t easily forgotten had to have a modicum of taste and discernment. On the debit side, he was slightly overweight, very bland in his opinions, and apparently enjoyed staring at Anna. As far as the weight problem went, she was prepared to meet him half-way: if he ignored hers, she&apos;d ignore his. The blandness could just be because he was amongst strangers and didn&apos;t want to tread on anyone&apos;s toes. But the thing with Anna was harder to overlook. Indeed as the evening went on it became quite blatant. Anna herself seemed to have no idea he was doing it, but both Tom and Jane had noticed and were increasingly fed up with him.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Well, there was always the buff envelope.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T6">She tried him the next day, at a reasonably late hour of the morning. There was an answering-machine with a Geordie voice on it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Hi. This is the number for Phil Harkness and Dave Edwards. Please leave a message after the beep, or we&apos;ll come and get you. Cheers.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">&quot;Hello,&quot; she said, feeling like an idiot. &quot;My name&apos;s Jane. We met on Friday night and you gave me your number. Give me a call back when you get back from wherever you are. Speak to you soon. Bye.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Then she realised she&apos;d forgotten to leave her number, so she had to repeat the whole gruesome process.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">The rest of Sunday was a washout. She couldn&apos;t go out, she couldn&apos;t settle to anything. There was nothing on television. The phone rang twice for Donna, then again for Sue. Inevitably Sue then stayed on the phone for an eternity, retailing all the current news, gossip and plain speculation that she could muster regarding her wide circle of acquaintance. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">One day,</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7"> Jane thought, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T9">I&apos;m going to lose it completely and rip out that woman&apos;s larynx with my bare hands</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">. She tried to read a book but by the time she got to the end of a sentence she&apos;d already forgotten how it had begun. She had a go at the quick crossword in Donna&apos;s copy of the </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style36"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Observer. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style33"><text:span text:style-name="T7">None of the clues made any sense to her.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">In the evening the phone rang again, but it was only Tom wanting a post-mortem on the previous night. He&apos;d just got back from dropping Anna at Heathrow; he sounded relieved. She said she was busy but she&apos;d call him back, feeling ashamed at the lie.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She&apos;d given up and gone to bed by the time the phone rang again. Donna knocked on her door. &quot;It&apos;s for you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Freezing and cursing in the hallway, Jane took the phone. &quot;Hello?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Is that Jane?&quot; It was the Geordie.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s Phil.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh, hello.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;Sorry it took me so long to call you back. I was out.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;No problem.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;I didn&apos;t think you&apos;d call.&quot; It seemed to be a widespread assumption. Jane was beginning to wish it was true.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;No, well, I did. I mean, there&apos;s no point in getting someone&apos;s number and then not calling them, is there?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;I suppose not.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;So. Here I am.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;Right. Well. I believe I have something that belongs to you.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;Do you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;You don&apos;t mean to say you&apos;ve forgotten?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;I didn&apos;t even know your name was Phil until you just told me.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;Oh.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;Don&apos;t get me wrong,&quot; she said hastily, &quot;I don&apos;t usually carry on like that.&quot; Since she couldn&apos;t remember just how she had carried on, this was as specific as her denial could get.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;Aye. Well, the thing is, it&apos;s a bit embarrassing.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">A terrible sensation like a cascade of icy water began to pass through her. &quot;Is it?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;I mean, I&apos;m as broad-minded as the next bloke, but I&apos;ve never had a girl I&apos;d never met do that to me in a pub before.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">She cleared he throat. &quot;What did I do, exactly?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;You put your knickers in me breast pocket.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;Ah.&quot; So that was one little mystery cleared up. &quot;Was that before or after I asked for your number?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;That was before you&apos;d even spoken to me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;I like to make sure I have a man&apos;s attention,&quot; said Jane, trying to sound like Sarah Bernhardt.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;Well, it worked, I&apos;ll give you that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">Sometimes honesty is the only policy. &quot;Look, Phil, I&apos;m sorry. I was extremely drunk and I&apos;ve just split up with my boyfriend and, well, I&apos;m sorry. It&apos;s not really in character for me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;Don&apos;t worry about it,&quot; he said. &quot;It&apos;ll be something to tell me grandchildren.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;You have grandchildren?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;God no, I&apos;m only twenty-four.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T24">I wasn&apos;t that pissed then</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">, she thought.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;Anyway,&quot; he was saying, &quot;if you&apos;re not too embarrassed, I wouldn&apos;t mind seeing you again.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;Really?&quot; Her astonishment was genuine. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T22">&quot;Really.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Okay then.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Tell you what. Do you like Chinese food?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"><text:s/>&quot;Not really.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;How about Thai?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"><text:s/>&quot;All right.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He suggested a restaurant that as it happened she&apos;d been to a couple of times; it wasn&apos;t bad. They made a date for the following Friday.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;How will I recognise you?&quot; she remembered to ask before ringing off. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;ll be the one with the frilly handkerchief.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">If this ever gets back to my mother</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">, Jane reflected, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">my life won&apos;t be worth living</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">. On the other hand, the Sarah Bernhardt method still seemed to be getting results. She went back to bed feeling moderately pleased with her weekend. Marcie was right. It was all a question of positive thinking. Michael Ashe could rot in hell.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Unfortunately for her peace of mind, however, Michael Ashe was not rotting in hell. He was alive and well and staying with the woman he&apos;d always loved, and what was worse he&apos;d written to tell her all about it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane didn&apos;t get letters. She didn&apos;t even get bills, because everything was in Donna&apos;s name. The airmail envelope was waiting for her on the kitchen table, as conspicuous as a fish in the Sahara desert. As she picked it up she could feel Sue and Donna circling like vultures. Their curiosity was almost tangible. She said nothing at all, hardly even glanced at it, and left it where it was while she cooked herself her evening meal. There was an exquisite bittersweet pleasure in watching her flatmates squirm, Sue especially.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She even toyed with the idea of not opening it at all. It was hard to imagine what he could have to say to her that wouldn&apos;t be torture to read. Just seeing his writing on the envelope was bad enough. It wasn&apos;t fair. Michael and Madeleine had this blissful love and all she could manage was a drip whose hobby was looking down Anna&apos;s cleavage or a man who collected women&apos;s underwear.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">In the end, as she had always known she would have to, Jane opened the letter. It was dated from the café, which was a small crumb of comfort: at least he hadn&apos;t moved back in with her.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Dear Jane,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">This isn&apos;t an easy letter for me to write, but I wanted to try and get my thoughts and feelings into some sort of order. You&apos;re entitled to that.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I feel very bad about the way I&apos;ve treated you. I should have told you everything right from the start; you were bound to find out sooner or later, and in any case you had a right to know. But I was afraid of bringing up all my old feelings and the longer I left it the harder it got. In the end I&apos;m pleased that you found those letters. They probably explained it better than I could have done. Even now I don&apos;t think I could bear to re-read them myself.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Madeleine and I have been talking a lot. About old times, and about Micheline. And about you. She&apos;s desperately unhappy. As you probably guessed, Marcel has left her. He was like another father to Micheline; God knows what he&apos;s going through. So many lives have been destroyed though this. I don&apos;t want yours to be another one.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I can&apos;t leave Madeleine now while we&apos;re both grieving for our daughter. We need to do this together. I hope you can understand. She needs me, and I need her too. We were Micheline&apos;s parents and there are things nobody else can help us with. It&apos;s impossible to put it into words. I only hope you never find out what it&apos;s like from personal experience.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I don&apos;t know when I shall be coming back to London, but I do know that I will come back. My life isn&apos;t here any more. Madeleine understands. There&apos;s no going back. She and I will never have what we used to have: too much has happened, and we&apos;re different people.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Jane, I don&apos;t know how to ask you this. It feels like a hell of a lot to ask after everything I&apos;ve put you though, but when I do come back, will you still be there for me? At least think about it. If you don&apos;t want to see me again I&apos;ll understand. I&apos;m not trying to rush you into a decision. <text:s/>Take as long as you need. I&apos;m staying at Odile&apos;s, so you can write to me here, or call if you prefer.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">With love, </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Michael</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane sat on her bed in a state of shock. Then she read it again, twice. Amazingly enough it still said the same things.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Moving on automatic pilot she cleaned her teeth, undressed, got into bed and put the light out. After a while she put the light on again and read his letter another time for luck. It was difficult to believe but there it was in black and white. Well, all right, black and pale blue. She tried falling back on good old-fashioned sensible cynicism. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">Madeleine&apos;s chucked him, that&apos;s all.</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"> But she remembered only too well the look in Madeleine&apos;s beautiful eyes whenever she&apos;d looked at him. It wasn&apos;t the look of a woman who&apos;d hoped he had a return ticket.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane turned out the light once again. Sleep wasn&apos;t going to be easy, but she knew that in a few hours&apos; time she&apos;d wish she</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T18">&apos;d</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T7"> </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">had some.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The alarm-clock on her bedside table heralded the dawn chorus. She made it into work somehow, her head a fog of weariness and uncertainty. The bitter machine coffee burned her tongue. She had another one almost immediately, and then another. It didn&apos;t help.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Marcie was close to exploding with curiosity about the weekend. Sitting next to her was almost physically painful. Working was impossible. The words on the screen in front of her made no sense: she couldn&apos;t hold enough of them in her head at once. Sleep tugged at her constantly like a black tide sucking her down and down, several times almost overwhelming her during the weekly team meeting. She had even more coffee. All the time the words of his letter kept running through her head, over and over and over. She found herself typing them without realising and having to delete them again. By the time she left the office, Jane calculated she was probably slightly further away from finishing the tasks she had to do than she had been when she&apos;d arrived.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">There was no way she could avoid it: Marcie practically frog-marched her to the pub. Slumped in her chair while Marcie fetched the drinks, Jane felt she could sleep for at least twelve hours.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well then?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well what?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What happened?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane tried to explain about the telephone numbers, about the evening with Tom and Anna. She could hear her own voice as if it was someone else talking. She was aware that it wasn&apos;t very coherent. Her audience was becoming restive.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m sorry, Marcie, I&apos;m just really tired.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You&apos;re not getting out of here until you&apos;ve told me everything, you know. Sooner you spill the goods the sooner you&apos;ll get to bed.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;All right.&quot; She closed her eyes, and hastily opened them again before unconsciousness could strike. She told her about the Geordie, which went down rather better. Marcie almost howled with laughter.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Jesus, Jane, I used to think I was bad.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;There was something else. I had a letter from Michael.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh, forget Michael. He&apos;s history.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;He wants me back.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, he&apos;ll just have to join the back of the queue, won&apos;t he?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You don&apos;t understand,&quot; Jane said. Words came out of her mouth that she had not uttered since she was seventeen. &quot;I think I&apos;m in love.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Serious?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I think so.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Christ, we&apos;ll have to do something about that then.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What do you mean?&quot; Jane could feel her temper rising like the mercury in a thermometer.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You can&apos;t go back to that toe-rag after what he did to you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You keep going back to Paul.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;He keeps coming back to me. That&apos;s different.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Why shouldn&apos;t I get back together with Michael? I don&apos;t see it&apos;s any business of yours anyway.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Here, keep your wig on.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;And don&apos;t you ever refer to the man I love as a toe-rag.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Incandescent with rage, Jane marched out of the pub leaving her drink unfinished on the table. She lit her last cigarette. It tasted foul and she threw it away almost immediately. The anger was just enough fuel to get her back to the flat. She went straight to bed and fell gratefully into the black welcoming abyss.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Sometime in the early morning she came to again. It felt good. She put on her light and re-read Michael&apos;s letter. That was even better. Lying back in bed she began to compose her reply. It was a pleasure she intended to spin out for a long, long time.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">13</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Tom was fretting. It wasn&apos;t something he often did and it made him profoundly uncomfortable. For one thing, there was Michael. He&apos;d heard nothing since returning from France. Tom had no idea what he was going through, beyond the obvious fact that it was agony. Nobody he knew had ever lost a child. He wished there was something he could do for him, but nothing came to mind. His therapeutic repertoire was limited to taking people down the pub. This was beyond him.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Then there was Anna. She&apos;d been very cold at the airport when he&apos;d seen her off. He&apos;d done everything he could to please her but it didn&apos;t seem to be getting him very far. She had a way of looking at him that made him feel irredeemably second-rate. Worse than that, he was starting to believe it was true. Self-doubt was not a problem he was used to.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Finally he was deeply worried about Jane. She was doing her best to bounce back but you could see it wasn&apos;t really working. That bloke she&apos;d brought along had been a complete washout. He was very fond of Jane and really hoped it would all work out for her, but again there was nothing he could do. If there was any justice in the world then Jane of all the people he knew deserved to get a break, but he was beginning to be troubled by a terrible feeling that perhaps there might not be any justice after all.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He wandered around the empty flat, unable to concentrate on anything. Several times he thought about phoning Anna but he just couldn&apos;t face it. She had this way of being silent on the telephone that made him wish he&apos;d never been born. He didn&apos;t have a number for Michael, and in any case he wasn&apos;t sure he could handle what he might hear. Tom had sense enough to know when he was out of his depth. So in the end he called Jane.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He&apos;d expected her to be feeling rather down. She hadn&apos;t been at all happy about their foursome on Saturday; even though she&apos;d put a brave face on things he had still been able to tell. It was a shock to hear her sounding so cheerful. She might have been a completely different woman. It wasn&apos;t long before she&apos;d told him why. Tom had immediate misgivings.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Are you sure about this? I mean, you haven&apos;t misread the letter or anything? You know what his writing&apos;s like.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;ve read it at least twenty times. I know what it says, Tom.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I just don&apos;t think you ought to rush into anything.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Why? Do you think he might not really mean it?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t know. I&apos;m just worried.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Not like you to worry, Tom.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, I am. You and Michael are two of the people I care most about in the world and I&apos;d hate to see either of you getting hurt.&quot; Then he realised what he&apos;d just said. &quot;Oh God. Have I just made a complete arse of myself?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Not at all,&quot; she said. &quot;That&apos;s really sweet. You&apos;re such a lovely bloke, Tom.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I wish Anna thought so.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;If she doesn&apos;t then she hasn&apos;t got the sense she was born with. When I look at the tossers most of my friends seem to end up going out with, there&apos;s no comparison. She ought to thank her lucky stars.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Her words were like a healing elixir. &quot;Do you think so?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Definitely. I was so angry with her on Saturday night, the way she was treating you. I was quite hoping she&apos;d go off with Douglas. They deserve one another.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;God, did you think he was </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style22"><text:span text:style-name="T23">that </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">bad?&quot; They both laughed.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Seriously,&quot; Jane went on, &quot;I think you should chuck her. Find yourself a proper girlfriend who knows what you&apos;re worth. There must be loads of women who&apos;d give their right arm for a man like you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Not sure I fancy a girlfriend with only one arm.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You know what I mean.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Tom pondered this advice. &quot;Got anybody in mind?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, Madeleine&apos;s single.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Be serious.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well now. There&apos;s Donna. She isn&apos;t seeing anyone at the moment. You like them thin, don&apos;t you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Within reason.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Ah. Maybe not Donna, then; she&apos;s unreasonably thin. Oh, I know! Marcie&apos;s friend Siobhan. She&apos;s just split up with this bloke who was a complete drip, used to write her poetry and everything. Marcie said it used to make her throw up, although she may have been exaggerating. Anyway I bet she&apos;d go for you like a shot: good straightforward decent bloke, no hangups, bit of dosh. As long as you don&apos;t try comparing her to a summer&apos;s day, I don&apos;t see how it can fail.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Are you serious?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Unless you&apos;ve got something against redheads. Some men do, you know.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Not especially.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;They&apos;re supposed to have a fiery temper, apparently, but I don&apos;t think it applies in Siobhan&apos;s case. She&apos;s got a much longer fuse than I have. If I&apos;d had to put up with bad sonnets week in and week out he&apos;d have ended up in Casualty.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Anything else I ought to know about her?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Only her phone number. Hang on a minute, I&apos;ve got it here somewhere.&quot; Jane&apos;s address-book was short on names but long on disorganisation, so it always took her a while to unearth what she was looking for. It did have the advantage that the person on the other end of the phone had plenty of time to find a pen and paper. Eventually she came up with the number and Tom dutifully wrote it down.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">By this time Jane felt she was on a roll. &quot;Tell you what,&quot; she said, &quot;I&apos;ll phone her myself first. Soften her up a bit.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Are you sure about all this?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Of course. I can&apos;t imagine why I didn&apos;t think of it before.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">As soon as she&apos;d put down the phone she was dialling Siobhan&apos;s number. She&apos;d never played Cupid before. At various times in her life other people had tried it on her, and she&apos;d always resented it deeply, but she was enjoying herself so much it never occurred to her to wonder how Siobhan or indeed Tom might feel about it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">If Siobhan thought that Jane was drunk or otherwise chemically unstable, she was too polite to say so. She listened patiently to a long encomium on Tom, his honesty, good-heartedness, generosity, and many other virtues which he may or may not have possessed but which Jane thought would sound inviting. When eventually Jane paused for a reaction, however, it all fell a bit flat.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Did Marcie not tell you, then? We&apos;re back together.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What do you mean? You and that what&apos;s-his-name?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Colin.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Are you sure?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Of course I&apos;m sure.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane floundered. &quot;I thought he made you sick.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What&apos;s that supposed to mean?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Look, you don&apos;t want to go messing about with poets. This guy has an MBA from Harvard.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t care. Colin&apos;s asked me to marry him and I&apos;ve said yes.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You said what? Are you out of your mind?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&apos;Jane, I don&apos;t want to seem rude or anything, but is this any of your business?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane had to admit she had a point there. &quot;Maybe not. I&apos;m sorry. It just came as a bit of a shock, that&apos;s all.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Even my parents took it better than that.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Sorry. Congratulations.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Thanks. Was there anything else? It&apos;s just I&apos;ve got a casserole in the oven.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No. Okay then. Be seeing you.&quot; She briefly thought of sending love to Colin, but realised it might sound a bit hollow.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Somewhat crestfallen she called Tom back. He was okay about it. Indeed she thought she detected a hint of relief.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Come on,&quot; he said, &quot;I&apos;ll buy you a drink.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What, now?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s only half-past eight. Do you have to ask your mother?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">It was much better going for a drink with Tom without Anna, to say nothing of Douglas. He was his old self again. She showed him Michael&apos;s letter and he agreed it meant what she&apos;d said it meant. Sharing it was pure pleasure. It was so good to watch him reading, knowing that he understood, really understood. When he&apos;d finished, she read it again herself. The novelty still hadn&apos;t worn off.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I must write back before he changes his mind,&quot; she said, not that she was at all worried about that possibility.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;He won&apos;t.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I still can&apos;t believe it. I really thought he&apos;d go back to her.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I didn&apos;t,&quot; Tom said unexpectedly. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Why not?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;ve known Michael a long time. Meeting her changed him completely, you know. He was really quite outgoing when I first knew him. Then they got together and he was very happy at first, but — well, you know what happened. When I came back from the States he was a mess. Because he was left that money and obviously he left his job he had nothing to do but think about it all. There were times he drank like it was going out of fashion. It was </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">scary, to be honest. I wanted to help but he wouldn&apos;t talk about anything. Until you showed me those letters I only knew one or two pieces of the story. Now and again he&apos;d let odd things slip; I knew there was a child, but I didn&apos;t even know if it was a boy or a girl. And I&apos;m the best friend he&apos;s got, or was until you came along.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You rescued him from all that. It was like a miracle. Suddenly he was taking an interest in life. He started eating properly, and cooking again. He&apos;d always used to love his food but when he was down he didn&apos;t care what he ate or if he ate at all. God knows I don&apos;t exactly have a healthy lifestyle myself, and even I thought he was getting pretty bad. Then you come along and wham, chicken provençale.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;But she was still there, in the background,&quot; Jane pointed out. &quot;I could tell there was something. It was driving me nuts.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;She was still there, but for the first time he had an alternative. You know, he used to disappear into his room for days and I&apos;d never see him, like he&apos;d been put into solitary confinement. Sometimes I felt like I should be sliding bread and water under the door. He was punishing himself. At the time, of course, I didn&apos;t know why. But when he met you I think he thought that maybe he&apos;d suffered enough. You remember that night he first met you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m not likely to forget it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;We came home and I was a bit pissed-off because I&apos;d thought I was in and then I&apos;d been given the thanks-but-no-thanks routine by your mate. So I hadn&apos;t really thought it had been much of a success, but then I saw the expression on his face and I thought: </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T26">Aye aye, something&apos;s going on here</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">. I didn&apos;t say anything, of course. Then I came back from Zurich and I was even more pissed-off, thanks to Anna, but he was so different, it was amazing.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;That was the night it all started.&quot; Jane could feel herself blushing slightly in a manner that could only be described as virginal.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Anyway, I suppose what I&apos;m trying to say is that I could see how important you were to him, maybe more clearly than you could. Going back to Madeleine would have been like going back into solitary, in a way.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;She still loves him, you know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t know that love is enough, on its own.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You&apos;re philosophical all of a sudden.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Tom smiled, a little distantly. It looked surprisingly good on him. &quot;If love was enough, they&apos;d never have broken up in the first place, would they? You read her letters.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Perhaps you&apos;re right.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He finished his drink. &quot;Fancy another?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;ll get this.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Tom watched her go up to the bar. She was exactly the sort of woman you would want for your best friend, he decided. Even if he hadn&apos;t known their previous history, he would have felt a bit edgy about Madeleine. There&apos;s a limit to how beautiful other people&apos;s girlfriends can decently be. Perhaps Jane thought that way about Anna? At any rate she was undoubtedly right about her, and for that he was grateful. Sometimes you need someone to tell you not to be such an idiot. Not for the first time in his life he&apos;d fallen for an attractive surface without waiting to find out what might be underneath. There was a lesson in there somewhere, but as Jane had pointed out it wasn&apos;t his way to be unduly philosophical.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Perhaps she&apos;d read his mind, because her first words when she came back with the drinks were: &quot;So what are you going to do about Anna?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Write her a letter, I suppose.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Coward.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You don&apos;t know what she&apos;s like on the phone. Scare anyone.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;That&apos;s not the point. It&apos;s the principle of the thing. If you&apos;re going to dump someone you should do it face to face if you can, or at least phone them.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, if you insist I&apos;ll phone her. But I won&apos;t enjoy it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Who said anything about enjoying it? These things just have to be done sometimes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Reluctantly Tom agreed. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">The trouble with Jane</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">, he thought,</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25"> is that she won&apos;t let you get away with things</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">. In theory this was one of her good points. Well: if he had enough to drink first even Anna could be faced. And Jane was right: it had to be done.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">On Friday night Jane raced to the phone, hoping it might be Michael. It was for her, but at first she didn&apos;t recognise the voice.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Jane?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"><text:s/>&quot;Yes?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s Phil here.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">It took her a moment to work this one out. &quot;Oh my God, I&apos;m sorry, I completely forgot.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Don&apos;t worry about it. I&apos;m in the restaurant. Come on over.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Give me half an hour.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No problem.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane was in such a panic that it wasn&apos;t until she was actually on the bus that she remembered the basis on which she and Phil were acquainted. Her track record of remembering things where he was concerned was pretty abysmal; you&apos;d think a thing like that would have stuck in your mind, she told herself reprovingly. She couldn&apos;t even remember what he looked like. Had he even told her?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The restaurant was packed. She looked around her for a man sitting on his own who might have struck her as passably attractive when she was extremely drunk. Given that she&apos;d apparently fancied Douglas, this second criterion wasn&apos;t likely to narrow it down much. There was a man with a beard over in that corner smiling at her. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">Oh Christ, what was I drinking?</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"> She went over to him.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Hi, Jane.&quot; The smile got bigger.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Phil.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I hope you&apos;re hungry,&quot; he said. &quot;I&apos;m starving.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;ve already eaten, actually.&quot; This was a complete fabrication.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh. Well, have a drink or something.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I won&apos;t stop.&quot; She took a breath. &quot;Look, this has all been a mistake. I&apos;m sorry.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m just as bad. Forget me own head if it wasn&apos;t screwed on.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t just mean sorry about forgetting tonight. I mean, I </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">am</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"> sorry about that, don&apos;t get me wrong. But — well, something&apos;s happened.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Boyfriend made a come-back, has he?&quot; He was trying not to show it, but she could tell he was disappointed.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Something like that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Phil took a small gift-wrapped parcel out of his pocket. &quot;Yours, I think.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Thanks.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Sure you won&apos;t stay for a drink?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;d better not.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No. Well, it was nice meeting you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes. Remember me to your grandchildren.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">When she got home she opened the parcel to find he&apos;d bought her a pair of Janet Reger. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">Well</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">, she thought, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">there&apos;s no harm in being an optimist</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">. For about half an hour she felt horribly guilty about the whole episode and then she decided to blame it all on Marcie. This cheered her up considerably. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">I&apos;ll wear them for Michael when he gets back</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">, she thought, and this idea cheered her up even more. Life could be a lot worse.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">14</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">It was raining, and had been all morning: a thin mournful rain which apparently intended to go on for ever. Although it was only a short walk Michael was thoroughly and miserably wet by the time he reached the crooked little house beside the church. It looked as if it might slide into ruins at any moment, but then it had probably looked that way for centuries and it was still standing somehow. Mme Godefroy, the curé&apos;s respectably voluminous housekeeper, answered the door unsmilingly. Michael could not remember ever having seen her smile; he had once suggested jokingly that her lips had been sewn together into a permanently disapproving purse. Madeleine had been scandalised.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;He&apos;s in his study,&quot; said Mme Godefroy, eager to imply that Michael was interrupting important ecclesiastical business. &quot;I&apos;ll wait.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">With the utmost reluctance, Mme Godefroy let him in and bustled off to inform Father Lautier of his arrival. Much as Michael had imagined, the old man had had his feet up with a pre-luncheon glass of red wine and a dog-eared copy of Bruyère&apos;s </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style22"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Characters. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Hospitably the old man invited him to stay to lunch, but he declined.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;This must be a very difficult time for you, my son.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You know my opinions perfectly well, and I shan&apos;t rehearse them again. Of course I would have preferred you to be reconciled with the Church and to have taken the sacrament of marriage, and I know Madeleine shares that view, but that&apos;s between you and God.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I suppose it is.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I hear you&apos;re going back to England.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael smiled. &quot;Is there anything that happens here that you don&apos;t know about?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The curé&apos;s nut-brown eyes smiled back. &quot;Not much, perhaps.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;My life is in London now, Father. I can&apos;t do anything about the past but perhaps I can do something for the future.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Father Lautier nodded. &quot;I know you to be a good man, Michel. In the eyes of the Church you have sinned, but which of us has not? If you came here for my blessing, you shall certainly have it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Thank you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;And Madeleine? What does she make of your decision?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;She accepts it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;That wasn&apos;t quite what I asked you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael looked down. &quot;She doesn&apos;t want me to go. She&apos;s said outright that she wants me to stay here and marry her, and, well, to have another baby.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I see.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Father, I can&apos;t do it. I just can&apos;t. Even if I did what she asked, we could never replace Micheline.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Do you think that is what she&apos;s asking you to do?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I think she&apos;s asking for a second chance.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;There is always a second chance with God. And a third, and a fourth, and as many chances as you need. That is the nature of love.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;In that case,&quot; Michael concluded unhappily, &quot;I no longer love her.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So you are going back to this English girl? Jane, was that her name? Old Jean-Marie was very taken with her.&quot; He laughed his dry, old man&apos;s laugh. &quot;If he was twenty years younger, you&apos;d have had a fight on your hands there.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I believe that Jane is my second chance.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;For your sake, I hope so, my son.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You will look after her, won&apos;t you? Madeleine?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Father Lautier smiled gently. &quot;Of course. The care of souls is my business.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Afterwards Michael never mentioned this conversation to anyone, but it was then that he finally made his decision. Even though he had had no answer from Jane, he knew he had to go now or not at all. It would be easier if he got it over quickly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Madeleine had offered to drive him to the ferry, but he thought it better to go with Odile. They stood outside the side door to the café, taking their final awkward leave of one another. He could see she was determined not to cry. She stood as she had stood at the funeral, alone, beautiful, proud in her aloneness and her beauty but also unbearably vulnerable. More than anything in the world he wanted to hold her and comfort her. Only his blind faith in his occasional angel kept him apart from her, his arms hanging uselessly at his sides.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Will you write to me?&quot; she asked.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t think that&apos;s a good idea.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I see.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s not the way you think.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh, and how do I think?&quot; There was a little of the old fire still burning. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m not trying to punish you for anything. Not for Marcel, not for the accident. Certainly not for having been the mother of my child.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style22"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Our </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">child.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;This isn&apos;t easy for me either.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Easy? Of course it&apos;s easy. You can go away to your own country, to your flat and your inheritance and your charming English girlfriend. What have I got? Where am I going to go? There isn&apos;t a soul in this town who doesn&apos;t know all of my business. I can&apos;t walk across the square without people nudging one another, whispering. You have no idea what it&apos;s like, do you? It&apos;s all very well for you. You can just walk away from it. Well, I don&apos;t have that luxury. This is my home. It&apos;s all I&apos;ve got.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I can&apos;t change the past.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No, but there&apos;s such a thing as repentance, or did they not teach you that when you were learning your catechism?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Do you think I haven&apos;t suffered?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t think you know what suffering is.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Her anger was between them like a steel shutter. A few metres down the street Odile was trying to start her car, always a hit-and-miss operation. It was time for him to be going.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m sorry,&quot; he said. &quot;I didn&apos;t want it to end like this.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Go and catch your damned boat,&quot; she said in a voice like broken glass. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The engine of the 2CV stuttered into life and he turned away from her, turned away and without looking back walked at a measured pace to the car. It was over.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Tom&apos;s German had never been very good, but if he was going to dump Anna the least he could do was do it in her own language. She spoke excellent English, in addition to French, Italian and probably several other languages: the only problem was she couldn&apos;t say a kind word in any of them. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He sat down with the telephone, his address-book, and a large glass of brandy. He&apos;d already worked out what he was going to say, written it all out and checked it twice with his German dictionary. If anything it sounded even more vicious in German than it had in English. He took a goodly sip of his drink and began to dial.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">After he had said his piece there was one of Anna&apos;s dreadful silences. Finally she said, in English:</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So. Is that all?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Then, quite suddenly, she burst into floods of tears. Tom had never been at his best in this kind of situation, and was uncomfortably aware of it. It was doubly worse because he hadn&apos;t expected her to react like this. Anger, yes; icy sarcasm, perhaps, but not this.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Don&apos;t cry,&quot; he said, uselessly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m sorry,&quot; she said. &quot;I&apos;m sorry.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s all right.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m sorry,&quot; she kept saying.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No, I&apos;m sorry. I didn&apos;t think you&apos;d take it like this.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">After some time she seemed to recover. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Do you want to call me back?&quot; he asked. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No, it&apos;s okay.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Tom fortified himself with another slug of brandy. &quot;I feel terrible about this.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s okay, I understand.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You do?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I should have known from the start. It&apos;s that blonde, isn&apos;t it?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What is?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, I hope you&apos;re very happy together.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"><text:s/>&quot;Anna, what are you talking about?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Don&apos;t lie to me. I could see what she was after.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"><text:s/>A dim light began to dawn. &quot;Who, Jane?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Whatever her name is. I don&apos;t care. Her sort are common enough. But I thought at least</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style18"><text:span text:style-name="T7"> </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style18"><text:span text:style-name="T33">you</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style18"><text:span text:style-name="T7"> </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">had some good taste.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;There&apos;s nothing going on between me and Jane.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh, just good friends?&quot; Her voice would have cut through steel. &quot;Don&apos;t insult me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;But Anna —&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Goodbye.&quot; The phone went down with some vehemence.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">So that was that. He sat for a moment in some dismay. It had never crossed his mind that Anna might really have cared for him. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">Women, eh?</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"> He shook his head, refilled his glass, and switched on the TV. He might just catch the end of the rugby highlights.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane had made several attempts to write her reply. Love-letters had never been her forte; indeed, she couldn&apos;t remember ever having written one before. For a long time she was stuck on the very opening line. &quot;Dear Michael&quot; sounded too formal. &quot;Michael darling&quot; was too much like Madeleine, and in any case she never called him darling, or anyone else for that matter. It was her mother&apos;s word. &quot;Beloved&quot; was even worse: the sort of thing they put on tombstones. She settled for her original idea.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Dear Michael,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I&apos;m sorry it&apos;s taken me so long to reply to your letter. It came as something of a surprise.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Ought she to leave that in? Sarah Bernhardt would have taken his return for granted. Then again maybe Sarah Bernhardt wasn&apos;t proving to be the best role-model. Jane felt more comfortable just being Jane. She went on:</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T7">I thought I&apos;d lost you forever, and that was very hard to bear. Only when I got your letter and realised there was still hope did I find out what you mean to me.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">That was a bit more like it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I haven&apos;t said this to anyone and meant it since I was still at school, and I don&apos;t think I&apos;ve ever said it in writing, but I love you.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She re-read that part to make sure it made sense, and then again to see if she really had the nerve to tell him. Even though she was cold sober, she was surprised to find that she did. It wasn&apos;t difficult at all, now she came to it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I didn&apos;t want to admit it even to myself, especially when it looked as if you were certain to stay with Madeleine <text:s/>She has such a claim on you and I&apos;ve known you for such a short time, <text:s/>I assumed it would be a no-contest. Men don&apos;t choose me when they have the chance of someone else.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Hang on, this was self-pity. Sarah Bernhardt would definitely not approve.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T7">That isn&apos;t self-pity, that&apos;s just been the story of my life. <text:s/>You&apos;ve changed all that. If it was your angel who prompted you to stay with me, then it&apos;s my angel too. Thank her for me, if it is a she. Somehow I think it is.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T7">Of course I&apos;ll be here for you when you come back. I can understand what you said about needing to grieve for your little girl. Take whatever time you need.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">That was as far as she&apos;d got when the phone rang.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s me,&quot; said the voice of a man who sounded as though he was frying eggs somewhere in the region of Alpha Centauri.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Who&apos;s me?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Me. Michael.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh God. Michael.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Are you okay?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You&apos;ll have to speak up, it&apos;s a terrible line.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You what?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I said you&apos;ll have to speak up.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I can&apos;t hear you,&quot; he said. &quot;You&apos;ll have to speak up.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane took a deep breath. &quot;Michael, where are you?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m on the train.&quot; This baffled her for a moment, then she remembered the massively expensive pay-phones they had on some trains these days.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Which train?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I said: I&apos;m on the train.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes, but which train? Where are you?&quot; She could hear her voice going out of control, hysterical even.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m coming home.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You what?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I said, I&apos;m coming home.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I love you,&quot; she bawled. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You what?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I LOVE YOU.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Sorry, I&apos;m going to have to ring you back. I&apos;ll call you from the flat, okay?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The line went dead. Very quietly, Jane said the rudest word she knew and put the phone down. She went back to her bedroom, passing Donna who was trying so hard to look as if she hadn&apos;t heard anything that it was worse than anything she might have said. Well: her secret was out now. The people across the street had probably heard her. In fact just about the only person who hadn&apos;t heard her was Michael.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She re-read her letter, such as it was. There didn&apos;t seem to be much point in sending it now, but she was too sentimental to throw it away. Jane opened her wardrobe and considered her plan of campaign. There seemed to be an awful lot of clothes in there for someone who never had anything to wear. What was it to be? The grand seduction? Too obvious. What, then? Smart but available? Always a good idea in theory but not so easy in practice. Casual? </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">The man I love is coming all the way from France just to be with me, and I&apos;m casual? I don&apos;t think so. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T28">Marcie used to say there were two kinds of clothes: the ones you put on in order to wear them and the ones you put on in order to take them off again.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">Sod it, let&apos;s go for the works. Janet Reger, come on down.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Hot water, or rather the lack of it, was an unending source of domestic strife. The boiler had been designed in the 1950s, when postwar austerity was still in and the idea of bathing more than once a month was regarded as Babylonian excess. Even if long years of overuse and lack of maintenance had not taken their inevitable toll, it would never have been equal to the task of supplying three smart and socially active young women with all the baths they would like. In consequence, having a bath was not something to be done on impulse. Hours, if not days, of intense negotiation were required to ensure that no other parties would be deprived of their rightful share of hot water. The only reason Sue was living there at all was that her predecessor had been expelled for the unforgivable sin of unilateral bathing.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">This placed Jane in a delicate position. If she&apos;d known when Michael was supposed to be arriving, she might have had time to take her things over to his place and change there. As it was he might turn up while she was still in the middle of getting ready. Not that she had a problem with him seeing her naked, it was just that she wanted him to undress her first. Anyway, they only had a shower and Jane wanted a proper bath. She knocked on Donna&apos;s door.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Is it okay if I have a bath?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s not your turn until Thursday.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I know, but it&apos;s kind of a special occasion.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Donna&apos;s eyebrows went up. It was an expression she&apos;d been wearing a lot recently. Jane had been tempted more than once to suggest that if the wind changed she&apos;d stay like that, but this was a moment for diplomacy.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You know Michael?&quot; Jane said cautiously. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Is he that guy who keeps phoning you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes. Well, he&apos;s been away, abroad, and now he&apos;s coming back. I&apos;m sorry it&apos;s all a bit short notice but I only just found out myself.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So you two </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style22"><text:span text:style-name="T23">are </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">an item then. Sue&apos;s going to be pleased.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"><text:s/>&quot;Why?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;She&apos;s got a fiver on it.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You what?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I thought it was easy money. I mean, no offence, Jane, but you&apos;re not exactly the romantic type, are you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;At least I don&apos;t look like a stick-insect!&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Do you want this bath or not?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Okay, okay, I take that back. Sorry.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">With much wheezing and groaning from the boiler, the bath began to fill with slightly brownish water. Jane added someone else&apos;s bubble-bath, presumably Sue&apos;s because Donna inclined to natural herbal extracts and this had come straight out of a chemical plant. She didn&apos;t like to think what it might be doing to the environment but at least it made the water a more acceptable colour. With a sigh of pure luxury she lowered herself in. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">Showers are all very well</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">, she thought, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">but there&apos;s nothing quite like a good hot bath</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">. She lay back, closed her eyes, and let the healing waters do their stuff.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">It was at this point that the phone rang.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Donna&apos;s muffled voice came through the door. &quot;It&apos;s Michael.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Tell him I&apos;ll call him back.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;He says it&apos;s important.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Just a minute.&quot; </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">This had better be good</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">, she thought, hauling herself out of the bath. The world which a moment ago had been deliciously warm now felt like Antarctica. She wrapped herself less than adequately in a towel and padded out into the hall.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Hello,&quot; she said. &quot;You made it back all right, then?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes,&quot; he said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I got your letter.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Did you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;And?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well. Here I am.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes.&quot; He&apos;d evidently lost none of his conversational flair. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I was in the bath, actually.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh, I&apos;m sorry. I didn&apos;t realise.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It doesn&apos;t matter.&quot; Icy water was trickling down the back of her neck, along her spine, and making its way down her legs to the hall carpet. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Have you had dinner yet?&quot; he asked. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No, not yet.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So would you like to come over, maybe? I could cook something.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;d love to.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Okay. I&apos;ll have a look and see what there is. You know what Tom&apos;s like for shopping.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Is he there?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes, but he said something about going out later.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">Good old Tom. What a gent.</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"> &quot;I&apos;ll be over in about three-quarters of an hour,&quot; she said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Great. I&apos;ll see you then.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes. I lo—&quot; Too late: he&apos;d put the phone down.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">It took her an age to get ready. For some reason she found it impossible to concentrate. She begged the use of Donna&apos;s hair-drier because her own had a tendency to blow its fuse. It was difficult to suppress a nagging feeling that Donna found the whole performance rather amusing, which wasn&apos;t improving her temper. Eventually she reached a point where she thought she was just about presentable.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;How do I look?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Donna looked her over with a practised eye. &quot;You&apos;ll do.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Thanks. Say sorry to Sue for me, about the bath.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No worries. Have a great evening, honey. We won&apos;t wait up.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">On the bus she almost passed out. She could hardly breathe, partly because she&apos;d chosen a dress that was slightly too tight on her but mostly from sheer adolescent nerves. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">For God&apos;s sake, Jane</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">, she told herself sternly, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">pull yourself together. You&apos;re a big girl now. Rather too big, as a matter of fact. I really must start going to the gym.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Finally there she was, standing in front of his door. She pressed the button. Nothing happened. She pressed it again, for longer. Finally the buzzer sounded and she could go in. He was waiting for her at the top of the stairs.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You look wonderful,&quot; he said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So do you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Me? I&apos;m just in my ordinary clothes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I know.&quot; She stood there like an idiot, wondering what happened next. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Dinner&apos;s almost ready. Would you like a glass of wine?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Please.&quot; She followed him timidly into the kitchen. &quot;Michael, there&apos;s something I&apos;ve got to tell you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh Christ.&quot; He sat down suddenly. &quot;You&apos;re not — I mean, you can&apos;t be? Are you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Am I what?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Pregnant.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Good God, no.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He relaxed. &quot;Thank God for that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She sat down beside him. &quot;It&apos;s not that. It&apos;s — oh, I don&apos;t know how to say this, it&apos;s really difficult.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What is it?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;ve never said this to anyone before, not properly.&quot; She felt for his hand. It was hot and slightly damp. Jane took a breath.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I love you,&quot; he said, and took her breath away again.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;That was supposed to be my line,&quot; she said as soon as she recovered.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Did your angel tell you?”</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I knew anyway.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Tom was in the back of a taxi on his way to a flat somewhere in the direction of Islington, blissfully untroubled by thoughts of Switzerland, the legal profession, or anything but the agreeable sensations of the moment. A blonde and rather fetching lady doctor was sitting on his lap and offering only token resistance to his attempts to undress her. He&apos;d never been one for drinking on his own.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Some hours later, as they lay in a warm post-coital drowse, Jane finally steeled herself to ask after Madeleine.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;She&apos;s angry. Mostly with me. Partly with God, I think.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Will she be all right?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t know. I hope so.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I feel guilty, taking you away from her.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Don&apos;t be. It was meant to happen.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;All of it? Micheline and everything?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t know. There has to be some point to it all, doesn&apos;t there? Otherwise it would just be unbearable.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">There was a thoughtful silence. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Do you believe in God?&quot; she asked.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I used to. I suppose I still do, in a way. I was brought up as a Catholic.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I didn&apos;t know that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It was my mother&apos;s idea. What about you? Do you believe in anything?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m not sure.&quot; She pressed herself against his body. &quot;Well, I believe in this.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I wish that was enough for me,&quot; he said sadly. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Won&apos;t it do to be going on with?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes. Yes, I think it will.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">15</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">There was one last letter, addressed to both of them at the flat where they now lived together, Tom having decamped to Islington.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Dear Michel and Jane,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">I hope you will not mind my writing to you but I thought you would want to know. My poor sister Madeleine passed away this morning. She had been ill for a long time and I believe it was a mercy in the end. She never really recovered from the shock of what happened to little Micheline. <text:s/>None of us has, in truth.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Her last request was that I should send both of you her love and blessings, and ask you to say prayers for her soul. She will be buried next to Micheline, as was her wish. No date has been fixed yet for the funeral. I do not know if you will want to attend.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Best wishes,</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Letter"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style14"><text:span text:style-name="T6">Pauline</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Between"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael read it in silence, and handed it to Jane. She took rather longer to read it, although her command of written French was pretty good these days.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Do you want to go?&quot; she asked him.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t know. Do you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I feel like we owe it to her.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Then we&apos;ll go.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The whole experience was very strange, familiar and yet unfamiliar. They went by air to spare Jane&apos;s stomach, and stayed at a new and impersonal hotel twenty-odd kilometres away from the town itself. Michael had hired a car, a rather grand maroon Citroën which made Jane feel as if she were a visiting dignitary. She&apos;d never been to a Catholic service before and was nervous about doing the wrong thing. In her specially bought black suit she felt very foreign and conspicuous.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael seemed very calm in comparison. He introduced her to the family, and to Marcel, who was looking as pale as a corpse himself; he acted as interpreter and almost as master of ceremonies. He might have been one of the undertakers. Throughout the service he gave her discreet prompts as to what to do next. She was grateful for his help but couldn&apos;t help feeling a little concerned at his lack of emotion.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">It was a beautiful day, incongruously so. They stood beside the open grave listening to the worn voice of Father Lautier and the singing of birds. Jane&apos;s gaze strayed to Micheline&apos;s </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">tiny grave just a few feet away, the golden letters shining on the gleaming black stone. She couldn&apos;t help herself: the tears wouldn&apos;t stay in. Dimly she was aware of Michael&apos;s fingers gripping hers. The old priest went on and on. She assumed he was saying the same sort of thing they said at English funerals. Other women were crying too. It was horrible.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Afterwards Michael took her straight back to the hotel. He suggested lunch but she couldn&apos;t face it. For a while she just lay on the bed and wept while he held her. Eventually the tears ran out, as they always do in the end.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m sorry,&quot; she said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s okay.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I didn&apos;t think it would affect me like this.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"><text:s/>&quot;It&apos;s okay,&quot; he said again.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He fetched her a glass of water, which helped a little. She sat up to drink it, which helped even more.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;How about you? How are you feeling?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He shook his head. &quot;I don&apos;t know. It&apos;s odd. It&apos;s as if none of it&apos;s really happening.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Maybe it will catch up with you later.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Maybe.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">They sat out on the hotel terrace and had an omelette and a bottle of crisp white wine. Jane was beginning to feel like a human being again. She had changed out of her mourning clothes but Michael still wore his, although he&apos;d discarded the jacket. On a day like this it was hard to believe that the world could really be so sad a place.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m going to burn her letters,&quot; he said, out of nowhere. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Don&apos;t do that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No, I should have done it years ago.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;But don&apos;t you want something to remember her by?&quot; As soon as she&apos;d said it, Jane realised what a fatuous question it was.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t think there&apos;s any danger I&apos;ll forget her,&quot; he said, smiling sadly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I still think you should keep them.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Why?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Because — I don&apos;t know. Because she deserves it. Because when something that big happens in your life, you have to respect it. It&apos;s part of who you are. You can&apos;t make it not have happened, Michael.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I know that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;And she was a lovely person.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You hardly knew her.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well enough. I don&apos;t cry at funerals normally. I hate crying in public. But I cried for her.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He was looking at her strangely, as if he&apos;d never seen her before. &quot;Yes, you did, didn&apos;t you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I couldn&apos;t believe you were so calm. You were the calmest person there.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;ve already grieved for her,&quot; he said quietly. &quot;For me she&apos;s been dead for a long time.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You still kept her letters, though, didn&apos;t you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes, that&apos;s true.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So why not keep them now?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Because now I&apos;m with you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;And I want you to keep them. I want </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style22"><text:span text:style-name="T23">us </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">to keep them. They&apos;re part of my history too, now.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;History? Yes, I suppose they are history, in a way.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">“Maybe one day someone else will find them,&quot; Jane mused, &quot;our great-grandchildren or something, they&apos;ll turn up in an attic, and the story will be told all over again.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s a very ordinary sort of story.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Not when it&apos;s your life.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">They fell silent for a while. The waiter came and took their plates away, poured out the last of the wine. The afternoon wore gently on.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">They decided to take a stroll along the bank of the little river which ran past the hotel. It was becoming uncomfortably warm. Midges were dancing underneath the trees. London seemed a very long way away. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">Well</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">, she thought, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">I suppose it </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style22"><text:span text:style-name="T27">is </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">a long way away. Another country.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What makes you think,&quot; Michael enquired delicately, &quot;that we&apos;ll have any great-grandchildren?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;People do.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;There isn&apos;t something you aren&apos;t telling me?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane smiled. &quot;Relax. I&apos;m not pregnant, as far as I know.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Just checking.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">They walked on a little further, and then she said:</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Would you like me to be? I mean, not now, but someday?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Come on, I bet you&apos;ve thought about it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"><text:s/>He wouldn&apos;t meet her eye. &quot;Perhaps.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Is that perhaps you would, or perhaps you&apos;ve thought about it?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Perhaps I would.&quot; Michael put his hands in his pockets. &quot;What about you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Me? God, no. I&apos;m hardly the maternal type.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, maybe one day.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">They came to an old stone bridge and stood watching the river pass beneath them until it felt as if the bridge was moving and the river was staying still. There were dragonflies hunting at the water&apos;s edge. Somewhere in the distance was a cuckoo. It struck Jane as odd that they had English birds over here. Of course national boundaries aren&apos;t such an issue when you can fly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So,&quot; he said, still not looking at her, &quot;I suppose you expect me to make an honest woman of you first.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Bit late for that, isn&apos;t it?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m asking you to marry me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh.&quot; She hadn&apos;t thought he was serious.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Unless you think it&apos;s too soon,&quot; he added quickly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s not that. I&apos;ve never been asked before, that&apos;s all.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">They stood and watched the river for a bit. The water was so clear that you could see fish moving through the weeds. One rose and took a fly right in front of them. It was difficult for Jane to focus her thoughts, what with the heat and the hypnotic movement of the water. She tried to think how she would like her life to be. Living together seemed to be working out all right so far. She&apos;d turned twenty-six: it was a reasonable sort of age.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">A sudden thought occurred to her. &quot;I don&apos;t have to become a Catholic or anything, do I?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Not on my account.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;All right then,&quot; said Jane.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">And that was that.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">16</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">At least, Jane had thought that was that. She reckoned without the unstoppable juggernaut into which her mother transformed herself, seemingly overnight. It was in vain that she protested that they just wanted a quiet registry-office job. Mrs Sharp had made up her mind long ago: her daughter was going to have Mendelssohn, orange blossom, pageboys, the full works.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Battle was joined as soon as they began to talk about the dress. Jane hated white: it made her look ill, and in any case she resented the implication that she&apos;d been saving herself all these years. She would have preferred pale blue, but her mother was having none of it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;White was good enough for me,&quot; she said firmly, as if this proved something.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;ll look awful.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s traditional.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t care.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well your father and I do, don&apos;t we, Arthur?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Let her have what she wants,&quot; her father suggested mildly. &quot;It&apos;s her wedding.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Don&apos;t be ridiculous,&quot; his wife snapped.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael, of course, was no use at all in these controversies. He seemed ready to submit to any indignities provided he could get the thing done. In a way this was quite sweet but it wasn&apos;t much help from Jane&apos;s point of view. She tried to hold out for ivory.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;That&apos;s so common these days,&quot; her mother objected. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, maybe there&apos;s a reason for that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;And you know what people are like. They&apos;re bound to make something of it.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;And what are they going to make of it if I look as if I&apos;m about to throw up?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Jane dear, don&apos;t be vulgar.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;That&apos;s how I&apos;ll look in white. I always do.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">It was no good. Mrs Sharp wanted white, she wanted satin and lace, she wanted a train the size of a football pitch. At the fitting Jane felt like a cross between a half-erected marquee and a cake in the process of being iced. It wouldn&apos;t have surprised her if someone had started putting glacé cherries round her neckline. As a piece of engineering, the dress her mother had chosen struck her as dangerously unsound, being held up largely by romantic </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">idealism. One false move could bring the whole structure down around her ankles, which was not a prospect she relished. And apart from anything else it was based on the assumption that she would lose half a stone between now and the big day. Personally Jane thought it was more likely that she would turn into a frog.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael had invited his mother and stepfather over from the States, and to everyone&apos;s astonishment they accepted. He was going to meet them at Heathrow and drive them up in a hire car. Of the numerous things which could go horribly wrong this seemed to be one of the more likely ones. Jane began to see why Madeleine had turned to religion. If Michael really did have a guardian angel, she undoubtedly earned her money. Still, he&apos;d made it once before without any loss of life, so perhaps he could do it again. There was only so much that Jane could worry about.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">One of the main things she was worrying about was the expense. The Sharps were comfortably off, but surely there was a limit. She made several attempts to broach this with her father, but he just made soothing noises and changed the subject. This only worried her all the more. The way her mother was carrying on there&apos;d be Dame Kiri Te Kanawa and a fly-past by the RAF.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">This didn&apos;t make it any easier to decide about the honeymoon. She wanted somewhere nice, of course, preferably hot with a beach and a long way from Sutton Coldfield; but she didn&apos;t want it to cost any more than it had to. Michael dropped hints about the south of France which she studiously ignored. Marcie suggested Thailand. Her mother came up with Hawaii, and failing that Barbados. Then Michael&apos;s mother offered them the use of their house in California, and Jane took it like a shot. They&apos;d still have to find the price of the air tickets, of course, but at least it wasn&apos;t Hawaii.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">With grim inevitability the day approached. Every morning Jane weighed herself on the bathroom scales which she&apos;d borrowed from Donna and every morning she was exactly the same weight as the day before. She was beginning to think the needle had been painted onto the dial. She asked Donna to come round and check if they were working properly; Donna promptly hopped onto them and clocked up an appallingly small figure without even undressing. This did nothing for Jane&apos;s morale. She had visions of her dress exploding half-way down the aisle.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Tom was her main source of strength during these black days. He had been a best man twice before and was blithely off-hand about the whole thing. Some of this optimism possibly stemmed from the fact that he&apos;d just got engaged himself. He listened with unflagging patience to Jane&apos;s constantly growing list of grievances. It would, he assured her, be all right on the day. He said it so often and so confidently that she almost started to believe him.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Cousins whose existence Jane could barely remember were enlisted as bridesmaids. Hotels were canvassed as potential venues for the reception. There were long and anxious conferences with caterers, with florists, with printers, with photographers, with limousine-</text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">hire firms. With a sinking heart, Jane went for the final fitting. Somehow, in defiance of the laws of physics, it appeared she would just be able to squeeze into the thing, and provided she was careful not to eat, drink or breathe while wearing it there was a reasonable chance that it might stay on and in one piece.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane and Michael rehearsed their lines with the assistance of the Anglican vicar, a bemused-looking man she&apos;d never seen in her life who might as well never have done this before. Apparently the doctrinal issues had been resolved by the very English expedient of not mentioning Michael&apos;s Catholicism. They got through the script without undue incident, except for the vicar turning over two pages at once a couple of times, but that was easily rectified. Jane told herself that people got married all the time; if they could do it, so could she. Michael was very grave and very precise in how he spoke. It occurred to her that he really was serious about this. That was a cheering thought, in its way.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">D-Day minus one arrived. Deaf to all entreaties, Marcie had organised a hen night. Tom was under strict instructions not to ply Michael with too much alcohol and to bring him safely back to the hotel. Under no circumstances was the groom to wake up naked in the guard&apos;s van of the Scottish night-mail. Tom had been told this sort of thing before, but there was a glint in Jane&apos;s eye that suggested it might be a good idea to pay attention this time.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">With a dark sense of impending catastrophe, Jane embarked at last on Marcie&apos;s idea of a proper send-off. This consisted of several drinks in a wine-bar, followed by an Italian meal accompanied by several more drinks, followed by further drinks in a pub, and finally a nightclub. Marcie had assembled a motley crew including a couple of colleagues from the office, one or two friends from Jane&apos;s college days, and a few of the more adventurous bridesmaids. Jane frankly welcomed the idea of oblivion. For some months now she had forsworn alcohol as part of her doomed campaign to lose some weight. Anything she drank tonight would therefore pass directly into her bloodstream, and by God she was ready for it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She was told afterwards that she had almost got them thrown out of the restaurant, firstly by persistent attempts to get the assembled company to join her in singing &quot;Lady Marmalade&quot; and then by singing it herself, several times. Then as they walked unsteadily from there to the pub she had apparently accosted several strangers, mostly male, and tried to interest them in various sexual favours. Marcie was uncharacteristically coy about this episode, which was a bad sign in itself. Finally, the doorman at the nightclub had refused to let her in and Marcie had taken her home in a taxi, in which she was violently sick twice. On the whole, you would have to call it a successful evening, or at any rate a thorough one.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Tom and Michael, on the other hand, had gone out for a quiet drink, just the two of them, and Tom had escorted his friend to the door of his hotel room for ten-thirty, where they shook hands very solemnly and parted for the night.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The day of the wedding dawned bright and clear: rather too bright for Jane&apos;s taste. The house was already in uproar. The dining-table was invisible under mountains of flowers. </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Bridesmaids were milling around in various states of undress. In the midst of chaos stood her mother, like Boadicea on the eve of battle, clipboard in one hand, telephone in the other, barking out her orders. Jane made herself tea. Her brother was in the kitchen, looking lost in a hired suit. When they were together you could see the family resemblance: Mike was darker and slighter than Jane, but they had the same eyes and the same diffident way of holding themselves. They greeted one another cautiously.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Nervous?&quot; he asked.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&apos;Just hung over.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;ll be fine.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I wish everyone would stop telling me that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Almost before the kettle had boiled her mother marched in. &quot;Jane. There you are at last.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s only ten to eight.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Have you had your shower yet?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Not yet.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, get a move on. The car will be here at nine. Arthur?&quot; Mercifully she left them and moved on to her next victim. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;She&apos;s been like that all morning,&quot; said her brother mournfully. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Jesus, when did she start?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Six o&apos;clock.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane shuddered and drank her tea. In the distance she could hear her mother haranguing an unfortunate florist.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The car was late, fortunately. With a good deal of help from her mother Jane was levered into the monstrous dress, and although spots floated before her eyes for a few seconds she didn&apos;t actually pass out. She staggered downstairs to where her father was waiting in a hired morning suit looking thoroughly miserable. He seemed to rally when he saw her.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You look wonderful,&quot; he said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Thanks. I wish I felt it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;ll be fine.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Sure.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Moving around in this dress was like walking underwater, and it definitely wasn&apos;t designed for confined spaces. Exactly how she managed to get all of it into the car was never clear to her, but it was done somehow, and they were off at last. Her father squeezed her hand confidingly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I think I&apos;m having second thoughts,&quot; she said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Are you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Not really.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The car lurched round a sharpish bend and breakfast threatened to reappear. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Are you all right, Jane? You look a bit green.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I told you, it&apos;s wearing white that does it. I should have had the ivory.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael sat on his hotel bed, fully tricked out in his borrowed finery, a hairbrush in his hand. Now that it was actually happening it had ceased to seem real. Tom was downstairs in the lobby looking out for the car. Good old Tom. You could always depend on him in a crisis. Not that this was supposed to be a crisis; on the contrary. Michael was perfectly clear in his own mind that this was the right thing to do. He&apos;d been told as much.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The last wedding he&apos;d been to had been Madeleine&apos;s school-friend Danielle and that flash boyfriend of hers; what was his name again? It had been a lovely day, not unlike today. Madeleine had looked wonderful in a deep blue satin dress that brought out the colour of her eyes. He could see her, bathed in the glorious multi-coloured light of a stained-glass window, smiling that lovely smile. A deep wordless longing for her ripped through him like a hook in his guts. It was so intense and unexpected that he dropped the hairbrush.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">There was a knock at the door. &quot;Overture and beginners,&quot; Tom said cheerfully.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael stood awkwardly. &quot;Do I look okay?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Tom inspected him, judiciously straightened his tie, flicked a speck of something from a lapel. &quot;You&apos;ll do.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">They walked carefully down the hotel stairs and out into the broad morning. Michael wished he could stop shaking.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">Church bells are unreasonably loud</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">, thought Jane. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">It&apos;s a wonder the noise abatement people haven&apos;t done something.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The car drew sedately to a halt. Her father got out and offered her his arm. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">Well: this is it. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">With great care she extracted herself from the car. Everything still seemed to be in more or less the right place. She couldn&apos;t breathe, but she hadn&apos;t expected to be able to. It helped a </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">lot that she wasn&apos;t wearing her glasses. This was one of the few things on which she and her mother had immediately agreed: Mrs Sharp had always thought glasses made Jane look frumpy, and Jane was keen to know as little as possible about what was going on around her. Her father was wearing his, and he would be doing the steering.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He guided her through the church door without incident. Somewhere up in front of her, or so she devoutly hoped, would be Michael and the vicar. Blurs of colour seethed on either side of her. The organist was giving it everything he had, which was quite a lot. Jane kept moving forward, taking short steps, trying to avoid any sudden movements. It was always possible, she told herself, that she might wake up and find herself safely in her bed at home. Lack of oxygen was starting to become a problem.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Suddenly there they were, up at the sharp end, and everything was terribly, appallingly quiet. A white spectral figure in front of her began to intone some sort of vaguely familiar verbiage. A sudden unreasoning knot of panic gripped her stomach. Who the hell was this man standing next to her? Did she really want to spend the rest of her life with him? Did she want his children? Or anyone&apos;s, for that matter?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">There was an expectant pause in the intoning. After what seemed like an age, Jane realised that she had been asked a question. In an unnaturally load voice she heard herself saying:</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I do.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Then someone was putting a ring on her finger, and someone else (or possibly the same someone) was kissing her, and the organist was off again as she started the long, slow journey back to the church door, sunlight and blessed air.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">17</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">When she came to think about it afterwards — for at the time it was all far too much of a blur to take in — there were several things about the reception which struck Jane as remarkable. For one thing, her brother Mike had turned up with a girlfriend for the first time in recorded history. He introduced her as Andrea from his mathematics course. She was a pale and anxious-looking girl with immensely thick glasses, which Jane uncharitably took to explain why Andrea seemed to find him attractive. Still, it was progress. Her brother had had no known liaisons with the opposite sex in all his twenty-one years and everyone had tacitly assumed it was simply never going to happen. At one time his mother had agonised over the question of whether or not he was gay, but apparently he was just neuter. But now all bets were off. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">Perhaps</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">, Jane thought fleetingly, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">there&apos;ll be another wedding and they&apos;ll go off and have mathematical children, God help us all.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She also met Tom&apos;s fiancée for the first time, and was agreeably surprised. Helen was very tall and laughed a lot. They seemed to be completely devoted to one another. Jane immediately arrived at the conclusion that she was worth three of Anna, and imparted this to Tom at the first opportunity. He agreed with enthusiasm. After that she was easily able to forgive herself for having neglected Tom so much during the build-up to the wedding. It was all the easier in that she&apos;d only started to feel guilty about this half an hour before.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The room which her mother had finally deemed suitable for the reception was a vast conservatory-like thing stuck on the side of what had once been a reasonably tasteful country house. Jane didn&apos;t like to imagine how much it might have cost. Palm-trees and potted shrubs were dotted about, and there was a grand piano in one corner although the music was actually piped. It was the kind of easily-ignorable doodling they play in lifts. White-clothed tables laden with finger food lined one side, and waiters were circulating with little trays of drinks. It all seemed inappropriately grand.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Her father, who had made a surprisingly tender and eloquent little speech, managed to catch her for a moment by the French windows in search of fresh air. He was pink in the face and his bow tie had begun to come apart, and Jane realised that he we was pleasantly but quite thoroughly drunk. She had never seen him in this state before.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Marvellous,&quot; he said. &quot;Absolutely marvellous.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What is?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Everything. Marvellous.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She smiled at him. &quot;Yes, it is, isn&apos;t it?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I love you, Jane.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I love you too, Dad.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Decent chap, young Michael.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes, he is.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Marvellous.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">This could have gone on indefinitely if her mother had not arrived at that moment and announced that it was time to cut the cake. Jane had more or less thrown in the towel by the time they got round to discussing the cake, with the result that Mrs Sharp had been free to commission what now appeared to be a scale model of the Coliseum in icing sugar. Jane looked at Michael. Michael looked at Jane. They both looked at the cake. A hush fell over the room. Several photographers waited expectantly. They took the knife awkwardly and tried to point it more or less at the middle.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;On a count of three,&quot; Jane whispered. &quot;One. Two. Three.&quot; There was an audible crunch of icing as the blade went in and then quite easily they had sliced right through and there was general applause.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Christ, they must have sharp knives in here,&quot; he said involuntarily. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Sharp by name, sharp by nature,&quot; Jane retorted cheerfully. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Not any more, Mrs Ashe.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">They hadn&apos;t discussed whether or not she was going to take his name, and suddenly Jane wasn&apos;t sure she liked the idea. She definitely wasn&apos;t sure she liked his assuming she would. However, this was not the moment to sort it out.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">But perhaps the strangest incident of the evening was Marcie&apos;s tears. Jane had known Marcie to cry on occasion, usually when Paul had left her as he periodically did and they were drowning her sorrows, but she&apos;d never had Marcie down as one of those people who cry at weddings, or funerals for that matter. Marcie was fundamentally sensible: that was one of the reasons Jane valued her. And yet the first thing Marcie did when Jane came into the reception was to throw her arms around her and burst into embarrassingly copious tears.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m sorry,&quot; she said, when she could speak again. &quot;I&apos;m so sorry, Jane love, I don&apos;t know what came over me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s all right,&quot; Jane said inadequately.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s just — I don&apos;t know — the dress and the flowers and the church and everything, it was just all so lovely. You looked such a picture.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Privately Jane preferred not to imagine what a picture she might have made in the lace marquee, but she said nothing.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m so happy for you,&quot; Marcie said, and then she started to cry again.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Thank you.&quot; Jane tried to catch Paul&apos;s eye, but he was carefully not noticing. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">Bloody men</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s so romantic,&quot; Marcie said. &quot;The whole white wedding bit. I always wanted that, you know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Did you?&quot; This was a side to Marcie she hadn&apos;t seen before.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;My parents being Chapel, they don&apos;t hold with all that, see.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;But if it&apos;s what you want...&quot; Jane stopped at this point, remembering how weak a fight she&apos;d put up for the kind of wedding she&apos;d wanted herself.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Anyway, I&apos;m really happy for you.&quot; Marcie was almost back to her usual self. &quot;Give him one for me, won&apos;t you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m not quite sure what to say to that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">A passing waiter supplied them with glasses, and they drank a private toast to one another. The moment had passed, and normal service had been resumed.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">As a party, it certainly seemed to go extremely well. Tom flirted outrageously with several of the bridesmaids, but Helen only seemed to be amused. Jane was pleased to see it: obviously Tom was in good form, and Helen knew him well enough to realise he meant nothing by it. One of Jane&apos;s cousins was sick on the patio: he was only fifteen and shouldn&apos;t have been allowed at the alcohol, but Jane was indulgent. She&apos;d done much the same thing herself at his age. Now that the potential for a major disaster had receded, her mother was rapidly mellowing and was conversing amiably with all and sundry, even her father. And he was clearly having the time of his life, which pleased Jane immensely.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Still recovering from the excesses of the previous night, Jane herself drank in moderation. Parties had never really been her kind of thing anyway. She hardly set eyes on Michael amongst the seething throng. A never-ending stream of obscure relatives exchanged meaningless pleasantries with her. From time to time she observed episodes in the attempts of one of Michael&apos;s old Cambridge friends to have his way with one of the bridesmaids whose name she couldn&apos;t remember. They seemed to turn up everywhere she went: out in the garden, in the hotel lobby, behind one of the palm trees. As the evening wore on he seemed to be making better and better headway, and eventually they disappeared from view altogether, from which she deduced a happy ending.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">At long last it was time for them to go. Their flight to LA was at some unspeakable hour in the morning and they were booked into a soulless hotel at Heathrow: in a final gesture of extravagance, they were travelling there by chauffeured Daimler. Jane was asleep before they even reached the motorway, her head on Michael&apos;s shoulder, lulled by the purring of the engine and the soft smell of the leather upholstery.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael stayed awake for the whole journey, although he was just as tired as she was. Everything seemed to have gone according to plan. He&apos;d asked her to marry him, she&apos;d agreed, and now it was done. He still wasn&apos;t entirely sure why he&apos;d done it, but he&apos;d known he had to. That ought to have been enough for him, or so he told himself, but of course it wasn&apos;t. He couldn&apos;t help thinking of the last time he&apos;d been in a church, and the nut-dry voice of Father Lautier over Madeleine&apos;s coffin. Perhaps it all made sense in the sight of God. If indeed there was a God: since his daughter died he had never been entirely sure. They drove on through the endless night, unblinking neon lights raking the sky, until he no longer knew where he was or where he was going.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">18</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">California, Jane thought, was by no means all it was cracked up to be. Certainly there was sunshine and golden beaches and the huge luxuriant Pacific, but there were also Californians and these were harder to enjoy. On the surface they were friendly enough, but the surface was all there seemed to be. Jane found herself missing Marcie and the abrasiveness of London life. It was all so bloody cheerful here.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael&apos;s stepfather Art was a case in point. Art was in advertising and relentlessly upbeat about absolutely everything. Admittedly you would need to be an optimist to have married Gabrielle. It was from her that Michael had inherited his dazzling blue eyes, and even in what Jane guessed to be somewhere in her fifties she was still extraordinarily beautiful, with the long blonde hair of a Botticelli angel and the figure to go with it. There was nothing angelic about her temperament, unfortunately. Gabrielle was used to being the centre of attention, and while this suited Jane well enough up to a point she soon began to resent having to compete for time with Michael. This was, after all, supposed to be their honeymoon.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The house was enormous and white and beautifully cool. Gabrielle fancied herself as an art collector, so almost every room contained two or three ravishing and outrageously expensive objects. To begin with Jane had found it rather showy, but soon she realised that in their world everybody lived like this. After a while she even stopped being so uncomfortable with having servants around the place.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">They had been there about a week when the subject first came up. They&apos;d been for a meal and were walking home along the beach under a glorious moon, which had not yet begun to pall. Unusually for them they were holding hands. Jane was pleasantly full and pretty content with life: she had Michael to herself for once and the vast breathing of the sea calmed and exhilarated her at the same time.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So,&quot; he said. &quot;What about it?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What about what?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You know. What we talked about.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Michael, we&apos;ve talked about lots of things one time or another.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You remember when I asked you to marry me.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Of course I do.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane tried to think back. &quot;Are you talking about babies, by any chance?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"><text:s/>&quot;I just wondered if you&apos;d thought any more about it.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Not really.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">There was silence for a bit, apart from the gentle swish of water. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I just wondered,&quot; he said again. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, there&apos;s no rush, is there?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I suppose not.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;And anyway, what would we live on? I&apos;d have to give up work, remember.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I could be a house-husband.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"><text:s/>&quot;It still wouldn&apos;t be enough.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael lapsed into a silence which might have been construed as sullen, and they walked on back to the house without exchanging another word. He did consent later to be seduced, but she felt as if he was being polite, and this worried her a little. Still, it might just be the stress of sharing a house with Gabrielle. She would insist on speaking French to him all the time. No doubt it was a treat for her, but it left Jane feeling very excluded.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The next morning Art asked Michael over breakfast if he&apos;d ever considered a career in advertising.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael said he hadn&apos;t.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;There&apos;d be some great opportunities for a guy like you. Educated, classy. They love all that Cambridge stuff over here.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Really?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh, sure. I have clients who would kill to have a Cambridge guy handle their account.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m not sure we&apos;d want to move out here, Art,&quot; Jane put in.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Why not? It&apos;s the land of opportunity.&quot; Art said this as if he not only really meant it but thought it was original.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s a long way from my family,&quot; she objected, although now she came to think of it this didn&apos;t strike her as an insuperable obstacle.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I think it&apos;s a great idea,&quot; Gabrielle said in her syrupy voice.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;We&apos;ll think about it,&quot; Michael said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">As soon as they decently could they fled the table. Jane was furious.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What business is it of theirs?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Art was only making conversation.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Your mother was sticking her bloody oar in.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m sure she just wants the best for us.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;If you ask me, she just wants you dancing attendance on her.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael shrugged. &quot;That&apos;s just the way she is.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;d noticed.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, I don&apos;t like it any more than you do. I told you we weren&apos;t close. Before the wedding I hadn&apos;t seen her for what, four, five years. Maybe it&apos;s bringing out her maternal side.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh God, you don&apos;t think she&apos;s after grand-children, do you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;She&apos;s already had one,&quot; Michael pointed out quietly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I forgot. No, I don&apos;t mean that, I just didn&apos;t make the connection. Did she know about all that?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Of course she did. We may not always have been on the best of terms, but she </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">is</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"> my mother.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;How was she about it?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He shrugged again. &quot;Off-hand, really.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane was shocked. &quot;You what?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;She never really approved of Madeleine in the first place, I don&apos;t know why. She only ever met her once. But none of my girlfriends was ever good enough for her.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Including me, by the look of it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I think she regarded the whole thing as some sort of divine judgement.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;That&apos;s a bit hard, isn&apos;t it?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Madeleine thought the same thing. It&apos;s ironic, really.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane looked him squarely in the eye. &quot;You don&apos;t think it&apos;s true, do you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t know what to think. I know the Church would take a pretty dim view of the whole thing.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I thought God was supposed to be love, or is that just the Church of England?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, my mother likes to take a black-and-white view of things.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I think that&apos;s appallingly insensitive.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;That&apos;s the way she is,&quot; he said again.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Sometimes reasonable people can be hard to get along with.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">That night Jane found herself unable to sleep. The endlessly perfect weather was getting on her nerves: she&apos;d never have thought grey skies could be so appealing. Gabrielle was getting on her nerves even more. How could any mother be so unfeeling? If, God forbid, anything like that had ever happened to her, she was quite sure her own mother wouldn&apos;t have taken that attitude. She&apos;d have made an impossible fuss, of course, but underneath it all she&apos;d have been on her side.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Gabrielle&apos;s treatment of Madeleine brought her back again to the subject of babies. Her own mother had never put any pressure on her in that direction: privately, Jane thought the idea of being a grandmother rather appalled her. Until very recently Mike had never shown any signs of reproducing, and everyone in the family seemed quite content with the situation. It was possible that her father might quite like the idea of grandchildren; he&apos;d never said anything, but then he never did. She could imagine him taking to the part very naturally.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">What worried her more was Michael&apos;s agenda. He seemed unreasonably keen on the idea. On general principles, Jane was determined not to be railroaded into anything; but beyond that it bothered her that he might be trying to replace Micheline, and she wasn&apos;t at all sure that was a good idea. For one thing he didn&apos;t seem to have coped especially well with fatherhood before. For another, their child would be theirs and not Madeleine&apos;s, and she wasn&apos;t having him relating to it as if it were. Madeleine was supposed to be history.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">And on top of all that she had to try and sort out her own attitude. She&apos;d never really thought about becoming a mother, apart from religiously taking every possible precaution to avoid it. She was still on the pill, although she&apos;d had to smuggle them into the house for fear of Gabrielle&apos;s disapproval. None of her friends had children, or any ambition to have children so far as she could tell. It simply wasn&apos;t something they ever discussed. After all, she was still young enough to wait: there was no biological hurry.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She remembered Madeleine&apos;s letters: how frightening and exhausting she&apos;d found it all. It sounded awful. You spent nine months throwing up and looking like a Sumo wrestler, then there were God knows how many hours of agony giving birth, and then you spent the next twenty-odd years cleaning and feeding and fetching and carrying and worrying yourself </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">sick. Jane couldn&apos;t imagine why anybody put themselves through it, given the choice. Poor Madeleine hadn&apos;t had the choice, of course.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Then again there was Pauline: she hadn&apos;t had the choice either, but she seemed remarkably happy with her lot all the same. Jane could remember Justine from the funeral, a solemn little child in a dark blue dress who never strayed far from her mother&apos;s side. Without much success, she tried to imagine what it might feel like to have one of those permanently attached to you. Maybe she&apos;d feel differently about it if the child was hers. After all, you were supposed to love them, weren&apos;t you? Jane couldn&apos;t remember ever having had tender feelings for any child in her entire life. She&apos;d certainly hated having a little brother trailing round after her. It was only now that he&apos;d gone off to university and found himself a girlfriend that he seemed to be showing any signs of turning into a human being. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">Christ</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">, she thought, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">imagine if I had a child and had to wait twenty-one years to form a relationship with it?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She turned over in bed to watch Michael sleeping. He didn&apos;t seem much more than a child himself, in some ways. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">Perhaps</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">, she thought hopefully</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">, there&apos;s some sign of a maternal side there, in my wanting to look after him. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">It didn&apos;t seem like very much to build on.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">A few days before they were due to fly home, Jane began to be haunted by the feeling that she had forgotten something. It started when she awoke and hung around awkwardly in the back of her mind all day. There didn&apos;t seem to be anything very threatening about it; it was just an annoyance. At first she put it down to a general feeling of inadequacy brought on by three weeks of Gabrielle&apos;s refined condescension. This was a good theory as far as it went, but it didn&apos;t make the feeling go away. At last she decided to look in her diary in case she&apos;d forgotten someone&apos;s birthday, and then she realised what it was.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Her immediate reaction was blind panic, but she quickly mastered herself. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">After all</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">, she told herself, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">I&apos;m only a day late. It&apos;s happened before — not often, true, but I&apos;m in a strange country a long way away from home, I&apos;ve been having quite a stressful time of it, no wonder if my system&apos;s on the blink. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She said nothing to Michael.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">All through the next day she was waiting for something to happen. She wasn&apos;t feeling especially pre-menstrual, but then living in the same house as Gabrielle was winding her up so much that she might as well have been, so perhaps she was and she just couldn&apos;t tell. All day she was in and out of the bathroom. Michael wanted to know if she was all right and she almost bit his head off. Even Gabrielle had started looking at her in a strange way. Jane wished the flight was today so she could get away from it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Another day came and went without so much as a spot of blood. They had all gone out for a meal to mark their last night there. Art had chosen a beautiful seafood restaurant with a magnificent view of the ocean, but Jane could appreciate neither the food, the wine, nor the view. Indeed it was Michael who made most of the conversational running. To Jane&apos;s annoyance he was asking Art about the advertising business. There wasn&apos;t much else you </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">could get Art to talk about, it was true, but she didn&apos;t like the idea that there might be something more behind it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">In all her life, Jane had never been more than two days late. This was now three, and there was not the slightest sign of anything even beginning to happen. She checked her hidden stash of pills and counted them. There were two more than there should have been. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T26">How the hell did that happen? </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She tried to think back over the days she had spent here, but her mind was frozen with fear and refused to co-operate.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What&apos;s the matter, Jane?&quot; said Michael, coming into their bedroom. &quot;You look as if you&apos;ve seen a ghost.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Her mouth was dry as dust. &quot;I think you&apos;d better sit down.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He sat on the bed and she sat beside him, feeling for his hand.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What is it?&quot; he said again, more gently this time.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I think I&apos;m pregnant.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;But I thought you were taking —&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, I must have forgotten, mustn&apos;t I?&quot; she snapped.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I see.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">There was a long silence between them. Jane wanted to cry. She could tell that he was pleased and at that moment she passionately hated him for it. Oh, it was all very well for </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T26">him</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">: he wouldn&apos;t have to go through pregnancy and childbirth and all that grisly business. She could imagine how everyone would rejoice at the news and felt absolutely, terrifyingly alone. She didn&apos;t want this child: not now, not like this. They&apos;d hardly started their life together. Why couldn&apos;t she have married a man with a low sperm count? There were all those couples who desperately wanted children and couldn&apos;t have them, and she only had to miss a day or two on the pill and wallop: welcome to the pudding club. It wasn&apos;t fair.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">It was no use: the tears came spilling hotly out. She clutched at Michael, for however deeply she resented him, he was there and she needed someone to hold onto as she had never needed anyone before. For a long time she couldn&apos;t speak and he held her and stroked her hair and waited.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t want anyone to know,&quot; she said eventually. &quot;Not until we&apos;re sure.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Of course.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I suppose you&apos;re bloody delighted.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Aren&apos;t you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No I&apos;m sodding well not.&quot; More tears were threatening. &quot;We were supposed to be planning this. We hadn&apos;t even decided if we wanted kids at all.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s not </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style22"><text:span text:style-name="T29">my</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style22"><text:span text:style-name="T23"> </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">fault,&quot; he pointed out, accurately if undiplomatically. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So whose fault is it? Are you saying I did this deliberately?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Of course not.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well then.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">That night they slept scrupulously apart. Now that she was face to face with the consequences, Jane&apos;s interest in sex had vanished like fairy gold. It had been the bait to a trap which had suddenly been sprung on her, and now her only thought was of escape. Returning to London would be a start, but only a start. Something would have to be done: she didn&apos;t know what exactly, but she couldn&apos;t go on like this. That was clear, if nothing else was.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">19</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Since her university days, Jane had never had much faith in doctors: after all, what sensible woman would entrust her physical well-being to someone who used to be a medical student? She was reluctant to take herself to her local clinic, in case she found herself being treated by someone she&apos;d last seen being pushed down the street stark naked in a shopping trolley with a traffic cone on his head. It was therefore an immense relief when she remembered Tom saying that his fiancée was a doctor. Although she didn&apos;t know Helen well, she&apos;d seemed like someone she could talk to. The moment this inspiration struck she phoned Tom to see what could be arranged.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">There was some bother about medical ethics, given that Jane was officially registered with another doctor, but somehow it was got over, doubtless through Tom&apos;s good offices although she was too upset at the time to thank him for it. They arranged for Jane to come over and see Helen privately at their flat one evening, Tom of course being diplomatically absent. She hadn&apos;t said exactly what the problem was, but she thought it likely that they would have guessed.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">With her doctor&apos;s hat on, Helen was much more serious in her manner, and reassuringly calm. She sat Jane down with a large gin and tonic and asked her what was the matter. Now that she came to tell someone else, Jane found it horribly embarrassing. Helen asked her if she&apos;d done a test, and Jane admitted she hadn&apos;t, but as she was now ten days overdue there didn&apos;t seem to be much doubt of it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You don&apos;t seem very happy about it,&quot; Helen observed neutrally.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m not. It wasn&apos;t — it was an accident.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You&apos;ve told Michael, I suppose?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes. He&apos;s the only person who knows, so far.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;How does he feel about it?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;He hasn&apos;t said, but I think he&apos;s as pleased as Punch.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I see.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Helen, I can&apos;t go through with this. I just can&apos;t. It&apos;s all too soon and we can&apos;t afford it and — and I&apos;m frightened.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;That&apos;s only natural.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I want an abortion.&quot; There: she&apos;d said it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I see,&quot; Helen said again. There was a grim silence. The room felt very cold. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Do you think that&apos;s terrible?&quot; Jane asked timidly. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s understandable.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Michael won&apos;t like it. He&apos;s a Catholic, you know. I mean he used to be. But he wants children, I know he does, he&apos;s said so. And there was all that business...&quot; She tailed off.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What business?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Hesitantly at first, not quite knowing how to explain it, Jane told Helen the whole story of Madeleine and the letters and the little girl who had died. Telling it to someone else made it all clearer somehow. She had to connect the facts together into a coherent narrative, and put like that it seemed to make a kind of sense rather than being just a headlong sequence of disasters. It didn&apos;t have much direct bearing on her own situation, but Jane took some comfort in the idea that even this might one day seem to have some kind of order and meaning to it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So let&apos;s see if I&apos;ve got this straight,&quot; Helen said. &quot;You&apos;re worried that Michael wants this child as some sort of replacement for the little girl who died, rather than for its own sake. You&apos;re also worried that because he&apos;s so keen on having a child he won&apos;t support you in having an abortion.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;That&apos;s putting it mildly.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Obviously I haven&apos;t examined you, and I don&apos;t have your notes, but I don&apos;t think there&apos;s any medical reason why you shouldn&apos;t have a termination if that&apos;s what you want. Of course your own doctor will have to check that out before you can go ahead. Legally the position is that it&apos;s your body and your decision, so there&apos;s nothing Michael could do to stop it unless he can persuade a judge to grant him an injunction. You&apos;d need to get a lawyer&apos;s opinion on that, but my guess is he wouldn&apos;t get very far if he tried that one.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Right.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;But of course you have to consider the impact on your marriage.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Tell me about it.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;And the impact on you.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;On me?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Lots of women have abortions and regret it afterwards.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Not me,&quot; Jane said grimly. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You&apos;d be surprised. I did, once.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You did?&quot; It had never really occurred to Jane that doctors were people too.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It happened when I was in my second year at medical school. Being a doctor was all I&apos;d ever wanted to do, since I was a little kid. The competition to get a place at medical school is insane, and once you&apos;re there the pressure is incredible. And I don&apos;t care what they say, it&apos;s still harder for women than it is for men. So there I was, working like a mad woman, hardly going out at all, and then I met this guy — his name was Fabrizio. Italian, over here to learn the language. Very dishy, dark hair, wonderful eyes, you know the type of thing. Anyway, he was just someone I used to see around now and again, it wasn&apos;t a relationship or anything like that, and one night we both got drunk and, well, nature took its course.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Crikey.&quot; Jane felt that some sort of comment was required.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So anyway, the next morning I was in a complete panic. I did one of those home pregnancy tests and it was positive. There was absolutely no way I was going to drop out of the course, and anyway Fabrizio would have been over the hills and far away if I&apos;d ever told him. So: I borrowed the money from a friend, booked myself into a private clinic and had a termination.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What was it like?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, it&apos;s a straightforward enough procedure if it&apos;s early in the pregnancy. In my case it took me a little while to raise the money but I was only about seven weeks gone. You&apos;re just in there overnight and you don&apos;t know much about it: you go to sleep pregnant, wake up and you&apos;re not pregnant any more. Anyway, I thought that would be the end of it, but I was wrong.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What happened?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Helen sighed. &quot;Babies. There were babies everywhere. It was incredible. Wherever I went, wherever I looked, there they were. I was even having dreams about babies. Of course I hadn&apos;t told anyone about it except the friend who&apos;d lent me the money, and she was sworn to secrecy. I was deeply ashamed and embarrassed about the whole sordid business. So when I started seeing all these babies there was no-one I could tell. I genuinely thought I was going mad after a while. It was like being haunted. My work was suffering. Eventually I went to see the student counsellor, and she sorted me out with a proper course of therapy. I was on antidepressants for a while.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Blimey.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Obviously I got myself together in the end, made it through the course and here I am. But I&apos;d never want to go through it again.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I can imagine.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;And I don&apos;t want you to go through it either, Jane.&quot; Helen sat forward in her chair. &quot;I know we don&apos;t know each other very well, but I&apos;ve heard a lot about you from Tom. He&apos;s very fond of you, you know. And in any case I wouldn&apos;t wish it on my worst enemy. I&apos;m not saying </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">you shouldn&apos;t have an abortion: it isn&apos;t for me to tell you what you should do. But I just want you to know how it affected me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;How do you feel about children now?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Same as Tom: we&apos;re going to have loads.&quot; Helen smiled broadly. &quot;I&apos;m a very lucky woman.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;But did you always want kids?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I think I probably did. Of course I wanted to be a doctor as well, but you&apos;re supposed to be able to have it all these days, aren&apos;t you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane thought glumly that she seemed to be having it all when she didn&apos;t even want half of it, but she said nothing.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;d offer you another drink,&quot; said Helen, &quot;but I don&apos;t think I should advise it in your condition.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No, well, I&apos;d better be going anyway.&quot; Jane stood up. &quot;Michael will be wondering where I&apos;ve got to.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Look, if you ever need to talk to anyone... you know where we are.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Thanks. I appreciate that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Do you want a lift back? Tom shouldn&apos;t be long.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No, I&apos;ll get the bus, I&apos;m fine.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">As she stood waiting for the bus she thought again of the story Helen had told her. If she hadn&apos;t heard it from her own lips she&apos;d never have believed it. To look at Helen, you wouldn&apos;t think she had a care in the world. Well, perhaps that meant it wouldn&apos;t be so bad as all that if she did have an abortion. After all, Helen had got over it in the end. And perhaps it wouldn&apos;t affect her that way. She certainly couldn&apos;t imagine feeling like that.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She was so absorbed in her thoughts that she almost went past her stop and made the driver slam on the brakes almost at the last minute. The resulting lurch was so violent that she hoped for an instant that it might have done the trick on its own. People were always losing babies. She&apos;d read magazine articles about it. But on second thoughts she decided she&apos;d better not count on it.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">While Jane and Helen were making their mutual confessions, Michael was sitting in a cramped wooden box talking to a man he&apos;d never met before. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;How long is it since your last confession, my son?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael had known this was coming and worked it out in advance. &quot;Seven years, three months and two days, Father.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">There followed a long recitation of sins, which he&apos;d been compiling for some time, including but not limited to lust, fornication and pride, and culminating in his recent marriage in an Anglican Church to a woman who was not in communion with Rome. There was a brief silence on the other side of the grille, and then appropriate penances were given. To Michael they seemed extraordinarily light. Surely this couldn&apos;t be it?</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Father, I wish to be formally reconciled with Mother Church.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Go in peace and sin no more,&quot; said the voice behind the grille, with perhaps a hint of impatience.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Somewhat bewildered, Michael clambered out to be replaced by a sharp-faced old woman in a plastic raincoat. He found himself a pew in the deserted Lady Chapel and began to pray, the old words coming back like long-lost friends. The statue of Our Lady looked down on him with a sad half-smile. The blue of her gown was the same blue as the sky the day they buried Madeleine. Over and again he murmured the ritual words until he could no longer tell when one prayer finished and the next began. It brought him a comfort he had forgotten, as if he could return to the days of his childhood when the world was safe, and death and separation and grief were just empty words that had no meaning and no terror for him.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">It was growing dark when he left the church and stole back like a thief to the flat where Jane would be arriving any minute. He felt that something had been set in order that had been waiting a long time. His faith was no more or less than it had been, but he had paid at last a debt that he had owed to God, to Madeleine and to their daughter. It was a good feeling.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">20</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">In the normal course of things, Jane would have confided her troubles to Marcie. However, after her behaviour at the reception she was no longer sure she trusted her judgement. The great thing about Marcie had always been that you could always rely on her to be completely unsentimental. But crying at a wedding? Next thing she&apos;d be leaning over prams making silly noises. No, Marcie was a broken reed.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Obviously her parents were not to know. Her father would worry himself sick, and as for her mother — well, it didn&apos;t bear thinking about. She&apos;d probably invade Poland. Jane felt she needed a more detached view. An idea occurred to her that was so far-fetched that for a long time she dismissed it out of hand, but it refused to go away and so eventually she gave in, thinking that it was completely insane but it couldn&apos;t hurt.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">It took her a long time to get through, because as she knew from her own experience nobody ever answers the phone in halls of residence, but after what seemed like eternity somebody finally picked up. What was even better was that he was actually in his room.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Mike? It&apos;s Jane.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh. Hi, sis. Great wedding.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Thanks.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;How was California?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Hot. Look, can I come and take you out to lunch?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What for?&quot; Her brother might be unworldly but he hadn&apos;t been born yesterday. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I want to talk to you. I want your opinion on something.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You want my opinion? Are you stuck with your maths homework or something?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Ha bloody ha. This is a free meal we&apos;re talking about. Do you want it or not?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Of course.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well then. Is Saturday okay?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Sure. Can I bring Andrea?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No. This is just the two of us.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Something up?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;ll tell you when I see you.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Okay, mystery girl.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane didn&apos;t know Cambridge at all, so they arranged that he would meet her off the train. She was a little apprehensive at visiting Michael&apos;s old university town: for some reason it seemed to make it more of a betrayal. Her brother was waiting for her on a bench outside the station entrance: much to her annoyance, he&apos;d brought Andrea, but she soon left them after a meaningless exchange of pleasantries. Mike led her to a pub.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What&apos;s the big secret, then?&quot; he asked once they&apos;d settled themselves. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane told him. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;That was quick.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t want the baby,&quot; she said, trying to sound calm and determined. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Why not?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She tried to explain. It sounded more and more confused and incoherent the more she said. She told him about Madeleine and Micheline. She told him about Helen, without mentioning any names. Finally she said simply:</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I just don&apos;t know what to do.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What does Michael say?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I haven&apos;t told him. I mean, he knows I&apos;m pregnant, but I haven&apos;t told him about, you know; I haven&apos;t said anything about an abortion. I just daren&apos;t.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I take it he&apos;d object?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I think we can safely say that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So if you did have an abortion, you&apos;d have to do it without telling him.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I suppose so.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Won&apos;t he wonder what happened? I mean, if you&apos;ve told him you&apos;re pregnant then presumably in nine months&apos; time he&apos;ll be expecting to see a baby.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;ll have to make something up.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Such as?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;God, I don&apos;t know. You&apos;re supposed to be the genius in this family. Think of something.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Mike stared morosely at his half-pint of cider. &quot;I&apos;m not sure it&apos;s ethical.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You can&apos;t go and do something like that behind Michael&apos;s back. It&apos;s his child as well.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s my body.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;But it&apos;s about more than that, surely? Isn&apos;t there a question of trust here?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What do you mean?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Look at it this way. Say we were talking about adultery.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;We&apos;re not,&quot; Jane objected.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I know, but just suppose we were. Now you could still argue that it&apos;s your body and you&apos;re entitled to do what you like with it, but that wouldn&apos;t be the issue, would it? You&apos;d have betrayed his trust in you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You know a lot about it. Here, Andrea&apos;s not married, is she?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Now in this case,&quot; Mike ploughed on, &quot;Michael trusts you at least to be honest with him about how you feel. What do you think it would do to him if you did this and he found out later?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Don&apos;t you dare breathe a word.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I think it would be the end of your marriage,&quot; Mike said firmly. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You do?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;In any relationship, the most essential thing is trust.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Have you been reading the problem pages in women&apos;s magazines again?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Look, you asked me for my opinion. There it is. Take it or leave it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">After that, Jane didn&apos;t have much appetite for lunch. Another potential avenue of escape had just been closed and she was beginning to run out of options. She remembered Madeleine&apos;s phrase about having a cancer inside her. That was exactly how it felt: an insidious and implacable disease was stealing her life away from her. More than ever she felt alone and friendless and utterly, utterly doomed.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">When she got back, Michael had a surprise for her. She found him in the spare bedroom, surrounded by large cardboard boxes, lumps of expanded polystyrene, and lengths of cable.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What on earth are you doing?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What does it look like?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;But for God&apos;s sake, Michael, you don&apos;t know the first thing about computers.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"><text:s/>&quot;Well, you can teach me.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane was perplexed. &quot;What for?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m starting a business,&quot; he announced proudly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She sat down rather suddenly on the bed. &quot;You&apos;re joking, aren&apos;t you? Please tell me you&apos;re joking.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Nothing very grand. I thought I could do some freelance translating.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, I dare say you could, but I don&apos;t see why.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;We&apos;ll be needing the money, remember?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane closed her eyes. This wasn&apos;t happening. She opened them again. It was. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Michael.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He didn&apos;t hear her. He had a cable in his hand and was peering at the back of the case trying to decide into which orifice it should be inserted. She tried again, more loudly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Michael, there&apos;s something I ought to tell you.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh, yes?&quot; She still didn&apos;t have his attention. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s about the baby.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">That did it. He dropped the cable and was beside her in an instant. &quot;What is it? Are you all right? Has something happened?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m fine.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well then?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I — I don&apos;t know. It&apos;s nothing.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It must be something.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She couldn&apos;t get the words out of her mouth. &quot;I can&apos;t.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Can&apos;t what?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I can&apos;t do it. Have it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What is it? You&apos;re not making sense, Jane. Tell me.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I can&apos;t have this baby. Not now.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Why not? What&apos;s happened?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Nothing&apos;s happened.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">His eyes were on her: she could feel them. It was as if he was looking right through her, like an X-ray, staring into her body where the alien cells of their child were growing and multiplying, single-mindedly pursuing their own grotesque agenda. It was an obscene violation.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What is it, Jane?&quot; his gentle voice was saying.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I just can&apos;t,&quot; she said, in hardly more than a whisper. &quot;I can&apos;t.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Why not?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t know. All I know is, I can&apos;t.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You do know. You must know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t,&quot; she said, with the stubbornness of a child.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Tell me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;ve told you, I don&apos;t know.&quot; With anger came the power of speech. &quot;What part of that sentence don&apos;t you understand?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t understand any of it. What&apos;s got into you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I want to have a — a — &quot; What was that word Helen had used? &quot;A termination.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She couldn&apos;t tell if he was in shock or simply hadn&apos;t understood her. Whatever happened, she knew it was important to make sure he realised what she was trying to tell him: it was too late to pull back now. So with a heroic effort she coerced her vocal chords into framing the words.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I want an abortion,&quot; she said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He was silent. The hand that rested on hers had become lifeless. For a wild moment she thought the shock might actually have killed him. Then at last he spoke. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I see.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The silence that followed these words was even more profound. If Jane had been able to speak, she would have been unable to resist the temptation to fill it with words, any words, explanations, excuses, anything, but she was mute. They both sat and stared at the pile of boxes as if it was going to tell them the answer somehow.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I can&apos;t believe it,&quot; he said. &quot;After everything. You know what this means to me. You </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style20"><text:span text:style-name="T23">know </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He&apos;d taken his hand away. The sense of abandonment was almost physical. His body was still there in the room but he had withdrawn completely, into a place where she could not follow him. She hadn&apos;t seen him like this for a long time, not since that awful morning at Odile&apos;s. Had she gone through all this only to lose him to Madeleine after all? A dreadful certainty crept over her like death. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T26">He&apos;s holding onto his pain</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">, she thought, </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T26">as if it were salvation</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">. Jane thought of the sun on the graves, on Micheline&apos;s tiny black and gold stone, on the freshly turned earth where they were burying Madeleine. She thought of Madeleine&apos;s eyes. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">It&apos;s no use: I can&apos;t compete with a saint, can I? Especially not a dead one</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">. It was hopeless: hopeless.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Silence fell between them like a final curtain.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">At that precise moment, Tom was doing the washing-up. This in itself would have surprised Michael had he known about it, but he would have been utterly astounded to learn that Tom had also cooked the dinner. He was still a beginner at the domestic arts, and he&apos;d managed to bake an immovable layer of charred black rice onto what had been one of Helen&apos;s best saucepans, but love excuses much. She was drying, handing back the occasional item which hadn&apos;t been thoroughly washed with admirable patience. They didn&apos;t often get to spend an evening together because of the hours Helen worked, and although they hadn&apos;t exactly eaten well there was an atmosphere of quiet contentment in their kitchen, small as it was.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I had another call from Jane,&quot; Helen said conversationally.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;How is she?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Worried.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Has she spoken to Michael yet?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;She&apos;s too scared.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Not surprised.&quot; Tom held up a wine-glass to the light and squinted.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Do you think she will?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Do I think she&apos;ll what?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Have the abortion.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t know. It&apos;s up to her.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;But you know her pretty well. What do you think?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Tom laid down the washing-up brush. &quot;I think she&apos;ll keep it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Why?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;For Michael&apos;s sake.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Helen frowned. &quot;I&apos;m not sure that she can.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;There&apos;s nothing wrong, is there?&quot; Tom was all concern. &quot;You never said.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No, no, there&apos;s nothing physically wrong with her, as far as I know. I just don&apos;t think she&apos;s ready for it, that&apos;s all.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So you think she should have the abortion, then?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I didn&apos;t say that,&quot; Helen said. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So what </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style22"><text:span text:style-name="T23">do </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">you think?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m not sure. I told her, you know. About Fabrizio.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Ah.&quot; Tom scratched his ear thoughtfully. &quot;What did she make of that?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You&apos;d have to ask Jane.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You&apos;re worried about her, aren&apos;t you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I just don&apos;t want her to make the wrong decision. I know what the consequences can be.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Do you </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style21"><text:span text:style-name="T23">think </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style21"><text:span text:style-name="T25">you</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style21"><text:span text:style-name="T23"> </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">made the wrong decision? With Fabrizio?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;That was different,&quot; Helen said defensively. &quot;I didn&apos;t really have a choice.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;But if you&apos;d had a choice? What would you have done?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Kept it, of course.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So that&apos;s what you think Jane should do.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s what I&apos;d do. But I&apos;m not her, am I? It isn&apos;t up to me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Then don&apos;t worry about it.&quot; Tom kissed her.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Stop it, you&apos;re getting suds all over my blouse.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Then you&apos;d better take it off, hadn&apos;t you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">And that was the end of the discussion for that evening.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"/></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">21</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The waiting-room was every bit as drab and depressing as Jane remembered waiting-rooms to be. It had unlovely pale green wallpaper, but fortunately most of it was obscured by a range of well-meaning posters about vaccinations and the perils of smoking. There was a small and rather gloomy fish-tank in one corner, and next to it a pile of disintegrating magazines which had once been glossy. Jane sat uncomfortably on a plastic chair, wishing she&apos;d brought a book to read. The receptionist had the most extraordinary hair she&apos;d ever seen: it looked as if had been injection-moulded in blue plastic. Jane wondered if her head really was that shape. Maybe she came from another planet where everyone looked like that. Or perhaps the alien reconnaissance craft had come across some old mail-order catalogues from the 1970s and they&apos;d erroneously concluded that this was the appearance of the typical Earthling. Jane had got into some quite involved speculation as to whether or not it was a carbon-based life-form before she was brought back to the present by the announcement that the doctor would see her now.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She&apos;d never been to the clinic since registering there when she first moved to London, and had no idea what to expect. Her first reaction on walking in was immense relief that Dr Brannigan was far too old to have been a contemporary of hers at university. He might have been pushed around in shopping trolleys once, but at least she&apos;d never witnessed it. Her second thought was that he was presumably Irish, therefore presumably Catholic, therefore presumably anti-abortion. As soon as she had finished this chain of reasoning, all she wanted to do was turn around and walk straight out again. But it was too late.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Do take a seat,&quot; he said, without looking up. He had a little bald patch right on the top of his head like a monk&apos;s tonsure.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Now then, Miss Sharp, what appears to be the trouble?&quot; He had kindly blue eyes and half-moon spectacles, just like Jean-Paul.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;ve got married, actually.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m afraid you&apos;d need a solicitor to cure that.&quot; He smiled professionally, pen poised above her notes. &quot;Shall I take your married name?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Ashe. With an E.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He wrote it laboriously onto the front of the brown docket. &quot;So, Mrs Ashe, what can I do for you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I think I&apos;m pregnant.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Do you, now?&quot; He seemed to look at her with a new interest. &quot;And what leads you to believe that?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She explained about the missing pills and the non-appearance of her period.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Is this your first pregnancy?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s possible, of course, that you may be mistaken.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Is it?&quot; Hope flooded her like sudden sunlight through clouds.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No doubt you&apos;re right. We&apos;ll have to do a test to be completely sure. Now then, let&apos;s take a look at you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He was brisk and thorough; no doubt he&apos;d done all this plenty of times before. His matter-of-factness was immensely reassuring. Jane had got so used to thinking of it as if it were some dreadful and incurable disease that it was a relief to think of it as something normal. He took her blood pressure and asked her if she smoked, to which she answered truthfully that she used to but had given up. He asked about her drinking habits, and she was a little less truthful, though he was probably allowing for that. He spoke briefly about a healthy diet and she nodded virtuously. On the whole, it all went extremely well.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">It was only when she was walking down the street with a specimen bottle in her handbag that she remembered what she&apos;d gone there to ask for. Well: she had another appointment next week. It would do then.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">While she was out, Michael had gone back to see the local priest: not for another confession, but simply for a pastoral chat. He felt the need of someone to confide in, and Tom wouldn&apos;t do. Since meeting Helen, he seemed to have become an altogether different person, and Michael wasn&apos;t sure he liked it. They were very happy together as far as he could see, but the old ease between himself and Tom had gone. He no longer came first. Michael didn&apos;t resent this: it was what happened when your friends started new relationships. He&apos;d seen it before, and had been guilty of it himself for that matter. But now it came to it, Tom was no longer there, and he needed someone to talk to.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Father Hammond received him in the vestry, which apparently doubled as his study. He was a stout red-faced man with untidy sandy hair and a hunted look. Michael asked if this was a convenient time and was given unconvincing reassurances that it was and offered a folding chair. The priest was sitting behind the table he used as his desk, which was covered in books and papers and Post-It notes. Michael felt guilty at adding to the poor man&apos;s troubles.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You&apos;re new to this area, are you?&quot; Father Hammond asked. For such a big man he had an incongruously high voice. &quot;I don&apos;t recall your face.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael admitted shamefacedly that he had been living there almost three years. The priest nodded sagely.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It happens often enough, my son. Better late than never is what I say.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael didn&apos;t know quite know how to open the subject. His host tried to make it easier for him.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Was there anything in particular you wanted to talk to me about?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s about my girlfriend, Father. I mean my wife.&quot; Father Hammond raised a questioning eyebrow, and Michael hastened to explain: &quot;We only got married a few weeks ago. I haven&apos;t got used to it yet. Calling her my wife, I mean.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I see.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;The thing is, Father.&quot; He stopped. He couldn&apos;t help feeling that a fat old man vowed to celibacy was not going to be much help on this subject. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes, my son?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, she&apos;s pregnant.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Thanks be to God,&quot; the priest said politely.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">This was turning out to be much harder than he&apos;d thought. &quot;She doesn&apos;t want to keep the baby.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The sacerdotal eyebrow went up again. Michael took a breath. &quot;She wants an abortion.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, the teachings of the Church are extremely clear. It is expressly forbidden for any Catholic —&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;But she isn&apos;t a Catholic.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Father Hammond sighed. &quot;If she will not accept the authority of the Church, then I fail to see how you expect me to be of help. Of course, if she had been received into the Faith prior to marriage then this situation would not have arisen. As it is...&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I understand, Father.&quot; Michael stood up, not without some slight awkwardness, for it was a small room and the chair had not been designed for someone of above-average height. &quot;Please accept my apologies for having trespassed on your time.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;If you would like to bring your wife here to have a talk, I would of course be happy to oblige. My door is always open.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Thank you.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael walked disconsolately home. It had been a stupid idea to go in the first place. What had he imagined he would gain from it? It wasn&apos;t as if he even thought of himself as a Catholic any more. He had enough sense to know that his instinctive horror at Jane&apos;s proposed course of action had nothing whatever to do with any Papal pronouncement on the subject. This wasn&apos;t an abstract point of ethics. This was about his whole life. If she went through with it then it would be the end of everything. Of Madeleine, of Micheline, of his marriage, of his angel — for it was the angel that had led him to Jane in the first place. None if it would make any sense. This death would be worse than the others, unbearable as they had been, because it would represent a deliberate betrayal.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane was still out when he got back to the flat. It seemed completely desolate, as if nobody had lived there for years. He couldn&apos;t think of a good reason for being there himself except that there was nowhere else to go. Michael lay down on the bed and shut his eyes.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Presently the phone rang. He ignored it for a while in the hope that whoever it was would go away, but they didn&apos;t. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s Tom,&quot; said a cheerful voice. &quot;How&apos;s it going?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh. You know.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Are you up to anything tonight?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Not especially.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Wondered if you&apos;d fancy a drink. Helen&apos;s on lates again.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;d better wait for Jane to come home.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Leave her a note. Come on, it&apos;s ages since you and me went down the pub.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael wasn&apos;t tempted by the prospect of jovial company, but there was something appealing about the idea of alcohol. &quot;All right. Where shall we go?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Tom suggested a small and slightly eccentric pub they hadn&apos;t been to in years. Michael wasn&apos;t even sure he could remember where it was, but he agreed anyway. At least it would get him out of the flat, even if he spent most of the evening wandering around London hopelessly lost.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">By some miracle he found the place without difficulty; by another, it was practically unchanged. Even the juke-box still had the same mix of &apos;70s disco classics and obscure Country &amp; Western numbers. He had first come here when he was a student and visiting some school-friends who were at London University. They&apos;d come here solely on the principle that it was the nearest pub to where they were staying, which is usually a sufficient recommendation for students. Michael had been fascinated by the bizarre sub-culture which </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">had been fostered by the landlord, an amazingly camp Australian called Sid. When he moved to London, he had brought Tom here; Sid was still in charge, and if anything more outrageous than ever. Some time ago Sid had gone off to the country to dry out, but he had been succeeded by his long-time deputy Marlene, whose real gender Michael had never been able to determine.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Hello, stranger,&quot; said Marlene, whose recall of faces was legendary. &quot;What&apos;ll it be?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;The usual,&quot; he said, pushing his luck.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Pint of best it is.&quot; Not a single muscle in his/her face betrayed the slightest triumph. This was all in a night&apos;s work for Marlene. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;And a whisky chaser.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;We&apos;re in a hurry tonight, aren&apos;t we, darling?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">At that moment Tom came in.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Don&apos;t look now, but your boyfriend&apos;s here,&quot; said Marlene. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What&apos;ll you have?&quot; Michael called. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Whatever you&apos;re having.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">They repaired to a corner table, to the accompaniment of Donna Summer, and exchanged polite enquiries as to the well-being of their respective partners.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I was only wondering,&quot; Tom said, &quot;because Jane came round to see Helen the other day. Professionally, if you see what I mean.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I know,&quot; Michael said. He hadn&apos;t known, actually, but he&apos;d suspected.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Ah. So you know what it was about.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I can guess.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">There was a brief pause while they separately took refuge in alcohol. &quot;Michael —&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t want to talk about it.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Fair enough.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">They drank some more. Michael was already a lot further down his pint than Tom liked.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">It took a long time and several more pubs before Tom felt he could broach the subject again. Closing time was hanging over them and Michael was trying to persuade him to stay over at the flat, where he thought there might be a bottle of something. Seeing that he had to </text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">get up and go to work the next morning, Tom was not too keen on this idea; nor did he want to miss Helen&apos;s sleepy return in the wee small hours. All the same he wanted to get Michael to talk, so he played along with the idea for a while.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I can&apos;t just turn up like this. What would Jane think?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Don&apos;t know, don&apos;t care,&quot; Michael said, with little-boy obstinacy.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Come on, you don&apos;t mean that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Don&apos;t care if I never see her again. Do you know what she&apos;s going to do?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Kill our baby, that&apos;s what.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Don&apos;t follow.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;She&apos;s pregnant, you know that, right? Well, she says she&apos;s having an abortion. Can you believe that?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Are you sure?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Course I&apos;m sure. She said so.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Why&apos;s that?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Because she&apos;s a heartless bitch, that&apos;s why. Come on, drink up. My shout.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I think you&apos;ve had enough, old son.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael became uncharacteristically truculent. &quot;Don&apos;t tell </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style22"><text:span text:style-name="T23">me </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">when I&apos;ve had enough. Drink what I like.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;All right, all right.&quot; Tom finished his drink, not without an effort. &quot;Got to be up in the morning. Think I&apos;ll call it a night.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Can&apos;t take the pace, that&apos;s your trouble. Always was.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Tom wondered if there was any chance of a taxi in this neck of the woods. He didn&apos;t like the way that this was going.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Come on, have another drink,&quot; Michael was saying.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No, really, I&apos;d better go.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Sit down. I&apos;ll get this.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;ve got to go to work tomorrow.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Bollocks to that,&quot; said Michael baldly. &quot;It&apos;s Helen, isn&apos;t it?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What do you mean?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s always the same. I&apos;ve seen it a hundred times. Bloke meets a girl and his mates go out of the window.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I thought you liked Helen,&quot; Tom said, in some bewilderment. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;That&apos;s beside the point. It&apos;s the principle.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;All right, you win. One more. But this has got to be the last one, okay?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Good man.&quot; Michael made his way unsteadily to the bar. Tom slumped heavily in his chair. He&apos;d already had enough before he started the last one. He wasn&apos;t looking forward to the morning&apos;s pain.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style22"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">agree with me, don&apos;t you?&quot; Michael was saying.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;About what?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&apos;Jane, of course.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What about Jane?&quot; Tom could feel his grasp on the conversation was slipping.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I told you, she&apos;s having an abortion. Heartless bitch.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I wouldn&apos;t say </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style22"><text:span text:style-name="T23">that.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Why not?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Tom floundered. &quot;Not Jane.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;But she </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style22"><text:span text:style-name="T23">is. </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">I know she is. She is. She said so.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Said what?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Said she was having an abortion. Killing our baby. Can you imagine that?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;That&apos;s rubbish.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What is?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s not a baby. Not yet, it isn&apos;t.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael glared. &quot;Of course it is. What is it if it isn&apos;t a baby?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s a foetus.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Same difference.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No it isn&apos;t. A baby is, well, it&apos;s a baby. What&apos;s there at the moment is just a </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style22"><text:span text:style-name="T23">potential </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">baby. Long way to go yet.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So what? If she&apos;d leave it alone it would turn into a baby. Can&apos;t see the difference.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Not necessarily. She might miscarry.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh, come off it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Lots of women do. It often happens and they don&apos;t even know about it. Helen told me.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So just because you live with Helen, suddenly you&apos;re Patrick bloody Steptoe, are you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m just saying,&quot; Tom said in his most reasonable voice, &quot;there&apos;s no guarantee at this stage.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;By that argument, if I beat your brains out with a bar-stool, I could just say: &apos;Well, Your Honour, he might have been run over by a bus.&apos;&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;But I&apos;m alive.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So&apos;s the baby. Or the foetus, if you insist.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No, but I&apos;m </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style22"><text:span text:style-name="T23">independently </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">alive. I mean, I&apos;m not physically attached to someone else.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Apart from Helen,&quot; Michael said unkindly. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You know what I mean.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Why are you taking her side? Whose friend are you, for God&apos;s sake? Hers or mine?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot; Michael, it isn&apos;t —&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Hers or mine?&quot; Michael repeated more loudly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Don&apos;t make a prat of yourself.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Hers — or — mine?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;All right then,&quot; Tom said, &quot;hers.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">They stared at one another for a long moment, eye to eye. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You absolute utter bastard,&quot; Michael said quietly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m going.&quot; Tom got to his feet, an operation which was a lot more effort than he had expected. It was frankly a relief to abandon his drink. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Then you can fuck right off.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Michael —&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Fuck off,&quot; Michael said, quite casually.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Tom never did know exactly how he got home that night; but it was a quite different world into which he awoke the next morning. The physical pain, though acute, was nothing: for he knew that an important part of his life had gone forever.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">22</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane was sure she had everything she was supposed to have. She had the little plastic bottle full of pale golden liquid; she had her little list of pertinent questions. The receptionist from Alpha Centauri waved her through, and she was back again across the desk from Dr Brannigan. There was some alchemy with the specimen bottle and the doctor nodded wisely.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, Mrs Ashe, it seems you were quite right. You are indeed pregnant.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Oh,&quot; Jane said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The wise blue eyes looked into hers. &quot;Are congratulations in order?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"><text:s/>&quot;Not really,&quot; she admitted. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Would you like to talk about that?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I want — I&apos;m not sure what I want.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Dr Brannigan waited.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I was going to ask you for an abortion,&quot; she said, all in one breath. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Is that what you want?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I think so.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Is that what your husband wants?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No,&quot; Jane said. Here at least she was on firm ground.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"><text:s/>Dr Brannigan took off his half-moon glasses, and polished them on his tie. They sat there for a while looking at one another. Jane blinked first. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m frightened.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;That&apos;s perfectly natural.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;No, you don&apos;t understand. I&apos;m worried that my husband wants this baby for the wrong reasons.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Mrs Ashe,&quot; he said. &quot;Exactly what is troubling you?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t know exactly.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Speaking as your doctor, there is absolutely no reason why you should not carry this child to term.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I see.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t, of course, presume to advise you on your marriage.&quot; He stopped, gazing archly over the top of his glasses. &quot;But you must realise that in the circumstances this is a somewhat unusual request.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I suppose I just don&apos;t feel ready for it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Nobody ever is.&quot; Dr Brannigan scratched his ear. &quot;I have two children myself, one of each. Both grown up now. If we&apos;d waited until we were ready for them, we&apos;d still be waiting. Parenthood is an impossible job, Mrs Ashe, and I can tell you from my own experience that you&apos;re as ready for it now as you&apos;re ever going to be.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Am I?&quot; Jane found this rather depressing.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He glanced down at her notes. &quot;You&apos;re twenty-six, I see. Do you know how old your mother was when you were born?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Er, twenty-four. No, twenty-three.&quot; Mental arithmetic had never been her strong point.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Would you say your mother had been a failure as a parent?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I suppose not.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I can assure you she was no more ready than you are.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"><text:s/>Jane felt she was being pushed into a corner. &quot;You can&apos;t stop me. It&apos;s my decision.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Indeed it is,&quot; he said politely.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Then there&apos;s nothing more to talk about, is there?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Terminating this pregnancy won&apos;t make it not have happened, you know.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Won&apos;t it?&quot; She thought about it. He was right, of course. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Go home and think about it. Talk to your husband. Talk to your friends, to your mother, perhaps. This isn&apos;t a decision to be taken lightly.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m not taking it lightly,&quot; she said firmly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m not suggesting that you are. But you need to be absolutely certain that you&apos;ve made the right choice, and I don&apos;t feel you have that certainty right now. There&apos;s still plenty of time.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I suppose so.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Come back in a couple of weeks, and see how you feel then.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;All right.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Ever since she&apos;d mentioned the A-word, Michael had been sleeping in the spare room amongst the debris of the still-uninstalled computer; but after her second visit to Dr Brannigan, Jane could no longer stand it. She needed someone to be close to, and she missed him desperately, however reluctant she was to admit it. And the doctor was right: she needed to talk to him.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">It wasn&apos;t easy striking up a conversation with a man who barely uttered a word and seemed unable to stay in the same room with her for more than five minutes. In the end she decided to take the bull by the horns.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You know I went to the doctor&apos;s yesterday.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I don&apos;t want to hear about it.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Well, perhaps you should.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael was already half-way to the door: it was now or never. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Michael, I’m scared,&quot; she said. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He stopped. &quot;You what?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;About the baby.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">They stood looking nervously at one another. Jane tried to read his eyes and failed dismally. She wished he&apos;d say something, anything. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Is something wrong?&quot; he said at last. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yes.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">“Was it something the doctor said? Tell me.”</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">“It’s just – Michael, I need to know. If – if I do have this baby. And I’m saying </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">if</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">. But… will it be our baby? Yours and mine? Or will it be hers?”</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He walked over to her. She just stood there feeling like an idiot. Her mouth was dry and she was a little nauseous, and for a moment she wondered if it was the onset of morning sickness or just nerves. Michael was taking her wooden hands in his.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Jane. My darling. Of course it will be ours. You’re my wife. You’re the woman I love. I meant every word I said in church, and I mean them now.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">“Really?” she said weakly.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">“Really. And I know this scares you. God knows it scares me too. The last thing I want is for history to repeat itself. You know, I lie awake at night sometimes wishing all this could go away. I wish I had your courage.”</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">This completely deprived Jane of such power as speech as she had left. He went on:</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">“I know – I don’t know how, but I just </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T25">know</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"> – that I could never live with myself if it came to an abortion. Sometimes I wish I could, but I know I couldn’t. And I’m too much of a coward to make that kind of a choice. I suppose I’ve been waiting for you to make it for me. And that’s wrong. We need to do this together, whatever we decide.”</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">“And if I decide – we decide – to keep it?”</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">“You’ll make me the happiest man in the world. And I will do everything I can do to deserve you, because you’re the best wife a man could ever have.”</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">“And if not?” Jane was dreading this question, but she knew it had to be asked.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">“Then you’ll still be the best wife a man could ever have, and I will still love you more than I have ever loved anyone, or ever could.”</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">In that moment Jane realised that these were the words she had always needed to hear. They were the more precious because she knew how hard it was for him to speak of his deepest feelings. It hadn’t all been a dreadful mistake after all. Everything was going to be all right. She came to a decision that afterwards she only occasionally came to regret.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane put her arms around her husband.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">“I’m going to have our baby,” she said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael had wanted to get a car so he could drive her to the hospital when the time came, but Jane had vetoed the idea. The stress of waiting for a cab would be nothing compared to the stress of Michael&apos;s driving, especially when he was panicking and in a hurry. She had to admit that she was more worried about him than she was about the baby. To begin with he&apos;d been so much happier and things had almost been back to the way they were: it was like the relief of rain after a long hot stuffy afternoon. But as time had gone by his concern for her and the child had grown in keeping with her waistline, until now he was so tense that he seemed even more pregnant than she was. She hoped he would cope better with the child when it finally arrived.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">In between fussing over her, he&apos;d been trying to make a go of the translating business. The work itself was easy enough for him, but dealing with the computer was another matter. Jane was forever having to help him out of various scrapes into which he&apos;d got himself. She hated the sight of the thing. However, it had now paid for itself and looked as if it might well become a viable source of income, so she bore with it. At least if he had work to do it kept him out of the way. He was worse than her mother, and that was saying a good deal.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Jane hadn&apos;t expected to enjoy being pregnant, and she didn&apos;t. Her back ached and she was very conscious of her ungainliness. People looked at her in the street. She went to ante-</text:span></text:span><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">natal classes and hated it because everyone seemed so jolly. The whole business just seemed appalling. More and more often she wondered whether she was making a terrible mistake. She would have liked to speak to Helen, but she and Tom seemed to be on Michael&apos;s banned list for some reason on which he was not forthcoming.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">By the end she could barely manage to haul herself around the flat, let alone go out. She was thoroughly fed up. It got so bad that she almost began to look forward to giving birth, simply to get it all over with. She expected the process of childbirth to be an unspeakable nightmare, but at least she&apos;d only have to go through it once, and then just possibly she might be able to wear something that didn&apos;t make her look like a blonde version of Nana Mouskouri.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The baby came, as babies often do, in the still small hours of the night. Jane was not amused. They&apos;d had a false alarm a couple of nights before, and she wasn&apos;t anxious to repeat the experience. But however fervently she wished the contractions would go away, they showed no signs of doing so. She woke Michael and told him. He sprang out of bed as if electrocuted. Her bag was ready-packed and waiting by the door. The number of their chosen taxi firm was on speed-dial; in the dress rehearsal the other night everything had gone perfectly to plan.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;There&apos;s no answer,&quot; he said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Keep trying. They&apos;re supposed to be open twenty-four hours.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael was hopping from one foot to the other. &quot;Still no answer.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;For God&apos;s sake, Michael, calm down, will you?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">For whatever reason, the taxi company resolutely refused to answer. Michael was trying to get dressed in the half-dark without letting go of the telephone, which was not an easy operation for a man who was not well-coordinated at the best of times. Jane had already put on the dress like a huge denim sack which was about the only thing she could get into these days.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;They&apos;re still not answering,&quot; he said unnecessarily.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So try somebody else.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;There isn&apos;t anyone else, not locally.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;So what am I meant to do, get the night-bus?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Michael didn&apos;t know. Jane tried to apply rational thought to the situation, seeing that he was unlikely to do so.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Who do we know who&apos;s got a car?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">They debated several possibilities, all of whom were either too far away or on holiday or had too small a car. By now Michael was getting close to the brink of complete panic and his mind was a total blank, so it was Jane who said the unsayable.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;What about Tom? He&apos;s got a company BMW and he&apos;s only down the road.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I can&apos;t ask Tom.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;All right then, I&apos;ll ask him.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She took the telephone from his unresisting fingers and dialled. A sleepy voice answered.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Yup?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;It&apos;s me,&quot; she said.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"><text:s/>&quot;Who&apos;s me?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Jane.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The voice woke up a little. &quot;Jane? What&apos;s up?&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;I&apos;m about to give birth and I need a lift.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;You what?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She said it again, slowly and clearly. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Give me ten minutes.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Make it five.&quot; </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;On my way.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">He rang off. Michael was looking at her, apparently unable to speak, his whole being one vibrating question.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;He&apos;s on his way,&quot; she said. </text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Thank God for that.&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">The drive to the hospital was not as bad as she&apos;d feared. Tom drove like the wind, but the streets were empty and he seemed to know what he was doing, so she didn&apos;t panic. She sat in the back with Michael holding her hand as if he was afraid it was about to fall off. He kept telling her it was going to be all right, as much for his own benefit as for hers. It reminded her of their wedding.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Afterwards the midwife said she&apos;d done extremely well. Privately Jane thought that if that was doing well, she hoped to God she never did badly; but the remark had been kindly meant, so she said nothing. Never in her life had she known pain or sheer exhaustion remotely like it. She&apos;d completely lost track of time: indeed she&apos;d lost track of everything except for what was happening to her body, or rather what her body was doing to her. Now that it was over she just wanted to sleep for a week.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">She was so dizzy with tiredness and the drugs that it was hard to grasp at first that the pink slippery bawling thing they put into her arms was really a baby. She looked down at him in bemusement. He was like a tiny version of Winston Churchill after a hard night. After a while he stopped bawling, which was a great improvement, although she reminded herself that it was only temporary. Michael was sitting on the edge of the bed with the widest smile she&apos;d ever seen.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Can I hold him?&quot; he asked.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">&quot;Is the Pope Catholic?&quot;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">Gingerly she passed over the tiny bundle and Michael took him in his arms. She still couldn&apos;t believe that anything so small could have caused such an enormous bulge. Looking at the two of them, father and son, she realised with something akin to shock that for the first time in years he was truly, blissfully happy. Indeed, she rather suspected that when she&apos;d had a bit of a rest she might even be happy herself. Then their son started to bawl again and she closed her eyes. Madeleine had been right: life was never going to be the same again.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">Epilogue</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Chapter_20_subheading">Normandy, 2014</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Opening_20_para">Jane’s mobile phone bleeped imperiously. It was only another fatuous text from her service provider welcoming her, for the third time, to France. It did at least provide a momentary distraction from the terror, even after all these years, of being driven by Michael; especially when it was on what she knew in her soul to be the wrong side of the road.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“I don’t know why you brought that thing,” he said. “We’re supposed to be on holiday.”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“I like to keep in touch.”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“In touch with what?”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">Jane ignored that remark. “How far is it now?”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“Twenty point something kilometres, if you believe the satnav.”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">They continued along the country road for a few more minutes in companionable silence. The late summer evening was taking a lingering and splendid farewell; the amazing bonfire of the sun left mysterious twilit pools under the oak-trees and the ancient hedgerows. It was the just the time of day, Jane thought, that road accidents happen.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“Put your lights on,” she said automatically.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">Michael <text:s/>complied, equally automatically. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“Tell me something,” he said. “Why did you want to come back here for our anniversary?”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">Jane had been avoiding this question for months, ever since she first made the suggestion. This was partly because she feared she didn’t know the answer, and partly because she feared she did.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“Honestly?”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“Honestly.”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“Because, I suppose – well, because I want to say thank you. To Madeleine.”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">Michael laughed aloud, which he was doing more often as he grew older. “You, a pilgrim?”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“If you want to put it like that.” Jane was always nettled at the suggestion that she had no spiritual side, just because she had never accepted Catholicism.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/>“Anyway, I can’t imagine why you of all people would want to thank her. I thought you hated her.”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“I used to. Maybe I’ve mellowed.”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">Michael looked at her sidelong. She wished he would keep his eyes on the road. “Are you sure this is a pilgrimage and not an exorcism?”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">This was another question Jane had asked herself. “It’s just that we never talk about her any more.”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“What is there to say that hasn’t been said already? It was a long time ago, Jane.”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“I know. And yet somehow it isn’t over.” This conviction had been growing in her for months, perhaps years now she thought about it. It had been a good marriage, according to all their friends. They had two grown children (nearly grown at any rate), both healthy, happy, and as far as Jane could tell well-adjusted; the house was nearly paid for; life had been pretty good to them. They had rows – who didn’t? It had been a rocky start, but they’d come through it all one way or another.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">But they never talked about Madeleine.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">It was true that Jane still resented her. This was not just because, as she saw it, Madeleine had brought a great deal of pain into Michael’s life at a time when he was not well-fitted to cope with it. There was also a large helping of good old-fashioned jealousy involved. Jane wasn’t proud of that, but she was too honest with herself to be able to deny it. Madeleine had been his first love, and there can only be one of those. Jane had had relationships before Michael, serious ones too, at least they had seemed so at the time: but Michael was the only man she had ever truly loved, and even though he drove her to distraction sometimes it was still the case.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">Their arrival in the town square broke into her reflections. To her surprise the place had hardly changed at all. She had subconsciously expected shopping malls and car parks and all the dreadful furniture of the modern town, but it was almost as if – and her stomach lurched at the thought – they had gone back in time. <text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23"><text:s/>The old pharmacy was still there, and the </text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style44"><text:span text:style-name="T14">pâtisserie</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">, and the post office, although it had gained a new plastic sign; the church, of course, which had seen centuries come and go; and there, in pride of place, the Café Ambrose, with its striped awning and the little wrought-iron tables with the old men playing cards. They might have been the same old men; it was hard to tell.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:span text:style-name="Font_20_Style19"><text:span text:style-name="T23">“Here we are,” Michael said, unnecessarily, parking their little hire car untidily.</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">They were expected at a little rural hotel a few kilometres beyond the town, but it had been assumed by both of them somehow without the need of a discussion that they would call in here first. Michael ordered a glass of the house red and after some misgivings – she was trying to watch her weight – Jane decided to join him.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><text:soft-page-break/>“A toast,” he said. “To us.”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“Absent friends,” Jane said. They touched glasses, and sat for a moment in silence.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“It never goes away,” he said. “Not really.”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“I know. I see it in your eyes sometimes.”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“I don’t even know what it means, to get over something like that. I can’t change the past, can I?”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">Jane nodded miserable assent.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“But do you know something? I’m happy. And I owe a hell of a lot of that to you. If the only way I could be here now, with you, was to go through all the things I went through, then it was worth it.”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“Are you saying that because it’s what you think I want to hear?”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“I’m saying it because it’s what you <text:span text:style-name="T1">need</text:span> to hear. And it’s true.”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">Jane looked into his face and saw no trace of deceit there. He was still, well, Michael – a little worn about the edges, perhaps, and certainly a lot more relaxed and, yes, happy. She felt a burden slip away from her that she had forgotten she was carrying. It was a giddy experience, and not just a glass of wine on an empty stomach.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">She heard herself speak without being conscious of speaking the words.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“You know what? I wouldn’t have it any other way.” Jane raised her glass. “To Madeleine, wherever she is. And the husband she left for me.”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">“To Madeleine,” he echoed.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">Jane searched his eyes for the beginnings of a tear, and found none.</text:p>
